sequence: Genus ( plural genera ) is a taxonomic rank used in the biological classification of living and fossil organisms as opposed to genera, or more commonly, subgenera, and more commonly species.A taxonomy is an approach to understanding the structure and function of biodiversity and how it relates to biological diversity in general. The term was used in the 17th century by naturalists to designate a classification scheme that placed organisms in a hierarchy in terms of evolutionary relationships. General relativity ( ;   ;     ; ) is a branch of general relativity and one of the most famous and well-known of all the ideas in modern physics.

The fisherman 's knot is a bend ( a knot for joining two lines ) with a symmetrical structure consisting of a straight line joining the ends of the two lines. The knot forms an "S" shape. The simplest version of a fisherman's knot is formed by drawing two lines through one another in a triangle shape, with the short line joining the top of the knot and the longer line joining the bottom. The knot forms a double fisherman's knot, or a "double fisherman's knot" when there are two lines joining one another.

Parsifal ( WWV 111 ) is an opera in three acts by Richard Wagner with the libretto by the composer himself. The opera is set in the period of the Roman Empire. It was performed in several cities in 1883 and was premiered in Vienna in 1885.Parsifal was produced for the fifth time in 1894, in which it received three times more performances than in 1892.The opera, which was written by Richard Wagner, opened in Vienna on September 29, 1881 and closed on November 7, 1881, having been originally planned for an eight-month run.

The M102 is a light, towable 105 mm howitzer used by the United States Army in the Vietnam War, the First Gulf War, and the Iraq War.Overview The M102 105 mm howitzer is used in air mobile (helicopter), attack plane, and light infantry operations. The weapon carriage is lightweight welded aluminum, mounted on a variable recoil mechanism. The weapon is manually loaded and positioned, and can be towed by a 2-ton truck or High Mobility Multipurpose Wheeled Vehicle (HMMWV), can be transported by UH-60 Black Hawk helicopters, or can be dropped by parachute with airborne units.

Isotope separation is the process of concentrating specific isotopes of a chemical element by removing other isotopes . The use of such a separation is used as an alternative to isotopic separation by ion exchange. A game of chess or other similar competitive strategy game is a game that is played by two players against the computer or other computer-controlled entities. Chess is one example of this. Other examples of competitive strategy games include Go, draughts, bridge, backgammon, and other games.Competitive strategy games are commonly played by two or more players, with the goal being to take a territory or area of the board.

This is a list of monarchs who ruled over East Francia, and the Kingdom of Germany (Regnum Teutonicum), from the division of the Frankish Empire in 843 until the collapse of the German Empire in 1918.Note on titlesThe Kingdom of Germany started out as the eastern section of the Frankish kingdom, which was split by the Treaty of Verdun in 843. The rulers of the eastern area thus called themselves rex Francorum ("king of the Franks"), rex Francorum orientalium ("king of the East Franks"), and later just rex.

A Select Library of the Nicene and Post-Nicene Fathers of the Christian Church , usually known as the Nicene and Post-Constantine Bible , was a compilation of Christian writings from the New Testament and other sources, which was edited by the Council of Nicaea in AD 325 and canonized by the Church as the official text of the Bible. It is the oldest existing Christian text. It consists of a collection of writings in two volumes from the early New Testament and also some writings from the Apostolic Age of the Church, with additional writings by early Church Fathers in between.

Wheat is a grass widely cultivated for its seed , a cereal grain which is a worldwide staple food . It can be found in various climates, from temperate to tropical regions. The name wheat is used generically for all grass species. The name wheat is an Old English term derived from the Anglo-Saxon word wille, meaning "bread" or "breadfruit". The West German state of West Berlin is the administrative and political centre of Germany and the world's most populous German state. West Germany has one of the world's largest economies and a high level of development, with the highest per capita income in Europe.

Bruce Lee (; November 27, 1940 – July 20, 1973), born Lee Jun-fan , was a Hong Kong and American martial artist, martial arts instructor, actor, director, screenwriter, producer, and philosopher. He was the founder of Jeet Kune Do, a hybrid martial arts philosophy drawing from different combat disciplines that is often credited with paving the way for modern mixed martial arts (MMA). Lee is considered by critics, media, and other martial artists to be the most influential martial artist of all time and a pop culture icon of the 20th century, who bridged the gap between East and West.

Psilocybin  is a naturally occurring psychedelic prodrug compound produced by more than 200 species of fungi. The most potent are members of the genus Psilocybe, such as P. azurescens, P. semilanceata, and P. cyanescens, but psilocybin has also been isolated from about a dozen other genera. Psilocybin is itself biologically inactive but is quickly converted by the body to psilocin, which has mind-altering effects similar, in some aspects, to those of LSD, mescaline, and DMT. In general, the effects include euphoria, visual and mental hallucinations, changes in perception, a distorted sense of time, and perceived spiritual experiences.

Poznań University of Technology , PUT ( Polish name : Politechnika Poznańska ) is a university in Poznań , Poland. The university has around 8,000 full time students and about 1,000 undergraduate and 400 graduate students. It is part of the Institute of International Relations (INR), a research-intensive university that focuses on international affairs. It is the second-oldest university of Poland. The main research programs are in economics, law, finance, public policy, and political science. Paracelsus was a physician, alchemist, and philosopher from the 13th century.

Fermat 's principle , also known as the principle of least time , is the link between ray optics and general relativity. According to this theory, there is a shortest time interval that gives the maximum distance traveled by light as it traverses a material medium. The principle also applies to the propagation of gravity waves (the gravitational force acting between two objects), and has been successfully used to measure these phenomena in the laboratory.The principle of least time can be illustrated as follows: imagine two observers in separate locations, each observing a different object.

Astrid Anna Emilia Lindgren ( ; ; 14 November 1907 – 28 January 2002 ) was a Swedish writer of children's literature from the 1940s to the early 1980s. She was the author of over thirty books, and her most important work, The Little Match Girl, has been translated into sixty-three languages, and was one of the first non-fiction books to gain widespread popularity for children, earning the nickname the "Magical Matchmaker".Early lifeBorn into a Lutheran family in Gothenburg, she attended the local public school and studied philosophy at the University of Uppsala.

Lucia di Lammermoor is a dramma tragico ( tragic opera ) in three acts by Italian composer Gaetano Donizetti . It tells the story of Prince Luciano of Montefeltro, a young man from a poor family who becomes the ruler of a large and prosperous city. The story is loosely based on the life of the Florentine poet Dante Alighieri, but the plot diverges from his account.Luciano enters the Florentine civil war early in the play. After a brief engagement, the young prince is killed at the Battle of Poitiers, during which his father is defeated and imprisoned.

Civil liberties are guarantees and freedoms that governments commit not to abridge, either by constitution, legislation, or judicial interpretation, without due process. Though the scope of the term differs between countries, civil liberties may include the freedom of conscience, freedom of press, freedom of religion, freedom of expression, freedom of assembly, the right to security and liberty, freedom of speech, the right to privacy, the right to equal treatment under the law and due process, the right to a fair trial, and the right to life.

A brain tumor occurs when abnormal cells form within the brain. There are two main types of tumors: malignant tumors and benign (non-cancerous) tumors. These can be further classified as primary tumors, which start within the brain, and secondary tumors, which most commonly have spread from tumors located outside the brain, known as brain metastasis tumors. All types of brain tumors may produce symptoms that vary depending on the size of the tumor and the part of the brain that is involved. Where symptoms exist, they may include headaches, seizures, problems with vision, vomiting and mental changes.

John Knox , born ( – 24 November 1572) was a Scottish minister, Reformed theologian, and writer who was a leader of the country's Reformation. He was the founder of the Presbyterian Church of Scotland.Born in Giffordgate, a street in Haddington, East Lothian, Knox is believed to have been educated at the University of St Andrews and worked as a notary-priest. Influenced by early church reformers such as George Wishart, he joined the movement to reform the Scottish church. He was caught up in the ecclesiastical and political events that involved the murder of Cardinal David Beaton in 1546 and the intervention of the regent Mary of Guise.

A museum ( ; plural museums or , rarely , musea ) is a building or institution that cares for cultural objects or documents. Museums include the Vatican Museum in Vatican City as well as the Louvre in Paris and the Metropolitan Museum of Art, New York.HistoryThe history of the word in the Latin is not clear but it is generally thought that it was first coined during the Roman Republic, probably around 200 B.C. This was because a number of Roman states had their own collections of ancient materials, such as Roman coins and pottery.

Cranial nerves are the nerves that emerge directly from the brain (including the brainstem), of which there are conventionally considered twelve pairs. Cranial nerves relay information between the brain and parts of the body, primarily to and from regions of the head and neck, including the special senses of vision, taste, smell, and hearing.The cranial nerves emerge from the central nervous system above the level of the first vertebrae of the vertebral column. Each cranial nerve is paired and is present on both sides. There are conventionally twelve pairs of cranial nerves, which are described with Roman numerals I–XII.

North America 's first transcontinental railroad ( known originally as the `` Pacific Railroad '' and later as the `` Central Pacific Railroad ''), the Colorado, was completed on December 17, 1863, when it linked Denver and the port town of Loveland, Colorado. It was constructed by the Central Pacific Railroad as part of its system of interurban, interurban spur lines.The first transcontinental railroad to connect the Atlantic and Pacific coast, the Colorado is the only railroad built entirely along the west coast; the Pacific was constructed entirely around the east coast.

An inverse multiplexer ( often abbreviated to inverse MUX or IMUX ) allows a data stream to be broken into multiple streams with each stream consisting of a single binary data unit (byte), a start address, an end address, and optionally a parity and CRC information. For each data block, there are at least two streams of data, with the number of streams as the size of the data unit.The inverse multiplexer is usually used to reduce the number of connections that need to be negotiated by a network layer (e.g, for high bandwidth).

Blake Edwards ( born William Blake Crump ; July 26 , 1922 – December 15 , 2010 ) was an American composer who wrote orchestral music, operas, chamber music, chamber music for film and TV, and songs. Edwards was known for his original compositional approach, and for combining elements of the classical, popular, avant-garde and electronic music styles. Celestial Mechanics, a subfield of Astronomy, is the area of physics concerned with the structure, motion, and physical laws of the celestial bodies, especially the Earth's Moon, planets, stars, and nebulae.

Squid are cephalopods in the superorder Decapodiformes with elongated bodies, large eyes, eight arms and two tentacles. Like all other cephalopods, squid have a distinct head, bilateral symmetry, and a mantle. They are mainly soft-bodied, like octopuses, but have a small internal skeleton in the form of a rod-like gladius or pen, made of chitin.Squid diverged from other cephalopods during the Jurassic and occupy a similar role to teleost fish as open water predators of similar size and behaviour. They play an important role in the open water food web.

Wind tunnels are large tubes with air blowing through them which are used to replicate the interaction between air and water. The tube itself is usually made of carbon fibre or aluminium. The tube is usually heated by a flame, which heats the surrounding air. In mathematics and computer science, the graph is a two-dimensional graph whose nodes have vertices, which are labeled vertices in the graph, and whose edges connect those nodes. The two dimensions of the graph are called the two-dimensional Cartesian space, where each vertex is labeled with a unit vector and the edges connect these vertices by unit vectors.

Celebration is a census-designated place (CDP) and a master-planned community in Osceola County, Florida, United States, located near Walt Disney World Resort and originally developed by The Walt Disney Company. The town, whose population was 7,427 at the 2010 census, is part of the Orlando–Kissimmee Metropolitan Statistical Area.After founding Celebration, Disney followed its plans to divest most of its control of the town. Several Disney business units continue to occupy the town's office buildings. Walt Disney World operates two utility companies, Smart City Telecom and Reedy Creek Energy Services, that provide services to the town.

Steven C. McConnell is an author of software engineering textbooks such as Code Complete , Rapid Development , and Software Design . He has written articles about software engineering throughout his career and received the ACM award for Distinguished Contributions to the Study of Software Engineering and the National Software Engineering Award in 1998 and 1999. McConnell is also known for his work in object-oriented programming, software design, and software testing.He has served as a member of the Board of Directors of the Society of Automotive Engineers and its predecessor, the Society for Automotive Engineers, and was named president of ASSE from 1990 to 1990.

Paweł Jasienica was the pen name of Leon Lech Beynar ( 10 November 1909 – 19 August 1970 ) , a Polish novelist who lived from 1920 to 1969. He is remembered primarily for his novels, which are of the surreal and surrealist trends. His style was influenced by Polish surrealists Piotr Wojnarowicz, Aleksander Wolski and Witold Gombrowicz and by German writer Thomas Mann.Beynar became known as a prolific author after publishing more than twenty novels. Beynar's main themes were the horror of a surrealist world in which nature is not what it seems, and the human mind's struggle to understand itself in a strange world.

Michael I ( ; 25 October 1921 – 5 December 2017 ) was the last King of Romania , reigning from 23 November 1990 to 5 December 2017. He was the father of Romania's first President Ioan Popescu-Eleopulescu. He ascended to the throne on his father's death, becoming the only king of Romania to rule through succession. He is regarded as a reformer, who led Romania away from the monarchy and toward a constitutional republic.HistoryEarly lifeIoan Popescu-Eleopulescu (; 20 July 1875 – 8 December 1948) was the son of Ioan Daco Popescu-Eleopulescu, who was King from 1782 to 1793.

Malayalam ( ; , ) is a Dravidian language spoken in the Indian state of Kerala and the union territories of Andhra Pradesh, Telangana and Tamil Nadu, and has the largest number of literate population in South Asia. It is also the fourth-largest language in India, and second in South Asia after Hindi.Kerala has a population of about seven million and is divided into 17 districts. Kannada is widely spoken throughout the state and is one of India's largest and most widely spoken languages.There are a number of other Indian languages, as well as many other regional languages.

Jobst of Moravia ( or Jošt Lucemburský ; or Jodokus von Mähren ; c. 1354 – 18 January 1411 ) was a Prussian statesman of the Habsburg dynasty. He became archduke of Bohemia in 1394, and served as prince elector of Bohemia from 1420 to 1429, before becoming duke of Bohemia on 3 March 1410. He is considered by many historians to be the most prominent of the Prussian dukes, as he played a key role in the development of the Hohenzollern dynasty (1398–1918) and of the Prussian royal house.Early years and educationLife and educationAs a young man, his family was of noble birth.

Milan Kundera ( , ; born 1 April 1929 ) is a Czech writer who went into exile in France in 1956 and subsequently wrote in French. He won the Nobel Prize in Literature in 1977 for his novels The Unbearable Lightness of Being (1977), The Unbearable Lightness of Being (1981), Zmaj (1982), One Day (1986), and Darkness Visible (1992).He was born in Prague and spent most of his childhood in Prague and then in Paris.Kundera is one of the most popular and highly regarded writers of the 20th century.

Norman Quentin Cook (born Quentin Leo Cook; 31st July 1963), also known by his stage name Fatboy Slim, is an English musician, DJ and record producer who helped to popularise the big beat genre in the 1990s. In the 1980s, Cook was the bassist for the Hull-based indie rock band the Housemartins, who achieved a UK number-one single with their a cappella cover of "Caravan of Love". After the Housemartins split, Cook formed the electronic band Beats International in Brighton, who produced the number-one single "Dub Be Good to Me".

John D. Carmack II (born August 20, 1970) is an American computer programmer and video game developer. He co-founded the video game company id Software and was the lead programmer of its 1990s games Commander Keen, Wolfenstein 3D, Doom, Quake, and their sequels. Carmack made innovations in 3D computer graphics, such as his Carmack's Reverse algorithm for shadow volumes. In 2013, he resigned from id to work full-time at Oculus VR, where he served as CTO and later Consulting CTO in 2019.BiographyEarly lifeCarmack was born in Shawnee Mission, Kansas, the son of local television news reporter Stan Carmack.

Nord (; officially ; ; , ), is a department in Hauts-de-France region, France bordering Belgium. It was created from the western halves of the historical counties of Flanders and Hainaut, and the Bishopric of Cambrai. The modern coat of arms was inherited from the County of Flanders.Nord is the country's most populous department. It also contains the metropolitan region of Lille (the main city and the prefecture of the department), the fourth-largest urban area in France after Paris, Lyon and Marseille. Within the department is located the part of France where the French Flemish dialect of Dutch has historically been spoken as a native language.

Wind tunnels are large tubes with air blowing through them which are used to replicate the interaction between air and an object flying through the air or moving along the ground. Researchers use wind tunnels to learn more about how an aircraft will fly. NASA uses wind tunnels to test scale models of aircraft and spacecraft. Some wind tunnels are large enough to contain full-size versions of vehicles. The wind tunnel moves air around an object, making it seem as if the object is flying.Most of the time, large powerful fans suck air through the tube.

The San Diego Zoo Safari Park, originally named the San Diego Wild Animal Park until 2010, is an 1,800 acre (730 ha) zoo in the San Pasqual Valley area of San Diego, California, near Escondido. It is one of the largest tourist attractions in San Diego County. The park houses a large array of wild and endangered animals including species from the continents of Africa, Asia, Europe, North and South America, and Australia. The park is in a semi-arid environment, and one of its most notable features is the Africa Tram, which explores the expansive African exhibits.

Tru64 UNIX is a discontinued 64-bit UNIX operating system for the Alpha instruction set architecture (ISA), currently owned by Hewlett-Packard (HP). Previously, Tru64 UNIX was a product of Compaq, and before that, Digital Equipment Corporation (DEC), where it was known as Digital UNIX (originally DEC OSF/1 AXP).As its original name suggests, Tru64 UNIX is based on the OSF/1 operating system. DEC's previous UNIX product was known as Ultrix and was based on BSD.It is unusual among commercial UNIX implementations, as it is built on top of the Mach kernel developed at Carnegie Mellon University.

Lewiston is a city and the county seat of Nez Perce County , Idaho , United States , in the eastern part of the Northern Idaho panhandle , near the Idaho state line . Nez Perce is a county seat for the Nez Perce Tribe. It was established as a town in 1784.The town is also known as the "Crown Jewel" of the Idaho Panhandle; it is considered the most scenic place to drive in Idaho, second only to the Grand Tetons. The city is home to the Nez Perce National Memorial and Museum, which features exhibits about the Nez Perce and the tribe.

Year 980 (CMLXXX) was a leap year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  Peace is concluded between Emperor Otto II (the Red) and King Lothair III (or Lothair IV) at Margut, ending the Franco-German war of 978–980. Lothair renounces his claim on Lower Lorraine, while Otto promises to recognize Lothair's son Louis V as the rightful heir of the West Frankish Kingdom. June 11 – Vladimir I (the Great), grand prince of Kiev, consolidates the Kievan realm from modern Ukraine to the Baltic Sea.

A monopropellant rocket ( or `` monochemical rocket '' ) is a rocket that uses a single chemical as its propellant: either a chemical propellant and oxidizer mixture, or a chemical reaction catalyst. These rockets may also use one or more oxidizing chemicals. The most common propellants are hydrogen and oxygen. These chemicals are often in the form of gaseous mixtures. Malmö, known as Malmestrande in Sweden, is a municipality in the county of Örebro in the central part of the Greater Stockholm metropolitan region of Sweden, on the southern shore of Lake Mälaren. It is the second-most populous municipality on Örebro.

An intranet is a computer network for sharing information , easier communication , collaboration tools , operational systems , and collaboration tools. The Intranet has become an integral part of almost every commercial and governmental organization, from small business to governmental organizations. The Internet was originally established as an intranet between ARPAnet and MIT, and developed out of a need to facilitate communication among the early researchers of the Internet. In mathematics, the integer is a number that can be expressed in decimal notation as a decimal fraction of a power of 10.

The National Academies of Sciences, Engineering, and Medicine (also known as NASEM or the National Academies) is the collective scientific national academy of the United States. The name is used interchangeably in two senses: (1) as an umbrella term for its three quasi-independent honorific member organizations the National Academy of Sciences (NAS), the National Academy of Engineering (NAE), and the National Academy of Medicine (NAM); and (2) as the brand for studies and reports issued by the operating arm of the three academies, the National Research Council (NRC).

Year 1164 (MCLXIV) was a leap year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  Battle of Renfrew: A Norse-Gaelic army led by Lord Somerled, ruler of the Isles, invades Scotland and is routed by the Scottish forces under the command of Walter fitz Alan and Herbert of Selkirk, bishop of Glasgow. England  January 30 – King Henry II tries to delimit spiritual and royal jurisdictions in the Constitutions of Clarendon, written in large part by his councilor Richard de Luci.

The Maunder Minimum, also known as the "prolonged sunspot minimum", was a period around 1645 to 1715 during which sunspots became exceedingly rare. During a 28-year period (1672–1699) within the minimum, observations revealed fewer than 50 sunspots. This contrasts with the typical 40,000–50,000 sunspots seen in modern times over a similar timespan.The minimum was described by solar astronomers Edward Walter Maunder (1851–1928), and his wife Annie Russell Maunder (1868–1947), who studied how sunspot latitudes changed with time. Two papers were published in Edward Maunder's name in 1890 and 1894, and he cited earlier papers written by Gustav Spörer.

A hot air balloon is a lighter-than-air aircraft consisting of a bag , called an envelope , which contains heated gas (typically nitrogen, oxygen, or hydrogen) to produce lift, with the airbag acting like an envelope to provide the gas envelope's buoyancy. Balloon-based flying machines have been known for centuries, with the earliest known examples dating back to ancient Greece, but they gained popularity only in the middle of the 20th century. An interspecies mating is an act of sexual reproduction involving more than just two species of animals.

Henry Olusegun Adeola Samuel (born 19 February 1963), known professionally as Seal, is a British singer-songwriter. He has sold over 20 million records worldwide, with hit songs "Crazy" and "Killer", the latter of which went to number one in the UK, and his most celebrated song, "Kiss from a Rose", which was released in 1994. Seal is renowned for his distinctive soulful singing voice. Seal has won multiple awards throughout his career, including three Brit Awards; he won Best British Male in 1992, as well as four Grammy Awards and an MTV Video Music Award.

Millets are a group of highly variable small-seeded grasses , widely grown around the world as cereal crops or grains. There is disagreement about the exact definition of the grass family. Many of its members are related to sorghum, but many others are unrelated to it, either because of their ancestry or because they were isolated from it. There are many different names for these grasses (e.g., species), although most of them have the same meaning, and are commonly used by farmers in the Americas, Europe, and Africa.

Yorkshire pudding is a baked pudding made from a batter of eggs , flour , and milk or water . It can be eaten hot or cold and is sometimes served with a variety of garnishes.Puddings are made with a variety of fillings such as meat, poultry, fish, vegetables, cheese, cream, honey, nuts, and fruits. A pudding is generally served warm but it is also a good cold snack.In the US, a typical Yorkshire pudding consists of 3-5 eggs (whole or split) , 1/2 to 1 cup of flour, or milk (for cream), and a cup of boiling water.

East Malaysia , also known as Sabah , Sarawak and Labuan or Malaysian Borneo , is the part of Malaysia that is situated north of the equator on the coast of the Malacca Straits in the country's southern half. It is the most populous state in Malaysia. The Brunei Darussalam ( ) is a republic within Southeast Asia in Southeast Asia, bordering Malaysia, to the west, and Thailand, Vietnam, and Indonesia, to the east. The capital is Bandar Seri Begawan in the western part, while the state capital, Bandar Ubat, is on the eastern coast.

Asperger syndrome ( AS ) , also known as Asperger 's , is a neurodevelopmental disorder characterized by significant difficulties in social and communication skills as well as poor self-awareness. The disorder is caused by an underlying genetic condition called a pervasive developmental disorder (PDD), and is usually characterized by problems with social interaction and communication. Asperger's is not the only disorder that may be diagnosed in individuals with the disorder.There are many possible causes of the disorder. People with AS may have been born with low intelligence or learning problems, have had a traumatic childhood or may have a developmental disorder themselves.

The history of Burgundy stretches back to the times when the region was inhabited in turn by Celts , Romans , Visigoths , Burgundians , Vandals , and others. The Burgundians were the first to settle Burgundy, settling the north and southwest of the region. They founded a number of cities including Béziers, Rouen, Montpellier, Château d'Yquem, Saint-Germain-des-Prés, La Bègue and Béziers, which remain major centres of the Burgundian culture. Barcelona ( , , ;  ; ;  ) is a metropolis located in the north-western part of Catalonia in Spain.

Purple is any of a variety of colors with hue between red and blue. In the RGB color model used in computer and television screens, purples are produced by mixing red and blue light. In the RYB color model historically used by painters, purples are created with a combination of red and blue pigments. In the CMYK color model used in printing, purples are made by combining magenta pigment with either cyan pigment, black pigment, or both.Purple has long been associated with royalty, originally because Tyrian purple dye, made from crushed shells, was extremely expensive in antiquity.

Kenneth Charles Williams (22 February 1926 – 15 April 1988) was an English actor. He was best known for his comedy roles and in later life as a raconteur and diarist. He was one of the main ensemble in 26 of the 31 Carry On films, and appeared in many British television programmes and radio comedies, including series with Tony Hancock and Kenneth Horne, as well as being a regular panellist on BBC Radio 4's comedy panel show Just a Minute from its second series in 1968 until his death 20 years later.Williams grew up in Central London in a working-class family; he claimed his father spoke as a cockney.

"Wilhelmus van Nassouwe", usually known just as "Wilhelmus" (; ; English translation: "The William"), is the national anthem of both the Netherlands and the Kingdom of the Netherlands. It dates back to at least 1572, making it the oldest national anthem in use today, provided that the latter is defined as consisting of both a melody and lyrics. Although "Wilhelmus" was not recognized as the official national anthem until 1932, it has always been popular with parts of the Dutch population and resurfaced on several occasions in the course of Dutch history before gaining its present status.

The Etruscan civilization  of ancient Italy covered a territory, at its greatest extent, of roughly what is now Tuscany, western Umbria, and northern Lazio, as well as what are now the Po Valley, Emilia-Romagna, south-eastern Lombardy, southern Veneto, and western Campania.The earliest evidence of a culture that is identifiably Etruscan dates from about 900BC. This is the period of the Iron Age Villanovan culture, considered to be the earliest phase of Etruscan civilization, which itself developed from the previous late Bronze Age Proto-Villanovan culture in the same region. Etruscan civilization endured until it was assimilated into Roman society.

ESP most commonly refers to : Extrasensory perception , a paranormal ability Spain ( España ) - ISO three-letter country code for Spain, the country of España; it is used only on postal, telephone, internet and land-line telephones and postal addresses; it is different from the ISO country code for the European Union. The code for the country is EUS . In the United States the code is . In the United Kingdom it is .The country code for Germany is DDE . Erythroleptidinium chloride (ERP, also ERP– or erythro- or ESR–), a crystalline, nonradioactive, salt form of erythrongoxide, is a yellow-brown powder.

Depleted uranium (DU; also referred to in the past as Q-metal, depletalloy or D-38) is uranium with a lower content of the fissile isotope  than natural uranium. Natural uranium contains about  , while the DU used by the U.S. Department of Defense contains   or less. The less radioactive and non-fissile  constitutes the main component of depleted uranium. Uses of DU take advantage of its very high density of   ( denser than lead).Civilian uses include counterweights in aircraft, radiation shielding in medical radiation therapy and industrial radiography equipment, and containers for transporting radioactive materials.

A spacecraft is a vehicle or machine designed to fly in outer space. A type of artificial satellite, spacecraft are used for a variety of purposes, including communications, Earth observation, meteorology, navigation, space colonization, planetary exploration, and transportation of humans and cargo. All spacecraft except single-stage-to-orbit vehicles cannot get into space on their own, and require a launch vehicle (carrier rocket).On a sub-orbital spaceflight, a space vehicle enters space and then returns to the surface without having gained sufficient energy or velocity to make a full orbit of the Earth.

The Barber of Seville , or The Useless Precaution is an opera buffa in two acts by Gioachino Rossini with a total running time of seventy-eight minutes, which was first produced at the Milan Opera House in 1798, the same year that Rossini was born. It is considered an operatic classic of Italian opera. The Barber of Seville was one of the most popular operas of the 18th century and is considered an important influence on operatic repertoire in the Renaissance.The opera was originally composed for tenor, and its first recording, in 1815, was made in 1818 with a cast of twelve.In 1829, the libretto and music were published.

The Buran program ( , , `` Snowstorm '' , `` Blizzard '' ) , also known as the ``Sputnik'' program, was an experimental Soviet intercontinental ballistic missile system designed by G.M. Korolev from 1969 to 1974.It was designed for a launch date in 1973. The Buick Century ( , , ) is a full-size, 4-wheel-drive Chevrolet four-door hatchback manufactured by Buick from 1961 to 1968. Buick began mass-producing the Century in 1962. The name derives from the first-generation Century.In 1962, Buick began selling a new model, the Century Coupe, as an addition to the line-up, replacing the earlier sedan.

A luge is a small one- or two-person sled on which one sleds supine ( face up ) and feet-first. The sled is suspended from a long cable with a hook attached to its nose. The sled is propelled by the pulling power of the person seated in front of the sled.Lugging the sled up the incline can be quite tiring.Lugging the cable back down can be extremely tiring, depending on the length of cable.Lugging up a hill can be dangerous as a fall from the height can injure the person who is strapped into the sled.

A monopropellant rocket (or "monochemical rocket") is a rocket that uses a single chemical as its propellant.Chemical-reaction monopropellant rocketsFor monopropellant rockets that depend on a chemical reaction, the power for the propulsive reaction and resultant thrust is provided by the chemical itself. That is, the energy needed to propel the spacecraft is contained within the chemical bonds of the chemical molecules involved in the reaction.The most commonly used monopropellant is hydrazine (N2H4), a chemical which is a strong reducing agent. The most common catalyst is granular alumina (aluminum oxide) coated with iridium.

Lanford Wilson (April 13, 1937March 24, 2011) was an American playwright. His work, as described by The New York Times, was "earthy, realist, greatly admired [and] widely performed." Wilson helped to advance the Off-Off-Broadway theater movement with his earliest plays, which were first produced at the Caffe Cino beginning in 1964. He was one of the first playwrights to move from Off-Off-Broadway to Off-Broadway, then Broadway and beyond.He received the Pulitzer Prize for Drama in 1980 and was elected in 2001 to the Theater Hall of Fame.

Albert the Magnanimous KG, elected King of the Romans as Albert II (10 August 139727 October 1439) was king of the Holy Roman Empire and a member of the House of Habsburg. By inheritance he became Albert V, Duke of Austria. Through his wife he also became King of Hungary, Croatia, Bohemia, and inherited a claim to the Duchy of Luxembourg.BiographyAlbert was born in Vienna as the son of Albert IV, Duke of Austria, and Joanna Sophia of Bavaria.He succeeded to the Duchy of Austria at the age of seven on his father's death in 1404.

In Euclidean geometry, an affine transformation, or an affinity (from the Latin, affinis, "connected with"), is a geometric transformation that preserves lines and parallelism (but not necessarily distances and angles).More generally, an affine transformation is an automorphism of an affine space (Euclidean spaces are specific affine spaces), that is, a function which maps an affine space onto itself while preserving both the dimension of any affine subspaces (meaning that it sends points to points, lines to lines, planes to planes, and so on) and the ratios of the lengths of parallel line segments.

Cotton is a soft, fluffy staple fiber that grows in a boll, or protective case, around the seeds of the cotton plants of the genus Gossypium in the mallow family Malvaceae. The fiber is almost pure cellulose, and can contain minor percentages of waxes, fats, pectins, and water. Under natural conditions, the cotton bolls will increase the dispersal of the seeds.The plant is a shrub native to tropical and subtropical regions around the world, including the Americas, Africa, Egypt and India. The greatest diversity of wild cotton species is found in Mexico, followed by Australia and Africa.

Mary Anning (21 May 1799 – 9 March 1847) was an English fossil collector, dealer, and palaeontologist who became known around the world for finds she made in Jurassic marine fossil beds in the cliffs along the English Channel at Lyme Regis in the county of Dorset in Southwest England. Anning's findings contributed to changes in scientific thinking about prehistoric life and the history of the Earth.Anning searched for fossils in the area's Blue Lias and Charmouth Mudstone cliffs, particularly during the winter months when landslides exposed new fossils that had to be collected quickly before they were lost to the sea.

Lindsey Adams Buckingham (born October 3, 1949) is an American singer, musician, songwriter, and producer, best known as the former lead guitarist and male lead singer of the music group Fleetwood Mac from 1975 to 1987 and 1997 to 2018. In addition to his tenure with Fleetwood Mac, Buckingham has released six solo albums and three live albums. As a member of Fleetwood Mac, he was inducted into the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame in 1998. Buckingham was ranked 100th in Rolling Stones 2011 list of "The 100 Greatest Guitarists of All Time".

The overhand knot, also known as a  knot and half knot, is one of the most fundamental knots, and it forms the basis of many others, including the simple noose, overhand loop, angler's loop, reef knot, fisherman's knot, Half hitch, and water knot. The overhand knot is a stopper, especially when used alone, and hence it is very secure, to the point of jamming badly. It should be used if the knot is intended to be permanent. It is often used to prevent the end of a rope from unraveling.

Hebron ( ;  ) is a Palestinian city in the southern West Bank,  south of Jerusalem. Nestled in the Judaean Mountains, it lies  above sea level. The largest city in the West Bank, and the second largest in the Palestinian territories after Gaza, it has a population of over 215,000 Palestinians (2016), and seven hundred Jewish settlers concentrated on the outskirts of the Old City of Hebron. It includes the Cave of the Patriarchs, which Judeo-Christian and Islamic traditions all designate as the burial site of three key patriarchal/matriarchal couples.

Naval Submarine Base New London is the primary United States Navy East Coast submarine base , also known as the Naval Submarine Base New London (NSBN L), the Naval Submarine Base L in New London, and the base that hosts the U.S. Navy's Fleet Activities Support Facility. The base is located in the New London-Waterford area on the Connecticut coast at latitude 31°45′ N, longitude 69°17′ W.N. It is located approximately 12.2 nautical miles (24.5 mi) from Cape Cod.The naval facility consists of two main facilities, the Naval Submarine Base New London and the Navy Operational Support Facility.

In the English language , the word nigger is an ethnic slur typically used against black people , especially African Americans, in American English. Historically, the word was first applied to the Natives of the Americas in the 16th century, as a result of centuries of slave trade and colonization. It was widely used to refer to slaves in the South as late as the 19th century and was widely accepted in the North as recently as the 1960s. Nas is an American rapper and singer born Curtis Jackson. Nas has been described as one of hip hop's most inventive and original rappers.

Arabidopsis (rockcress) is a genus in the family Brassicaceae. They are small flowering plants related to cabbage and mustard. This genus is of great interest since it contains thale cress (Arabidopsis thaliana), one of the model organisms used for studying plant biology and the first plant to have its entire genome sequenced. Changes in thale cress are easily observed, making it a very useful model.StatusCurrently, the genus Arabidopsis has nine species and a further eight subspecies recognised. This delimitation is quite recent and is based on morphological and molecular phylogenies by O'Kane and Al-Shehbaz and others.Their findings confirm the species formerly included in Arabidopsis made it polyphyletic.

Isotope separation is the process of concentrating specific isotopes of a chemical element by removing other isotopes. The use of the nuclides produced is varied. The largest variety is used in research (e.g. in chemistry where atoms of "marker" nuclide are used to figure out reaction mechanisms). By tonnage, separating natural uranium into enriched uranium and depleted uranium is the largest application. In the following text, mainly the uranium enrichment is considered. This process is crucial in the manufacture of uranium fuel for nuclear power plants, and is also required for the creation of uranium-based nuclear weapons.

The oxidation state , or oxidation number , is the hypothetical charge of an atom if all of its bonds are hydrogen bonds. This charge is defined as the negative of the number of electrons it has. A positive oxidation number implies that the atom is ionized, but an atom's oxidation state does not imply whether it can undergo chemical reactions. In biology, an endosymbiont is a living organism that contains and maintains its own genetic code, or genetic information. Examples include microorganisms, viruses, fungi, protists, and some plants.

Shakespearean tragedy is the designation given to most tragedies written by playwright William Shakespeare . Many of his history plays, which were originally known as plays in progress (TPP) or unfinished works, were written after his death, as he died less than three months after their completion.The term is usually applied to a work whose author is unknown. This is sometimes used by critics to denote works by Shakespeare, who is often considered to be the most influential of English dramatists.Shakespearean tragedies generally deal with personal and social issues in English society in his time.

A resistojet is a method of spacecraft propulsion ( electric propulsion ) that provides thrust by heating a , typically a solid propellant-based, propellant tank to a high temperature and compressing it to reduce its density. Eugenio Einaudi (; 23 June 1864 – 20 November 1924) was an Italian writer best known for his novel "The Leopard". He is often considered one of the principal figures in modern Italian literature and one of Italy's most important literary figures. He wrote in a literary style that was often characterized by an emphasis on language, in contrast to his predecessors in the avant-garde movement.

Éraic (or eric) was the Irish equivalent of the Welsh galanas and the Anglo-Saxon and Scandinavian weregild, a form of tribute paid in reparation for murder or other major crimes. The term survived into the sixteenth century as , by then relating only to compensation for the killing of an Irishman. In the case of homicide, if the attacker fled, the fine had to be paid by the tribe to which he belonged.In Irish mythology the eraic takes an important place. In the Oidheadh Chloinne Tuireann, the children of Tuirreann owe an eraic to Lugh.

Los Alamos National Laboratory ( often shortened as Los Alamos and LANL ) is a United States Department of Energy national laboratory, located in Los Alamos, New Mexico. The Laboratory was established in 1945 with the initial intent of creating nuclear weapons. It is the world's most productive nuclear weapons facility with over 40 nuclear weapons tests conducted, the third-highest number in history, after the USA, Russia, and the United Kingdom. In the course of its work, it is one of the few nuclear weapons production facilities outside of the United States.

Pope Leo VII ( ; died 13 July 939 ) was the bishop of Rome and nominal ruler of the Roman Catholic Church until his resignation on 10 May 968. He also became pope after Gregory XII's death in 1314.He was elected pope on 10 April 968 on the second day of his pontificate, as the sole successor of Gregory XII, but he was soon deposed, and Gregory's successor was Leo VI, who became pope on 10 October 968.BiographyBorn in Venice in 907, Leo was raised in the house of a wealthy courtier. His parents were probably Italian, probably of noble family.

Rice is the seed of the grass species Oryza sativa ( Asian rice ) or less commonly Oryza glaberrima (wheatgrass), a species of flowering plant native to Asia. The grain is commonly referred to as brown rice but is commonly also referred to as white rice due to the different color of the hull. It can also be referred to as paddy rice or wild rice.Brown rice is often used in Indian and Southeast Asian cuisine, and is often seen as a staple food in many Asian countries.There is also a small amount of white rice in North and South America, as well as in Australia and many other countries.

Eugène Adrien Roland Georges Garros (; 6 October 1888 – 5 October 1918) was a French pioneering aviator and fighter pilot during World War I and early days of aviation. In 1928, the Roland Garros tennis stadium was named in his memory; the French Open tennis tournament takes the name of Roland Garros from the stadium in which it is held.Biography Eugène Adrien Roland Georges Garros was born in Saint-Denis, Réunion, and studied at the Lycée Janson de Sailly and HEC Paris.At the age of 12, he contracted pneumonia, and was sent to Cannes to recuperate.

Josiah Willard Gibbs ( ; February 11 , 1839 – April 28 , 1903 ) was an American scientist who is widely recognized as the founder of the field of synthetic organic chemistry. He is considered the pioneer of modern chemical synthesis and is credited with pioneering the development of a number of synthetic organic processes, notably the synthesis of the chlorofluorocarbon (CFC), the chlorine atom, and the halogen, respectively.Biographical details of Gibbs are not well known; in his later years he suffered from a progressive neuromuscular disease and, at his death, was in failing health.

The red slender loris (Loris tardigradus) is a small, nocturnal strepsirrhine primate native to the rainforests of Sri Lanka. This is No. 6 of the 10 focal species and No. 22 of the 100 EDGE mammal species worldwide considered the most evolutionarily distinct and globally endangered. Two subspecies have been identified, L. t. tardigradus and L. t. nycticeboides.Taxonomy Genus Loris Red slender loris, Loris tardigradus Horton Plains slender loris or mountain loris, Loris tardigradus nycticeboides Dry zone slender loris or lowland loris, Loris tardigradus tardigradus Gray slender loris, Loris lydekkerianusThe ears are less prominent in Loris tardigradus tardigradus compared to Loris lydekkerianus.

Saxony-Anhalt ( ; ) is a state of Germany, bordering the states of Brandenburg, Saxony, Thuringia and Lower Saxony. It covers an area of and has a population of 2.19 million inhabitants, making it the 8th-largest state in Germany by area and the 11th-largest by population. Its capital is Magdeburg and its largest city is Halle (Saale).The state of Saxony-Anhalt was formed in July 1945 after World War II, when the Soviet army administration in Allied-occupied Germany formed it from the former Prussian Province of Saxony and the Free State of Anhalt.

Halebidu (IAST: Haḷēbīḍ, literally "old capital, city, encampment" or "ruined city") is a town located in Hassan District, Karnataka, India. Historically known as Dorasamudra or Dwarasamudra, Halebidu became the regal capital of the Hoysala Empire in the 11th century CE. In the modern era literature it is sometimes referred to as Halebeedu or Halebid as the phonetic equivalent, a local name after it was damaged and deserted after being ransacked and looted twice by the forces of the Delhi Sultanate in the 14th century.Halebidu is home to some of the best examples of Hindu and Jain temples with Hoysala architecture.

A tremor is an involuntary, somewhat rhythmic, muscle contraction and relaxation involving oscillations or twitching movements of one or more body parts. It is the most common of all involuntary movements and can affect the hands, arms, eyes, face, head, vocal folds, trunk, and legs. Most tremors occur in the hands. In some people, a tremor is a symptom of another neurological disorder. A very common tremor is the teeth chattering, usually induced by cold temperatures or by fear.TypesTremor is most commonly classified by clinical features and cause or origin.

Mosquitoes are members of a group of almost 3,600 species of small flies within the family Culicidae ( from the Latin word Cicade meaning "to walk"). They are found throughout the world, except Antarctica and the arctic regions. They range in size from about 10-15 mm to 25-40 mm, with males having larger bodies and longer tails. Females have wings, but they are only rarely seen, as they prefer to sleep on land.The Latin name for the species is Aedes aegypti, which means "the servant of the gods".

Nuclear engineering is the branch of engineering concerned with the application of breaking down  atomic nuclei (fission) or of combining atomic nuclei (fusion),  or with the application of other sub-atomic processes based on the principles of nuclear physics. In the sub-field of nuclear fission, it particularly includes the design, interaction, and maintenance of systems and components like reactors, power plants, or weaponry. The field also includes the study of medical and other applications of radiation, particularly Ionizing radiation, nuclear safety, heat/thermodynamics transport, nuclear fuel, or other related technology (e.g., radioactive waste disposal) and the problems of nuclear proliferation.

Year 1068 ( MLXVIII ) was a leap year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on the last Wednesday of January, the third Tuesday in March, or the first Wednesday in August. It had 28 days and was the twenty-third and last consecutive leap year. It was the first to have twenty-eight consecutive months of 29 days or less.The name "La Grange" was derived from "Gerrard," the place of its founding, in the parish of La Grange, County Kerry, Ireland, and its inhabitants are known as the Irish.

Till Death Us Do Part is a British television sitcom that aired on BBC1 from 1965 to 1975. The show was first broadcast as a Comedy Playhouse pilot, then in seven series until 1975. In 1981, ITV continued the sitcom for six episodes, calling it Till Death.... The BBC produced a sequel from 1985 until 1992, In Sickness and in Health.Created by Johnny Speight, Till Death Us Do Part centred on the East End Garnett family, led by patriarch Alf Garnett (Warren Mitchell), a reactionary white working-class man who holds racist and anti-socialist views.

In combinatorics and in experimental design, a Latin square is an n × n array filled with n different symbols, each occurring exactly once in each row and exactly once in each column. An example of a 3×3 Latin square isThe name "Latin square" was inspired by mathematical papers by Leonhard Euler (1707–1783), who used Latin characters as symbols, but any set of symbols can be used: in the above example, the alphabetic sequence A, B, C can be replaced by the integer sequence 1, 2, 3.

Pietro Mascagni (7 December 1863 – 2 August 1945) was an Italian composer primarily known for his operas. His 1890 masterpiece Cavalleria rusticana caused one of the greatest sensations in opera history and single-handedly ushered in the Verismo movement in Italian dramatic music. While it was often held that Mascagni, like Ruggiero Leoncavallo, was a "one-opera man" who could never repeat his first success, L'amico Fritz and Iris have remained in the repertoire in Europe (especially Italy) since their premieres.Mascagni wrote fifteen operas, an operetta, several orchestral and vocal works, and also songs and piano music.

A spacecraft is a vehicle or machine designed to fly in outer space . A type of artificial satellite , spacecraft are operated under the supervision of a human being.The design of any space vehicle is constrained by a series of operational requirements that are defined by its purpose and its mission, such as what it does, where it needs to go, and how it should perform. In computer science, software engineering, or software development, is a method for the creation of software that allows its use in an organization or industry. When done well, this can be a very efficient way to develop software.

Scooby-Doo is an American animated franchise comprising many animated television series produced from 1969 to the present, as well as their derivative media. Writers Joe Ruby and Ken Spears created the original series, Scooby-Doo, Where Are You!, for Hanna-Barbera Productions in 1969. This Saturday-morning cartoon series featured teenagers Fred Jones, Daphne Blake, Velma Dinkley, and Shaggy Rogers, and their talking Great Dane named Scooby-Doo, who solve mysteries involving supposedly supernatural creatures through a series of antics and missteps.Scooby-Doo was originally broadcast on CBS from 1969 to 1976, when it moved to ABC.

A gold standard is a monetary system in which the standard economic unit of account is based on a fixed weight or fineness. Hinduism is the third-largest monotheistic religion in the world, with a number of branches of Hinduism around the world. Founded by the god Vishnu as a religious sect in ancient India, Hinduism evolved as a syncretic religious movement that emphasized the unity of all religions in a single world. Hinduism traces its origins to the eponymous Upanishad, a hymn to Vishnu, attributed to his son, Lord Shiva. Hinduism was the religion that the Puranas were written in.

Year 1045 ( MXLV ) was a common year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) and used for the Gregorian Calendar . This year was a leap year with a total solar eclipse of December 22, 1047 and an  astronomical conjunction with the sun and Venus on December 25, 1046. The Julian calendar is more commonly called the Gregorian calendar because the  New Testament was written before the Calendar Act was signed in 1582, and had no reference to the Julian year.HistoryDuring the Roman Empire the year 1045 was a common year, and the Julian calendar used in Italy was the year 1045 BC.

A funeral home , funeral parlor or mortuary , is a business that provides burial and funeral services for the living. They usually provide a service for both adults and children and charge for it as a full-fledged business. The term may be applied to a business, institution, or industry whose primary purpose is the sale of goods to the public, usually for the purchase or rental of a home.A funeral home is a type of funeral parlor , and a common business is a funeral home in a funeral establishment, which provides services for the living in a cemetary or mortuary.

The Magic Flute ( German : , ) , K. 620 , is an opera in two acts by Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart, originally composed for two soloists and one chorus. It was premiered at the Vienna Philharmonie on 29 December 1785, the first opera by Mozart. In 1787, Mozart completed the first of three operas to be based on the opera.The second opera, Cosi fan Tutte (1787;   or , ), was composed as a counterpoint to The Magic Flute in 1788.In 1790 Mozart's opera Don Giovanni was premiered in Vienna, and then at Königsberg the same year.

A musician is a person who composes, conducts, or performs music. According to the United States Employment Service, "musician" is a general term used to designate one who follows music as a profession. Musicians include songwriters who compose music as well as write lyrics for songs, conductors who direct a musical performance, or performers who perform for an audience. A music performer is generally either a singer who provides vocals or an instrumentalist who plays a musical instrument. Musicians may perform on their own or as part of a group, band or orchestra.

Year 884 ( DCCCLXXXIV ) was a leap year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) in the ninth month of the Julian or Gregorian calendar and lasting until Sunday, November 30. It was the eighth leap year of the Julian or Gregorian calendar, in line with the rule of three hundred and thirty-five days. Leap years are counted in the month they fall and are not counted in the month of the preceding leap year. In mathematics, a binomial theorem is a theorem about the coefficients in a binomial coefficient expansion.

In the philosophy of mathematics , the abstraction of actual infinity involves the acceptance ( if the axiom of infinity is true ) that any countable set is infinite. Gnosticism (; from  gnōstra , "knowledge") is a non-Christian form of spirituality, philosophy and religion in which the world is regarded as a spiritual creation of the divine being. In Gnosticism the divine nature is said to possess only an impersonal form, but is in fact part of, or a manifestation or emanation from the world, or both. It may be contrasted with the later "Christian gnosticism" and "New Age gnosticism".

Rubber, also called India rubber, latex, Amazonian rubber, caucho, or caoutchouc, as initially produced, consists of polymers of the organic compound isoprene, with minor impurities of other organic compounds. Thailand, Malaysia and Indonesia are three of the leading rubber producers. Types of polyisoprene that are used as natural rubbers are classified as elastomers.Currently, rubber is harvested mainly in the form of the latex from the rubber tree (Hevea brasiliensis) or others. The latex is a sticky, milky and white colloid drawn off by making incisions in the bark and collecting the fluid in vessels in a process called "tapping".

Radiohead are  an English rock band formed in Abingdon, Oxfordshire, in 1985. The band consists of Thom Yorke (vocals, guitar, piano, keyboards), brothers Jonny Greenwood (lead guitar, keyboards, other instruments) and Colin Greenwood (bass), Ed O'Brien (guitar, backing vocals) and Philip Selway (drums, percussion). They have worked with producer Nigel Godrich and cover artist Stanley Donwood since 1994. Radiohead's experimental approach is credited with advancing the sound of alternative rock.After signing to EMI in 1991, Radiohead released their debut single, "Creep", in 1992.

Sir Robert Alexander Watson Watt  (13 April 1892 – 5 December 1973) was a British pioneer of radio direction finding and radar technology.Watt began his career in radio physics with a job at the Met Office, where he began looking for accurate ways to track thunderstorms using the radio signals given off by lightning. This led to the 1920s development of a system later known as high-frequency direction finding (HFDF or "huff-duff"). Although well publicized at the time, the system's enormous military potential was not developed until the late 1930s.

Pioneer 10 (originally designated Pioneer F) is an American space probe, launched in 1972 and weighing , that completed the first mission to the planet Jupiter. Thereafter, Pioneer 10 became the first of five artificial objects to achieve the escape velocity needed to leave the Solar System. This space exploration project was conducted by the NASA Ames Research Center in California. The space probe was manufactured by TRW Inc.Pioneer 10 was assembled around a hexagonal bus with a  diameter parabolic dish high-gain antenna, and the spacecraft was spin stabilized around the axis of the antenna.

Shawn Fanning (born November 22, 1980) is an American computer programmer, entrepreneur, and angel investor. He developed Napster, one of the first popular peer-to-peer ("P2P") file sharing platforms, in 1999. The popularity of Napster was widespread and Fanning was featured on the cover of Time magazine.The site in its initial free P2P incarnation was shut down in 2001 after the company's unsuccessful appeal of court orders arising from its encouraging the illegal sharing of copyrighted material. A paid subscription version of the site followed, and was purchased by Rhapsody on December 1, 2011.

The IAI RQ-5 Hunter unmanned aerial vehicle ( UAV ) was originally intended to serve as the United States Army Air Force's (USAF) main aerial intelligence, surveillance, reconnaissance (ISR) aircraft during the Cold War. Developed from the US Navy U-2, it saw limited service as early as 1962 but was eventually cancelled in the 1970s after only six operational aircraft were built. The Intercontinental Ballistic Missile ( ICBM ) is a type of intercontinental ballistic missile (ICBM) intended for use against a target at any point in the United States.

Year 876 (DCCCLXXVI) was a leap year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  At the invitation of Benevento, the newly-restored Byzantine fleet appears in the waters off Otranto. On the orders of Emperor Basil I, the Byzantines sail up the Adriatic Sea and reconquer part of southern Italy. The city of Bari is occupied in the name of the Byzantine Empire. Instead of holding it for his 'ally' Adelchis of Benevento, Basil makes it the capital of the new Byzantine Theme of Longobardia.

Heavy Metal : F.A.K.K . 2 is a third-person shooter video game made by Ritual Entertainment in 2000 . The game is set in an alternative future in which the human species has developed nuclear energy as a means of powering their colonies, and humanity is at the brink of destruction. The game's storyline takes place during the year 2142, with the player fighting various enemies who are attempting to destroy humanity.The game received positive reviews, winning several awards including the "Game of the Year" award from GamePro and the "Best Game" award from Electronic Gaming Monthly.

Dresden ( , ; Upper Saxon : Dräsdn ; ) is the capital city of the German state of Saxony and the most populous city in northern Germany. It is located on the River Elbe in the northern part of the Ruhr region of Germany. It is the third-most populous city in Germany and the second-most populous city outside the former East Germany. In 2012, it had a population of 1,849,542, making it the seventh most populous city in Germany. Dreyfus syndrome is a disorder characterized by chronic and recurrent seizures. The cause is unknown. It is a heterogeneous disorder of brain development.

In academic publishing, a scientific journal is a periodical publication intended to further the progress of science, usually by reporting new research.ContentArticles in scientific journals are mostly written by active scientists such as students, researchers and professors instead of professional journalists. There are thousands of scientific journals in publication, and many more have been published at various points in the past (see list of scientific journals). Most journals are highly specialized, although some of the oldest journals such as Nature publish articles and scientific papers across a wide range of scientific fields.

A funeral home, funeral parlor or mortuary, is a business that provides burial and funeral services for the dead and their families. These services may include a prepared wake and funeral, and the provision of a chapel for the funeral.ServicesFuneral homes arrange services in accordance with the wishes of surviving friends and family, whether immediate next of kin or an executor so named in a legal will. The funeral home often takes care of the necessary paperwork, permits, and other details, such as making arrangements with the cemetery, and providing obituaries to the news media.

Turbo Pascal is a software development system that includes a compiler and an integrated development environment (IDE) for the Pascal programming language running on CP/M, CP/M-86, and DOS. It was originally developed by Anders Hejlsberg at Borland, and was notable for its extremely fast compiling times. Turbo Pascal, and the later but similar Turbo C, made Borland a leader in PC-based development.For versions 6 and 7 (last), both a lower-priced Turbo Pascal and more expensive Borland Pascal were produced; Borland Pascal was more oriented toward professional software development, with more libraries and standard library source code.

Toilet humour , or potty or scatological humour ( compare scatology ) , is a type of off-colour humour dealing with bodily functions, such as toilet use, urination, defecation, defecation, excretion of faeces or vomit, urine, bowel movements and the sexual activity of a male or female individual. It is generally regarded as vulgar humour.The word came to English from French in the late 16th and early 17th centuries. The first printed examples date to 1701, and the first publication of a print comic (a satire) by a British author in English was in 1727.

In mathematics and physics, Laplace's equation is a second-order partial differential equation named after Pierre-Simon Laplace, who first studied its properties. This is often written as or where  is the Laplace operator,  is the divergence operator (also symbolized "div"),  is the gradient operator (also symbolized "grad"),  and  is a twice-differentiable real-valued function. The Laplace operator therefore maps a scalar function to another scalar function.If the right-hand side is specified as a given function, , we haveThis is called Poisson's equation, a generalization of Laplace's equation.

David is a masterpiece of Renaissance sculpture, created in marble between 1501 and 1504 by the Italian artist Michelangelo. David is a  marble statue of the Biblical figure David, a favoured subject in the art of Florence.David was originally commissioned as one of a series of statues of prophets to be positioned along the roofline of the east end of Florence Cathedral, but was instead placed in a public square, outside the Palazzo Vecchio, the seat of civic government in Florence, in the Piazza della Signoria, where it was unveiled on 8 September 1504.

Bikram Yoga is a system of hot yoga, a type of yoga as exercise, devised by Bikram Choudhury and based on the teachings of B. C. Ghosh, that became popular in the early 1970s. Classes consist of a fixed sequence of 26 postures, practised in a room heated to  with a humidity of 40%, intended to replicate the climate of India. The room is fitted with carpets and the walls are covered in mirrors. The instructor may adjust the students' yoga postures. Choudhury's teaching style was abrasive.

In academic publishing , a scientific journal is a periodical publication intended to further the progress of science , usually written in a peer-reviewed format. It provides the official record of published scientific work, as well as providing readers with an opportunity to review the work and submit comments. As the name suggests, the journals are peer-reviewed by a group of peers (editors). They generally have an open access policy and do not charge for access and readership. There are several different categories of scientific journals. For a list of peer-reviewed journals that focus on particular areas or disciplines, see Scientific Journals by Subject.

Gerard Adams (; born 6 October 1948) is an Irish republican politician who was the president of Sinn Féin between 13 November 1983 and 10 February 2018, and served as a Teachta Dála (TD) for Louth from 2011 to 2020. From 1983 to 1992 and from 1997 to 2011, he followed the policy of abstentionism as a Member of Parliament (MP) of the British Parliament for the Belfast West constituency.In 1984, Adams was seriously wounded in an assassination attempt by several gunmen from the Ulster Defence Association (UDA), including John Gregg.

Gossypium  is a genus of flowering plants in the tribe Gossypieae of the mallow family, Malvaceae, from which cotton is harvested. It is native to tropical and subtropical regions of the Old and New Worlds. There are about 50 Gossypium species, making it the largest genus in the tribe Gossypieae, and new species continue to be discovered. The name of the genus is derived from the Arabic word goz, which refers to a soft substance. Cotton is the primary natural fibre used by modern humans, amounting to about 80% of world natural fibre production.

Sir Robert Alexander Watson Watt ( 13 April 1892 – 5 December 1973 ) was a British pioneer of radio and television, who pioneered the idea of transmitting sound images over radio waves.Early yearsHe was born in New Zealand and was the youngest of twelve children. His family moved to Oxfordshire, England, in 1891, settling in a house built for the Watt family by the Rev. John Smith. Henry David Thoreau (May 20, 1817 – September 17, 1862) was an American novelist, philosopher, and writer known as the "father of modern environmentalism."

Gregory of Nyssa , also known as Gregory Nyssen ( ; c. 335 – c. 395 ) , was bishop and patriarch of the Eastern Orthodox Church for more than 70 years. He played a prominent role during the schism in Eastern Christianity that led to the establishment of the Holy See of Rome in the early modern period.Born into an aristocratic family, Gregory was named after his father Gregory the Illuminator. He attended a monastery in Rome and studied Greek under St. Polycarp of Thessalonica, where he was initiated into monastic life, studying the writings of St. Gregory Palamas on monastic spirituality.

Belarusians , also known formerly as Byelorussians (from the Byelorussian SSR), Belarussians or Belorusians, are an East Slavic ethnic group native to modern-day Belarus and the immediate region. Over 9.5 million people proclaim Belarusian ethnicity worldwide. Nearly 8 million of Belarusians reside in Belarus, with the United States and Russia being home to more than half a million Belarusians each.LocationBelarusians are an East Slavic ethnic group, who constitute the majority of Belarus' population. Belarusian minority populations live in countries neighboring Belarus: Ukraine, Poland (especially in the Podlaskie Voivodeship), the Russian Federation and Lithuania.

The 8 inch ( 203 mm ) M110 self-propelled howitzer is an American-made self-propelled artillery system consisting of an M115A1 howitzer and M2 Bradley chassis, a 155mm M2 Howitzer gun mounted on the front, and a towed M109 self-propelled anti-tank gun mounted on the back.The M110 was developed between 1945 and 1948 at the Aberdeen Proving Ground (APG) at Aberdeen Proving Ground, Maryland, and was designated the M1A1 for the first version. Aeroplanes and aerostats are unmanned aerial vehicles or unmanned aerial vehicles used for aerial surveying, aerial mapping, environmental monitoring and military operations.

This list of Anuran families shows all extant families of Anura . Anura is an order of animals in the order Primateia, with the Anura being the largest, and the Anura suborder is the second largest. The genus Anura contains over 600 known species, of which more than 400 are found only in the family. The Anura has a range in temperate and tropical climates from Africa to Mexico, and is one of only two suborders that have no freshwater or marine representatives.The suborder Anura contains about 150 species. The Anura includes all members of the family Anura that do not belong to the order Artiodactyla.

Frame Relay is a standardized wide area network ( WAN ) technology that specifies the physical and data link layers, such as the radio link or the Internet Protocol (IP) layer, between different types of networks, including fixed, switched and hybrid networks. It was first described as a standard in 1993 by the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) in RFC 2553. WAN uses the Internet Protocol and its extensions. Wendell Willkie, Jr. (October 10, 1919 – March 18, 1986) was a political activist and former U.S. vice president who served two terms from 1953 to 1961 and again from 1961 to 1964.

Keep the Aspidistra Flying, first published in 1936, is a socially critical novel by George Orwell. It is set in 1930s London. The main theme is Gordon Comstock's romantic ambition to defy worship of the money-god and status, and the dismal life that results.BackgroundOrwell wrote the book in 1934 and 1935, when he was living at various locations near Hampstead in London, and drew on his experiences in these and the preceding few years. At the beginning of 1928 he lived in lodgings in Portobello Road from where he started his tramping expeditions, sleeping rough and roaming the poorer parts of London.

The United Nations Foundation is a charitable organization headquartered in Washington, DC, that supports the United Nations and its activities. It was established in 1998 with a $1 billion gift to the United Nations by philanthropist Ted Turner, who believed the UN was crucial for addressing the world's problems. Originally primarily a grantmaker, the UN Foundation has evolved into a strategic partner to the UN, mobilizing support to advance the Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs), and help the UN address issues such as climate change, global health, gender equality, human rights, data and technology, peace, and humanitarian responses.

The MGM-31A Pershing was the missile used in the Pershing 1 and Pershing 1a field artillery missile systems. It was a solid-fueled two-stage ballistic missile designed and built by Martin Marietta to replace the PGM-11 Redstone missile as the primary nuclear-capable theater-level weapon of the United States Army and replaced the MGM-1 Matador cruise missiles operated by the German Air Force. Pershing later replaced the European-based MGM-13 Mace cruise missiles deployed by the United States Air Force and the German Air Force. Development began in 1958, with the first test missile fired in 1960, the Pershing 1 system deployed in 1963 and the improved Pershing 1a deployed in 1969.

Wheat is a grass widely cultivated for its seed, a cereal grain which is a worldwide staple food. The many species of wheat together make up the genus Triticum; the most widely grown is common wheat (T. aestivum). The archaeological record suggests that wheat was first cultivated in the regions of the Fertile Crescent around 9600 BCE. Botanically, the wheat kernel is a type of fruit called a caryopsis.Wheat is grown on more land area than any other food crop (, 2014). World trade in wheat is greater than for all other crops combined.

Domenico Cimarosa ( ; 17 December 1749 – 11 January 1801 ) was an Italian composer of the Neapolitan school. Cimarosa is one of the great Neapolitan composers, his music being a major influence on the development of Italian music from the 19th century on. He is recognized as a key composer of Neapolitan music and an important exponent of the  style.BiographyCimarosa was born into a poor Tuscan family and began his professional career in Naples in 1763. He was trained at Naples University, where he earned the degree in music theory with a special interest in harmony.

The MGM-31A Pershing was the missile used in the Pershing 1 and Pershing 1a field artillery missile systems . It is also known in the Soviet Union as the T-64A/B, or the T-62M/P and T-72/P.The Pershing 1A was used as part of the Pershing missile system. The Pershing was designed in the late 1950s, and entered service in 1958 with the Soviet Army during the Cold War. In 1962 it was replaced by the much more successful Soviet-designed T-62 tank destroyer.The Pershing 1B is the missile of the Soviet-made KAB-500/500 series of long-range air-to-surface cruise missiles.

The Porsche 914 or VW-Porsche 914 is a mid-engined sports car designed , manufactured and marketed collaboratively by Volkswagen and Porsche in the late 1970s. It was the first all-wheel drive Porsche to reach production. It is a rear-wheel drive car powered by a 2.8-liter V8 engine and developed by Volkswagen and Porsche.It was the last car designed jointly by the two companies before the formation of Volkswagen Group in 1986. The Panamax (also known as Pannamax) is a full-size luxury sedan produced by Toyota from 1981 to 1985 and then by Fiat from 1986 to 2005.

Near Earth Asteroid Rendezvous – Shoemaker ( NEAR Shoemaker ) , renamed after its 1996 launch in honor of planetary scientist Clyde Shoemaker, will rendezvous with asteroid 1999 JU3. This mission will be managed by NASA and is the first rendezvous mission between a planetary body and an asteroid. The spacecraft will carry a set of three solar arrays to power its solar panels to generate power during long periods of night. Aerial surveillance (or aerial surveillance, also sometimes called aerial survey) is a form of observation using aircraft. This is a very general description of many different aircraft-specific techniques.

Year 1107 (MCVII) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Scotland January 8 – King Edgar (the Valiant) dies at Edinburgh Castle after a 9-year reign. He is succeeded by his brother Alexander I (the Fierce), who is married to Sybilla of Normandy (an illegitimate daughter of King Henry I). A split of unity, between Alexander and his younger brother David I, makes David co-ruler in Lothian and Strathclyde (Southern Scotland). He does not receive the title of king, but of "Prince of the Cumbrians".
