Edward Teller (; January 15, 1908 – September 9, 2003) was a Hungarian-American theoretical physicist who is known colloquially as "the father of the hydrogen bomb" (see the Teller–Ulam design), although he did not care for the title, considering it to be in poor taste. Throughout his life, Teller was known both for his scientific ability and for his difficult interpersonal relations and volatile personality.Born in Hungary in 1908, Teller emigrated to the United States in the 1930s, one of the many so-called "Martians", a group of prominent Hungarian scientist émigrés.

Willow Rosenberg is a fictional character created for the fantasy television series Buffy the Vampire Slayer (1997–2003). She was developed by Joss Whedon and portrayed throughout the TV series by Alyson Hannigan.Willow plays an integral role within the inner circle of friends—called the Scooby Gang—who support Buffy Summers (Sarah Michelle Gellar), a teenager gifted with superhuman powers to defeat vampires, demons, and other evil in the fictional town of Sunnydale. The series begins as Buffy, Willow, and their friend Xander (Nicholas Brendon) are in 10th grade and Willow is a shy, nerdy girl with little confidence.

Felix Edmundovich Dzerzhinsky ( ; ;  – 20 July 1926), nicknamed "Iron Felix", was a Bolshevik revolutionary and official. Born into Polish nobility, from 1917 until his death in 1926 Dzerzhinsky led the first two Soviet state-security organizations, the Cheka and the OGPU, establishing a secret police for the post-revolutionary Soviet regime. He was one of the architects of the Red Terror and decossackization.Early life Felix Dzerzhinsky was born on 11 September 1877 to ethnically Polish parents of noble descent, at the Dzerzhinovo family estate, about  from the small town of Ivyanets in the Minsk Governorate of the Russian Empire (now Belarus).

Aden ( ,  ;   Yemeni: ) is a city, and since 2015, the temporary capital of Yemen, near the eastern approach to the Red Sea (the Gulf of Aden), some  east of the strait Bab-el-Mandeb. Its population is approximately 800,000 people. Aden's natural harbour lies in the crater of a dormant volcano, which now forms a peninsula joined to the mainland by a low isthmus. This harbour, Front Bay, was first used by the ancient Kingdom of Awsan between the 7th to 5th centuries BC. The modern harbour is on the other side of the peninsula.

La traviata ( ; The Fallen Woman ) is an opera in three acts by Giuseppe Verdi set to an Italian melody composed by the American composer-composer Charles F. Handy. It premiered on 23 March 1884. The libretto by Handy is one of several works that Verdi wrote as a part of his ongoing project of composing and conducting works of operatic proportions. It is regarded by many critics as the finest opera ever performed in the world, and is still performed in its original version by the Royal Opera House in London and the New York Metropolitan Opera.

Clothing (also known as clothes, apparel, and attire) are items worn on the body. Typically, clothing is made of fabrics or textiles, but over time it has included garments made from animal skin and other thin sheets of materials and natural products found in the environment, put together. The wearing of clothing is mostly restricted to human beings and is a feature of all human societies. The amount and type of clothing worn depends on gender, body type, social factors, and geographic considerations. Garments cover the body, footwear covers the feet, gloves cover the hands, while hats and headgear cover the head.

A shaped charge is an explosive charge shaped to focus the effect of the explosive 's energy . Different types of charge can be separated into the three categories listed below. The British Army is the largest land force service in the UK and the world's fourth largest land force. It is the second oldest continuously serving regular armed force in the world after the US Army, and has been in service since the late 16th century. The Army consists of approximately 4 million personnel, of which approximately 2 million are Regular Force.

Script Creation Utility for Maniac Mansion ( SCUMM ) is a video game engine developed at Lucasfilm Games , later acquired by Sierra On-Line, Inc. , in 1992, and made available as a free software application. It uses Direct3D 8 and Direct3D 10 for rendering, as well as DirectWrite for 3D text. It can generate high-definition games for a wide range of systems, including PCs, consoles, handheld devices and game consoles, and it can generate high-resolution images from 3D models. SCUMM is often considered the first "3D game engine" and the first of a new genre.SCUMM was written by Mark C. Seifert, and John Carmack.

Year 881 (DCCCLXXXI) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  February 12 – King Charles the Fat, the third son of the late Louis the German, is crowned as Holy Roman Emperor by Pope John VIII at Rome. August 3 – Battle of Saucourt-en-Vimeu: The West Frankish kings Louis III, and his brother Carloman II, rout Viking raiders (near Abbeville). Britain  Battle of the Conwy: King Anarawd of Gwynedd (Wales) initiates a revenge attack on the Mercian armies, and defeats them on the River Conwy.

In philosophy, systems theory, science, and art, emergence occurs when an entity is observed to have properties its parts do not have on their own, properties or behaviors which emerge only when the parts interact in a wider whole.Emergence plays a central role in theories of integrative levels and of complex systems. For instance, the phenomenon of life as studied in biology is an emergent property of chemistry, and many psychological phenomena are known to emerge from underlying neurobiological processes.In philosophy, theories that emphasize emergent properties have been called emergentism.In philosophyPhilosophers often understand emergence as a claim about the etiology of a system's properties.

Crocodiles (family Crocodylidae) or true crocodiles are large semiaquatic reptiles that live throughout the tropics in Africa, Asia, the Americas and Australia. The term crocodile is sometimes used even more loosely to include all extant members of the order Crocodilia, which includes the alligators and caimans (family Alligatoridae), the gharial and false gharial (family Gavialidae) among other extinct taxa.Although they appear similar, crocodiles, alligators and the gharial belong to separate biological families. The gharial, with its narrow snout, is easier to distinguish, while morphological differences are more difficult to spot in crocodiles and alligators.

Pali is a Middle Indo-Aryan liturgical language native to the Indian subcontinent . It is widely studied because it is the official language of both India and Bangladesh, as well as being used by over 3.4 million persons in these countries. Prakrit, the official script of Bangladesh, is based on the Sanskrit script, which was the national script for the country.The Prakrit alphabet was developed in India by Aryabhatta and it was subsequently standardized by Chandragupta. The script is written from right to left in writing. It has more than 400 consonants.

Medina, officially Al Madinah Al Munawwarah  and also commonly simplified as Madīnah or Madinah , is the second-holiest city in Islam and the capital of the Medina Province of Saudi Arabia. , the estimated population of the city is 1,488,782, making it the fourth-most populous city in the country. Located at the core of the Medina Province in the western reaches of the country, the city is distributed over , of which  constitutes the city's urban area, while the rest is occupied by the Hejaz Mountains, empty valleys, agricultural spaces and older dormant volcanoes.Medina is generally considered to be the "cradle of Islamic culture and civilization".

Salmon is the common name for several species of ray-finned fish in the family Salmonidae . Other fish in the family have similar names.History and descriptionFish of the genus Salmon are native to the rivers and lakes of Western North America and are found as far south as the Canadian Arctic and as far north as the Yukon Territory. Salmon can be found from New York to the Arctic Ocean in the United States, and north to the Pacific Ocean.Salmon are the largest fish on earth, and one of only three vertebrates (alongside whales) that cannot move their fins.

The Bell OH-58 Kiowa is a family of single-engine, single-rotor, military helicopters used for observation, utility, and direct fire support. Bell Helicopter manufactured the OH-58 for the United States Army based on its Model 206A JetRanger helicopter. The OH-58 was in continuous U.S. Army service from 1969 to 2017, when it was replaced in these roles by the Boeing AH-64 Apache and Eurocopter UH-72 Lakota.The latest model, the OH-58D Kiowa Warrior, is primarily operated in an armed reconnaissance role in support of ground troops. The OH-58 has been exported to Austria, Canada, Croatia, the Dominican Republic, Taiwan, Saudi Arabia, and Greece.

A hot air balloon is a lighter-than-air aircraft consisting of a bag, called an envelope, which contains heated air. Suspended beneath is a gondola or wicker basket (in some long-distance or high-altitude balloons, a capsule), which carries passengers and a source of heat, in most cases an open flame caused by burning liquid propane. The heated air inside the envelope makes it buoyant, since it has a lower density than the colder air outside the envelope. As with all aircraft, hot air balloons cannot fly beyond the atmosphere.

Toilet humour, or potty or scatological humour (compare scatology), is a type of off-colour humour dealing with defecation, constipation, urination and flatulence, and to a lesser extent vomiting and other bodily functions. It sees substantial crossover with sexual humour, such as dick jokes.Toilet humour is commonly an interest of children and young teenagers, for whom cultural taboos related to acknowledgement of waste excretion still have a degree of novelty. The humour comes from the rejection of such taboos, and is a part of modern culture.MusicToilet humour is sometimes found in song and rhyme, particularly schoolboy songs.

Larry Simon Gelbart ( February 25 , 1928 – September 11 , 2009 ) was an American television writer , producer and comedian. He started writing for the television series The Dick Van Dyke Show (1971–1973) and hosted it for 10 years. Gravitation is a force in the universe that acts between objects of mass. It is sometimes called the gravitational pull. Gravitational forces are described by Albert Einstein's special relativity and are a consequence of the Newtonian gravitation law, which says that the gravitational force between two masses can be expressed as a product of their masses.

Hugh John Lofting ( 14 January 1886 – 26 September 1947 ) was an English author trained as a civil servant in the Department of War and Navy. His most notable works include the best-known of which is The Island of Doctor Moreau, and he was awarded the Royal Society of Literature's Silver Medal in 1952.Lofting is often considered the forebear of the modern detective novel.Early life and schoolingLofting was born on 1 January 1886 in Stourbridge, a small English town in the North of England. His father was a schoolteacher, and from a young age he was educated at home.

The pancreas is an organ of the digestive system and endocrine system of vertebrates . In humans , it is a small endocrine organ located in the right upper arm and is the second most important organ of metabolism after the kidney. It is the body's largest organ, after the liver, and is the fourth most common organ in human bodies. A pareidolia is a hallucination that occurs when objects such as plants or objects in a scene are perceived as being moving when in reality no such movement occurs. An example of a physical pareidolia is the perceived movement of butterflies when they fly in a field.

Budapest (, ; ) is the capital and most populous city of Hungary. It is the ninth-largest city in the European Union by population within city limits; the city has an estimated population of 1,752,286 over a land area of about . Budapest, which is both a city and county, forms the centre of the Budapest metropolitan area, which has an area of  and a population of 3,303,786, comprising 33% of the population of Hungary.The history of Budapest began when an early Celtic settlement transformed into the Roman town of Aquincum, the capital of Lower Pannonia.

A jubilee is a particular anniversary of an event , usually denoting the 25th , 40th , 50th , 60th or 100th year after the day the event occurred. Jamaica  is a country in the Western Hemisphere  of the Western Hemisphere , on the Atlantic Ocean. It lies on the northeastern coast of the Caribbean Sea , about   south  of Puerto Rico . Its capital is Kingston  and has a population of about 4.7 million people. Jamaica is known as the birthplace of jazz music and popular music. Jamaica was the first British colony to ratify the United Nations Universal Declaration of Human Rights in 1948.

Lingerie (, , ) is a category of primarily women's clothing including undergarments (mainly brassieres), sleepwear, and lightweight robes. The choice of the word is often motivated by an intention to imply that the garments are alluring, fashionable, or both. In a 2015 US survey, 75% of women and 26% of men reported having worn sexy lingerie in their lifetime.Lingerie is made of lightweight, stretchy, smooth, sheer or decorative fabrics such as silk, satin, Lycra, charmeuse, chiffon, or (especially and traditionally) lace.

Magma is the molten or semi-molten natural material from which all igneous rocks are formed . Magma is found beneath the Earth's crust, and the term magma refers to both the fluid portion within a volcano and the solid magma that remains after it has cooled sufficiently to become liquid. Man is an ancient and complex biological organism. He evolved over time from simpler forms of life. Man evolved in the geological past and is a product of biological evolution. The modern human lineage is composed of humans. Human beings are a hominid group of primates who share a single species with chimpanzees.

In linguistics, an adjective (abbreviated ) is a word that modifies a noun or noun phrase or describes its referent. Its semantic role is to change information given by the noun.Traditionally, adjectives were considered one of the main parts of speech of the English language, although historically they were classed together with nouns. Nowadays, certain words that usually had been classified as adjectives, including the, this, my, etc., typically are classed separately, as determiners.Some examples: That's an interesting idea. (attributive) That idea is interesting. (predicative)  The good, the bad, and the ugly.

The covalent radius, rcov, is a measure of the size of an atom that forms part of one covalent bond. It is usually measured either in picometres (pm) or angstroms (Å), with 1 Å = 100 pm.In principle, the sum of the two covalent radii should equal the covalent bond length between two atoms, R(AB) = r(A) + r(B). Moreover, different radii can be introduced for single, double and triple bonds (r1, r2 and r3 below), in a purely operational sense.

Hilbert 's paradox of the Grand Hotel ( colloquial : Infinite Hotel Paradox or Hilbert 's Hotel ) is a problem of arithmetic geometry in which every nonnegative integer greater than 1 is either zero or nonzero. Its solution is the Grand Hotel Hotel , and it is known to all members of the mathematics community as " Hilbert's Hotel problem", and the most famous application of the paradox is undoubtedly the Hotelier's paradox: "I am not a hotelier". The paradox can be stated as follows:Let be a positive nonzero integer. Let .

Columbia Business School ( CBS ) is the business school of Columbia University in the City of New York in New York City, U.S.A.Established in 1898 as Columbia University's School of Business Administration, it is the oldest undergraduate business college in the United States and the third oldest of its kind in the world. Claudio Abbate (; 27 August 1694 – 1 November 1791) was an Italian physician, zoologist and author. Abbate was a major figure in early human embryology and the study of insects, and was one of the founders of modern taxonomy.

Gregory Benford ( born January 30 , 1941 ) is an American science fiction author and astrophysicist who is Professor of Astrophysics at the Center for Astrophysics and Space Sciences, and the co-founder of the American Institute for Scientific Research. He is best known for his works of speculative fiction and has been awarded the Hugo Award in five different categories.BiographyEarly life and education Benford was born in Seattle, Washington and grew up in San Jose, California. Baldur's Gate  is a role-playing video game developed by Obsidian Entertainment, and published by Interplay Entertainment.

Year 1030 ( MXXX ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) and concluding on Sunday, July 1. In common usage the calendar year starts on Wednesday 1 January, and ends on Sunday 31 January. The years in the Julian and Gregorian calendars are based on Julian year 0. In computing, byte is an unsigned binary integer. The byte value of a number is its number of bits, which is a multiple of 8 (2^8), a multiple of 16 (2^16) or a multiple of 256.

A verb  is a word (part of speech) that in syntax conveys an action (bring, read, walk, run, learn), an occurrence (happen, become), or a state of being (be, exist, stand). In the usual description of English, the basic form, with or without the particle to, is the infinitive. In many languages, verbs are inflected (modified in form) to encode tense, aspect, mood, and voice. A verb may also agree with the person, gender or number of some of its arguments, such as its subject, or object.

The History of East Asia generally encompasses the histories of China, Japan, Korea, and Mongolia from prehistoric times to the present. East Asia is not a uniform term and each of its countries has a different national history, but scholars maintain that the region is also characterized by a distinct pattern of historical development. This is evident in the interrelationship among East Asian countries, which not only involve the sum total of historical patterns but also a specific set of patterns that has affected all or most of East Asia in successive layers.

In commutative algebra, the prime spectrum (or simply the spectrum) of a ring R is the set of all prime ideals of R, and is usually denoted by ; in algebraic geometry it is simultaneously a topological space equipped with the sheaf of rings .Zariski topology For any ideal I of R, define  to be the set of prime ideals containing I. We can put a topology on  by defining the collection of closed sets to beThis topology is called the Zariski topology.A basis for the Zariski topology can be constructed as follows.

Akasha or Akash ( Sanskrit ) means space or sky or æther in traditional Indian cosmology , depending on the source. It appears as the fifth and final part of the Vedas, the final chapter of which is the Purana, which describes the creation of heaven and earth and the fall of mankind. The Akasha is associated with the cosmos in the Hindu cosmology, and is one of the three cosmic planes or spheres in the cosmology. The Akita  is a large freshwater fish native to the island of Kyushu and other parts of Japan, including some in the Sea of Japan.

The governor general of Canada  is the federal viceregal representative of the . The  is head of state of Canada and the 14 other Commonwealth realms, but  resides in  oldest and most populous realm, the United Kingdom. The , on the advice of  Canadian prime minister, appoints a governor general to carry on the Government of Canada in the 's name, performing most of her constitutional and ceremonial duties. The commission is for an indefinite period—known as serving at  Majesty's pleasure—though five years is the usual length of time. Since 1959, it has also been traditional to alternate between anglophone and francophone officeholders—although many recent governors general have been bilingual.

In chemistry , an aldehyde is an organic compound containing a functional group with the structure −C ( H )–( C ) or −C–H ( )–OH, for example, a methyl alcohol, a ketone, a methyl ester, and so on. In computer science, an ASCII character string or ASCII code unit (or code point) is the sequence of characters used to represent one or more bytes in a computer readable character set. Character encoding refers to the algorithm used by the computer to convert characters into a fixed length code point sequence.

Charles University, known also as Charles University in Prague ( (UK); ; ) or historically as the University of Prague , is the oldest and largest university in the Czech Republic. It is one of the oldest universities in Europe in continuous operation. Today, the university consists of 17 faculties located in Prague, Hradec Králové, and Plzeň. The Charles University belongs to top three universities in Central and Eastern Europe. It is ranked around 200–300 in the world.HistoryMedieval university (1349–1419)The establishment of a medieval university in Prague was inspired by Holy Roman Emperor Charles IV.

A beta particle , also called beta ray or beta radiation ( symbol β ) , is a high-energy , short-lived, charged particle of the atomic nucleus . The term is most often used in physics and chemistry, where it is generally referred to as a particle beta. The most familiar form of particle beta is the electron, which can interact with matter and radiation in a variety of ways, from being absorbed and scattered by matter (to produce gamma rays) to being emitted from matter (to make radio waves). A bifurcation is an abrupt change in the direction of a plane.

Thrust is a reaction force described quantitatively by Newton's third law. When a system expels or accelerates mass in one direction, the accelerated mass will cause a force of equal magnitude but opposite direction to be applied to that system.The force applied on a surface in a direction perpendicular or normal to the surface is also called thrust. Force, and thus thrust, is measured using the International System of Units (SI) in newtons (symbol: N), and represents the amount needed to accelerate 1 kilogram of mass at the rate of 1 meter per second per second.

Mecklenburg-Vorpommern ( MV ; , ) , also known by its anglicized name Mecklenburg–Western Pomerania , is a state in eastern Germany. It forms the southernmost part of the Pomeranian Lowlands and forms the boundary between West and East, and is bordered to the east by the Austrian and Moravia regions, to the north and west by Lower Austria and Lower Silesia, to the south and east by Westphalia and Pomerania, and to the south-west by Brandenburg and the Saar. The city of Nuremberg in the state's northeast corner is the regional capital, and the county of Mecklenburg‐Western Pomerania is the administrative division encompassing the whole region.

Pioneer 10 ( originally designated Pioneer F ) is an American space probe , launched in 1972 and weighing , the second largest American space probe (after NASA's Apollo 17) and the first to enter lunar orbit. It was designed to demonstrate the feasibility of a space station and to gather data about the surface of the Moon.Launched under a joint program by two American companies, the project was jointly funded by the Air Force, the Department of Defense (DoD) and NASA, and developed at both the Johnson Space Center, Houston, Texas, and Cape Canaveral, Florida.

A tremor is an involuntary , somewhat rhythmic , muscle contraction and relaxation involving oscillations or twitching movements of one or more of the musculoskeletal muscle groups. As the name implies, a tremor usually starts in a specific part of the body (the "site of tremor" ) and spreads to other parts of the body. Transport in Japan includes air, sea, train and bus services, as well as a ferry network. The national railway network comprises about 100,000 miles (161,000 kilometers) of track, including 6,000 miles (9,000 km) of double-track electrified lines, and over 50,000 passenger coaches.

Kannada ( ; ಕನ್ನಡ , ; less commonly known as Kanarese ) is a Dravidian language spoken predominantly by the people of Tamil Nadu and Kerala in Southern India and in Bangladesh. The language has been used as a lingua franca in Southern India, with many native speakers moving to southern India to find work. The Tamil diaspora is composed of approximately 3 million people spread over the globe. The language is the official  of India, Nepal, Pakistan, Bangladesh, Maldives, Sri Lanka, and Bhutan.History The language of ancient India, Tamil, first appeared around 1000 BC.

Year 1493 (MCDXCIII) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January 19 – Treaty of Barcelona: Charles VIII of France returns Cerdagne and Roussillon to Ferdinand of Aragon. March 1 – Martín Alonso Pinzón returns to the city of Bayona in Spain from the  voyage of discovery, sending the first notice about the discovery to the Catholic Monarchs (Christopher Columbus is delayed by a storm in the Azores). March 4 – Christopher Columbus anchors in Lisbon and completes his February 15 letter on the first voyage conveying the news of his discoveries.

Thomas Becket , also known as Saint Thomas of Canterbury, Thomas of London and later Thomas à Becket (21 December 1119 or 1120 – 29 December 1170), was Archbishop of Canterbury from 1162 until his murder in 1170. He is venerated as a saint and martyr by the Catholic Church and the Anglican Communion. He engaged in conflict with Henry II, King of England, over the rights and privileges of the Church and was murdered by followers of the king in Canterbury Cathedral. Soon after his death, he was canonised by Pope Alexander III.SourcesThe main sources for the life of Becket are a number of biographies written by contemporaries.

Lindsey Adams Buckingham ( born October 3 , 1949 ) is an American singer , musician , songwriter , and record producer. Beginning in the late 1960s, he has been the lead singer and musical director of the band, Fleetwood Mac. Buckingham's career began with the 1970 release of their fourth studio album Rumours, which was the biggest-selling British album of that year. In mathematics, the binomial theorem is a theorem in analysis. It asserts that for n positive integers, if a binary function f(n) is independent of the order of n (i.e.

Year 878 ( DCCCLXXVIII ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) in the Gregorian reform calendar in the early 20th century of Europe and the United States. The year was introduced by King Louis XI of France on June 5, 1469, and was a reform of the Julian and Julianan calendars.The year was celebrated as a festival, the Feast of the Sacred Fools, on June 14.HistoryThe year 762 was the fifth year of Pope Damasus, who reformed the calendar after the fall of the Western Roman empire in 476.

Alfa Romeo Automobiles S.p.A. is an Italian luxury car manufacturer and a subsidiary of Stellantis . The company was founded in 1922 and the car was launched in 1929. The name "Alfa Romeo" comes from its founder's name Alfa Romeo, which was the name of the company.Alfa Romeo is the second-most-popular brand in Europe behind Volkswagen, and is the fourth-most-popular in North America. American Airlines ( ) is a major international aviation carrier based in Miami, Florida. The airline is the world's fourth-largest, after United Airlines, Delta Air Lines, and Alaska Airlines.

Mystery religions , mystery cults , sacred mysteries or simply mysteries , were religious schools of the Greco-Roman world for the purpose of propagating the ideas, rituals, and practices associated with the worship of gods, spirits, deities, or supernatural beings. A member of a mystery cult was one who believed in a supernatural world or gods or was an initiate who had been taught by a master in the use of magic and spiritual magic. This article presents an overview of how the European Union works as an integrated market. It focuses on EU integration and on the main tasks each member state has in this area.

Montevideo  is the capital and largest city of Uruguay. According to the 2011 census, the city proper has a population of 1,319,108 (about one-third of the country's total population) in an area of . Montevideo is situated on the southern coast of the country, on the northeastern bank of the Río de la Plata.The city was established in 1724 by a Spanish soldier, Bruno Mauricio de Zabala, as a strategic move amidst the Spanish-Portuguese dispute over the platine region. It was also under brief British rule in 1807, but eventually the city was retaken by Spanish criollos.

Rubber , also called India rubber , latex , Amazonian rubber , caucho , or caoutchouc , as initially produced in the Amazon rainforest , is the soft material made from the exoskeleton of the rubber tree (Aithusa canadensis). The material has many applications such as footwear, packaging, construction equipment, and toys. The term rubber is also used to refer to other rubber products with varying properties, such as automotive tires, clothing, adhesives, and cosmetics.Rubber can be made of natural rubber, hydrocarbon rubber, and synthetic rubber.

Westminster is an area of Central London, part of the wider City of Westminster.The area, which extends from the River Thames to Oxford Street has many visitor attractions and historic landmarks, including the Palace of Westminster, Buckingham Palace, Westminster Abbey, Westminster Cathedral and much of the West End shopping and entertainment district.The name  originated from the informal description of the abbey church and royal peculiar of St Peter's (Westminster Abbey), west of the City of London (until the English Reformation there was also an Eastminster, near the Tower of London, in the East End of London).

New Sweden ( ; ; ) was a Swedish colony along the lower reaches of the Delaware River in America. It was founded by Swedish immigrants in 1750 on the Delaware River between present-day Delaware and North Bergen in the state of New York. A third settlement on the Delaware River near present-day Point Pleasant, West Virginia, was founded later, but became known as West Point (1763). In physics, quantum mechanics , the theory of particles that are in many ways quantum mechanical entities, is the dominant branch of theoretical physics.

In chemistry , a nucleophile is a chemical species that forms bonds with electrophiles by donating an electron pair . In alkali metals, this may be done by substituting an ionic bond or, less commonly, a covalent bond (e.g, hydrogen bonds). The covalent bonds in alkali metal-containing molecules may be weak and may give rise to ionic defects, but this may be overcome by additional covalent bonding. Northeastern University , commonly shortened as Northeastern, is an American private university in Boston, Massachusetts . It was established in 1851 and has graduated more than 25,000 students since.

François Marie Adrien Maurice Mitterrand ( 26 October 19168 January 1996 ) served as President of France from 1981 to 1995, and Prime Minister of France from 1981 to 1997. A Socialist, he was the first president of a republic since the end of World War II, and the first president of a party in modern French history to hold office while also holding the rank of Minister of Foreign Affairs.Born in Paris to an upper-class family on 27 November 1895, Mitterrand served as a student in the Lycée Nationale, before he entered politics.

Menstruation (also known as a period and many other colloquial terms) is the regular discharge of blood and mucosal tissue from the inner lining of the uterus through the vagina. The menstrual cycle is characterized by the rise and fall of hormones. Menstruation is triggered by falling progesterone levels and is a sign that pregnancy has not occurred.The first period, a point in time known as menarche, usually begins between the ages of 12 and 15. Menstruation starting as young as 8 years would still be considered normal. The average age of the first period is generally later in the developing world, and earlier in the developed world.

Hugh John Lofting (14 January 1886 – 26 September 1947) was an English author trained as a civil engineer, who created the classic children's literature character of Doctor Dolittle. It first appeared in illustrated letters to his children written by Lofting from the British Army trenches in the First World War.Personal lifeLofting, born in January 1886 in Maidenhead, Berkshire, to Elizabeth Agnes (Gannon) and John Brien Lofting, was of English and Irish ancestry. His eldest brother, Hilary Lofting, later became a novelist in Australia, having emigrated there in 1915.Lofting was educated at Mount St Mary's College in Spinkhill, Derbyshire.

Millets  are a group of highly variable small-seeded grasses, widely grown around the world as cereal crops or grains for fodder and human food. Most species generally referred to as millets belong to the tribe Paniceae, but some millets also belong to various other taxa.Millets are important crops in the semiarid tropics of Asia and Africa (especially in India, Mali, Nigeria, and Niger), with 97% of millet production in developing countries. The crop is favored due to its productivity and short growing season under dry, high-temperature conditions.Millets are indigenous to many parts of the world.

An airport is an aerodrome with extended facilities, mostly for commercial air transport. Airports often have facilities to park and maintain aircraft, and a control tower. An airport consists of a landing area, which comprises an aerially accessible open space including at least one operationally active surface such as a runway for a plane to take off and to land or a helipad, and often includes adjacent utility buildings such as control towers, hangars and terminals. Larger airports may have airport aprons, taxiway bridges, air traffic control centres, passenger facilities such as restaurants and lounges, and emergency services.

The Who are an English rock band formed in London in 1964. Their classic lineup consisted of lead singer Roger Daltrey, guitarist and singer Pete Townshend, bass guitarist and singer John Entwistle, and drummer Keith Moon. They are considered one of the most influential rock bands of the 20th century, and have sold over 100 million records worldwide. Their contributions to rock music include the development of the Marshall Stack, large PA systems, the use of the synthesizer, Entwistle and Moon's influential playing styles, Townshend's feedback and power chord guitar technique, and the development of the rock opera.

Great Barrier Island  lies in the outer Hauraki Gulf, New Zealand,  north-east of central Auckland. With an area of  it is the sixth-largest island of New Zealand and fourth-largest in the main chain. Its highest point, Mount Hobson, is  above sea level. The local authority is the Auckland Council.The island was initially exploited for its minerals and kauri trees and saw only limited agriculture. In 2013, it was inhabited by 939 people, mostly living from farming and tourism and all living off-the-grid. The majority of the island (around 60% of the total area) is administered as a nature reserve by the Department of Conservation.

In mathematics , the Dirac delta distribution ( distribution ) , also known as the unit impulse symbol , is an integral probability distribution over , with a probability density function given by
. This is an infinite sum over , and it describes the probability that a single event will occur in a non-increasing interval. The value of this distribution is the number of possibilities for the event that the event occurs given the probability of all other events in the interval being equal to zero. The D'Alembert Institute is a French scientific organization that focuses on the study of the history and culture of the Roman Empire.

Numismatics is the study or collection of currency,  including coins, tokens, paper money, medals and related objects.Specialists, known as numismatists, are often characterized as students or collectors of coins, but the discipline also includes the broader study of money and other means of payment used to resolve debts and exchange goods.The earliest forms of money used by peoples is referred to as "Odd and Curious", but the use of other goods in barter exchange is excluded, even where used as a circulating currency (e.g., cigarettes in prison).

Antioch on the Orontes ( ; , Antiókheia hē epì Oróntou ; also Syrian Antioch ) was a Hellenistic city-state founded by King Agrippa, and known for its temple dedicated to Apollo (Apokalips) – the founder of Hellenistic astronomy, the star of which is depicted as an eagle (as in his inscription) with a winged club in its left beak. Antwerpen ( ; Antwerpen, Antwerp, , ; ) is the westernmost part of Antwerp and the largest municipality in Belgium. It is located on the river Meuse, about 11 km south-east of the city centre and about 9 km south-west of the former town of Nieuwpoort.

Script Creation Utility for Maniac Mansion (SCUMM) is a video game engine developed at Lucasfilm Games, later renamed LucasArts, to ease development on their graphic adventure game Maniac Mansion (1987). It was subsequently used as the engine for later LucasArts adventure games.It falls somewhere between a game engine and a programming language, allowing designers to create locations, items and dialogue sequences without writing code in the language in which the game source code ends up. This also allowed the game's script and data files to be cross-platform, i.e., re-used across various platforms.

Year 870 ( DCCCLXX ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) in 752 AD. A common year is a Gregorian calendar year in which the day of the week (Sunday in most modern calendars) is a fixed point on the lunar calendar.The first common year began when the Roman emperor Septimius Severus ordered that the Julian calendar be adopted as the new calendar for the Roman Empire in AD 563. Carroll D. Moseley (; May 17, 1947 – October 11, 2001) was an American author, editor, translator and screenwriter.

Enriched uranium is a type of uranium in which the percent composition of uranium-235 (written 235U) has been increased through the process of isotope separation. Naturally occurring uranium is composed of three major isotopes:  uranium-238 (238U with 99.2739–99.2752% natural abundance), uranium-235 (235U, 0.7198–0.7202%), and uranium-234 (234U, 0.0050–0.0059%). 235U is the only nuclide existing in nature (in any appreciable amount) that is fissile with thermal neutrons.Enriched uranium is a critical component for both civil nuclear power generation and military nuclear weapons.

Landslides, also known as landslips, are several forms of mass wasting that may include a wide range of ground movements, such as rockfalls, deep-seated slope failures, mudflows, and debris flows. Landslides occur in a variety of environments, characterized by either steep or gentle slope gradients, from mountain ranges to coastal cliffs or even underwater, in which case they are called submarine landslides. Gravity is the primary driving force for a landslide to occur, but there are other factors affecting slope stability that produce specific conditions that make a slope prone to failure.

Thrust is a reaction force described quantitatively by Newton 's third law . When a system expels or accelerates mass from its immediate surroundings, the net force acting on that mass changes the momentum or the kinetic energy of the mass that was expelled or accelerated, but does not change the direction of the acceleration. The net force acts on the mass in all directions simultaneously, as if the mass were acting as a single rigid object. The force is always in one dimension, since it acts across space, but the force vector varies with the orientation of the accelerated mass.

Fidelio , originally titled  (Leonore, or The Triumph of Marital Love), Op. 72, is Ludwig van Beethoven's only opera. The German libretto was originally prepared by Joseph Sonnleithner from the French of Jean-Nicolas Bouilly, with the work premiering at Vienna's Theater an der Wien on 20 November 1805. The following year, Stephan von Breuning helped shorten the work from three acts to two. After further work on the libretto by Georg Friedrich Treitschke, a final version was performed at the Kärntnertortheater on 23 May 1814.

Gaelic football ( ; short name ) , commonly known as simply Gaelic , GAA or Caid , is an inter-regional football competition, comprising three divisions: the top tier of Leinster and Munster Leagues, as well as one division comprising the counties of Munster, Leinster, Tipperary and Sligo; the lower tier of Ulster and Connacht Leagues; and one division of the county of Laois and Donegal Leagues. The competition was established as an inter-county rivalry by the Irish Gaelic League (IGL) in 1948, and was founded as an offshoot of Irish football.

Fighting Fantasy is a series of single-player role-playing gamebooks created by Steve Jackson and Ian Livingstone . The first volume was published in 1989, with the subsequent three volumes released between 1995 and 2003. In computer science, parallel computing (or parallel processing) refers to the ability to parallelize a computation across several processing units (also known as units of execution or threads) on the same computer or across several computers. This capability is used to perform a computation on several processing units, with each processing unit executing only a single step of the computation.

Reptilia is Canada's largest indoor reptile zoo, with  of indoor exhibits featuring over 250 reptiles, amphibians and arachnids. It is accredited by CAZA.Currently there are two Ontario locations, one in Vaughan and one in Whitby.LocationsThe original Reptilia zoo was established in Vaughan; it is housed in a  facility. In 2018, it opened a second location in Whitby in a former  Rona store. In late 2018, it announced plans to create similar zoos in London and Barrie. London City Council rejected the proposal for a  reptile zoo in Westmount Mall.AttractionsAbout 250 species of reptiles are in the zoo's collection.

A finger is a limb of the body and a type of digit, an organ of manipulation and sensation found in the hands of most of the Tetrapods, so also with humans and other primates. Most land vertebrates have five fingers (Pentadactyly).Land vertebrate fingers The five-rayed anterior limbs of terrestrial vertebrates can be derived phylogenetically from the pectoral fins of fish. Within the taxa of the terrestrial vertebrates, the basic pentadactyl plan, and thus also the fingers and phalanges, undergoe many variations.Morphologically the different fingers of terrestrial vertebrates are homolog. The wings of birds and those of bats are not homologous, they are analogue flight organs.

Medina , officially Al Madinah Al Munawwarah and also commonly simplified as Madīnah or Madinah , is the second-holiest city in Islam, after Mecca. It was the only capital of the Abbasid caliphate, and is considered by Muslims to be one of the most holy places on Earth. It is located in the northwestern Arabian Peninsula, on the east side of the Saudi-Arabia border, and is the largest city in Saudi Arabia.History
History Pre-Islamic and Islamic historyThe city of Medina is named after two cities. It was founded during the Caliphate of the Abbasid Caliphate.

The Alcubierre drive, Alcubierre warp drive, or Alcubierre metric (referring to metric tensor), is a speculative warp drive idea based on a solution of Einstein's field equations in general relativity as proposed by theoretical physicist Miguel Alcubierre during his PhD study at the University of Wales, Cardiff, by which a spacecraft could achieve apparent faster-than-light travel if a configurable energy-density field lower than that of vacuum (that is, negative mass) could be created.Rather than exceeding the speed of light within a local reference frame, a spacecraft would traverse distances by contracting space in front of it and expanding space behind it, resulting in effective faster-than-light travel.

Harlequin (;  ;  ) is the best-known of the zanni or comic servant characters from the Italian commedia dell'arte. The role is traditionally believed to have been introduced by Zan Ganassa in the late 16th century, was definitively popularized by the Italian actor Tristano Martinelli in Paris in 1584–1585, and became a stock character after Martinelli's death in 1630.The Harlequin is characterized by his chequered costume. His role is that of a light-hearted, nimble, and astute servant, often acting to thwart the plans of his master, and pursuing his own love interest, Columbina, with wit and resourcefulness, often competing with the sterner and melancholic Pierrot.

D'Urville Island , Te Reo Māori name  ('red heavens look to the south'), is an island in the Marlborough Sounds along the northern coast of the South Island of New Zealand. It was named after the French explorer Jules Dumont d'Urville. With an area of approximately , it is the eighth-largest island of New Zealand, and has around 52 permanent residents. The local authority is the Marlborough District Council.HistoryThe official name of the island is Rangitoto ki te Tonga / D'Urville Island, with the Māori language name, associated with Kupe, meaning "Red Heavens Look to the South".

Activision Publishing , Inc. is an American video game publisher based in Santa Monica , California . It serves as a publishing arm of Activision Blizzard Inc. ( OIB ), the parent company to the Call of Duty, Skylanders, Guitar Hero, NBA 2K, LittleBigPlanet, Skylanders Adventures, Skylanders Giants franchises. It was founded by Rob Kostich and Jason Rubin in 1992, and its headquarters is located in Santa Monica . It was formerly known as Kostich and Rubin Games, Inc. It has offices in Santa Monica, San Francisco, New York, and Orlando, Florida.

Year 1103 (MCIII) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Levant  Spring – Bohemond I, Norman prince of Antioch, is released from Seljuk imprisonment at Niksar, after a ransom is paid of 100,000 gold pieces. During his absence, Tancred (Bohemond's nephew) attacks the Byzantines, and re-captures the cities of Tarsus, Adana and Mamistra in Cilicia. Tancred is deprived of his lordship by Bohemond's return, and is rewarded with a small fief within the Principality of Antioch.

Relative density, or specific gravity, is the ratio of the density (mass of a unit volume) of a substance to the density of a given reference material. Specific gravity for liquids is nearly always measured with respect to water at its densest (at ); for gases, the reference is air at room temperature . The term "relative density" is often preferred in scientific usage. If a substance's relative density is less than 1 then it is less dense than the reference; if greater than 1 then it is denser than the reference.

The War Game is a 1966 British pseudo-documentary film that depicts a nuclear war and its aftermath . Written , directed and starring David Niven , the film was based on Ian Fleming's 1953 novel Casino Royale , which was later adapted into a 1958 James Bond film starring Roger Moore.The War Game is one of the first films to depict nuclear war, and the first to show nuclear weapons being fired in real time.It is notable as the first time nuclear war is shown to have a real impact on the people involved and as one of the first such films to depict a nuclear winter.

George Shipway ( 25 May 1908–1982 ) was a British author best known for his historical novels , but he is also one of the most well-known science fiction writers of all time and one of the few authors to be awarded the Hugo, Nebula, Arthur C. Clarke and Theodore Sturgeon Memorial Awards. He also published several short novels.BiographyEarly life and early life in the familyShipway was the third child of the Reverend James Shipway and his fourth wife, Elizabeth (Cox). He was the only of his three sisters to remain in the family home.

Lieutenant General Henry Shrapnel (3 June 1761 – 13 March 1842) was a British Army officer whose name has entered the English language as the inventor of the shrapnel shell.Henry Shrapnel was born at Midway Manor in Bradford-on-Avon, Wiltshire, England, the ninth child of Zachariah Shrapnel and his wife Lydia.In 1784, while a lieutenant in the Royal Artillery, he perfected, with his own resources, an invention of what he called "spherical case" ammunition: a hollow cannonball filled with lead shot that burst in mid-air. He successfully demonstrated this in 1787 at Gibraltar.

In combinatorics and in experimental design , a Latin square is an n × n array filled with n different symbols, denoted by the Latin letters c , h , p , s , j , and x , where the symbols c , h , p , s , and j are of the same size, while x is the same size as the largest symbol in that row or column. It is the lowest common factor of the size n and of the number of symbols in the array. The California Institute of Technology (Caltech) is an American institution located in Pasadena, California, United States.

In the Ancient Greek religion , Hestia ( ; , `` hearth '' or `` fireside '' ) is the goddess of fire, air, and fire-worship, the goddess of light and the goddess of light-giving. Her name means "female fire" in Greek. According to Plutarch , she is a daughter of Aeacus and Cresphontes. Hestia is also the mother of the Titans and, according to Hesiod, her father is Uranus. Hestia is sometimes portrayed as an old woman. Heracleides (; ; ;  , Greek  : ὄλυχος) was a Hellenistic writer who is known by his own name but who was most commonly called Heracleitus.

Peperomia (radiator plant) is one of the two large genera of the family Piperaceae. Most of them are compact, small perennial epiphytes growing on rotten wood. More than 1500 species have been recorded, occurring in all tropical and subtropical regions of the world, though concentrated in Central America and northern South America. A limited number of species (around 17) are found in Africa.DescriptionThough varying considerably in appearance (see gallery below), these species generally have thick, stout stems and fleshy leaves, sometimes with epidermal windows. Peperomia flowers typically come in yellow to brown conical spikes.These tropical perennials are grown for their ornamental foliage.

Strasbourg (, , ;  ;  ,  ) is the prefecture and largest city of the Grand Est region of eastern France and the official seat of the European Parliament. Located at the border with Germany in the historic region of Alsace, it is the prefecture of the Bas-Rhin department.In 2019, the city proper had 287,228 inhabitants and both the Eurométropole de Strasbourg (Greater Strasbourg) and the Arrondissement of Strasbourg had 505,272 inhabitants. Strasbourg's metropolitan area had a population of 790,087 in 2017, making it the ninth-largest metro area in France and home to 13% of the Grand Est region's inhabitants.

Nansen passports, originally and officially stateless persons passports, were internationally recognized refugee travel documents from 1922 to 1938, first issued by the League of Nations to stateless refugees. They quickly became known as "Nansen passports" for their promoter, the Norwegian statesman and polar explorer Fridtjof Nansen.HistoryThe end of World War I saw significant turmoil, leading to a refugee crisis. Numerous governments were toppled, and national borders were re-drawn, often along generally ethnic lines. Civil war broke out in some countries. Many people left their homes because of war or persecution or fear thereof.

Columbina (in Italian Colombina, meaning "little dove"; in French and English Colombine) is a stock character in the commedia dell'arte. She is Harlequin's mistress, a comic servant playing the tricky slave type, and wife of Pierrot. Rudlin and Crick use the Italian spelling Colombina in Commedia dell'arte: A Handbook for Troupes.HistoryThe role of the female servant was originally that of an entr'acte dancer. Women were not allowed to be part of the story that was being played out on stage, but they were allowed to have a dance in-between the action.

Bruce Lee ( ; November 27 , 1940 – July 20 , 1973 ) , born Lee Jun-fan , was an American martial artist and film star. He played the lead role in many of his films, which were highly popular throughout Asia.Lee is best known for his starring role in The Green Hornet (1964), which is widely considered to be the first martial arts movie. He also starred in The Chinese Boxer (1965), Drunken Master (1966), Enter the Dragon (1980) and Dragon: The Bruce Lee Story (1990).

The governor general of Canada is the federal viceregal representative of the . The is head of state of Canada. In Canada, he or she presides over the Commonwealth realm of Canada, which has a constitutional monarchy. Canadian provinces and territories form the Commonwealth Realm of Canada. The Central Bank of Cyprus is the official bank of the Republic of Cyprus. In practice, it mainly acts as a financial institution of the central government. Its capital and reserves are made available to the Cyprus government, but they are not controlled or used for the government's monetary policies.

A pegmatite is an igneous rock showing a very coarse texture, with large interlocking crystals usually greater in size than  and sometimes greater than . Most pegmatites are composed of quartz, feldspar, and mica, having a similar silicic composition as granite. However, rarer intermediate composition and mafic pegmatites are known.Many of the world's largest crystals are found within pegmatites. These include crystals of microcline, quartz, mica, spodumene, beryl, and tourmaline. Some individual crystals are over  long.Most pegmatites are thought to form from the last fluid fraction of a large crystallizing magma body.

Celebration is a census-designated place ( CDP ) and a master-planned community in Osceola County , Florida , United States, on the north-eastern end of the state's Gulf of Mexico coast . The community consists of more than 300 buildings, a school, and a cemetery. It was founded in 1960 as a community for African Americans with the goal of integrating Osceola County. The International Space Station ( ISS ) is an unmanned Russian cargo spacecraft launched by the space shuttle, the Russian Soyuz MS-04, from the Cosmodrome in Dnepropetrovsk, Ukraine, on 11 January 2005.

Purple is any of a variety of colors with hue between red and blue . In the RGB color model, a color's hue lies in its chromaticity, which is an intensity value of the color and an intensity value of each of the four colors in that color's gamut. Fenrir is a character from Norse mythology and the second son of Loki and Völuspá. As a god of war, he fought and defeated Thor, the God of Thunder. He is known for his ferocious battle with the giant Grímnismál, which the latter killed using a hammer that he had stolen from a god named Höðr.

The History of East Asia generally encompasses the histories of China , Japan , Korea , and Mongolia from prehistoric times up until the fall of the Qing dynasty (1644). History of Japan and Korea in particular is considered the earliest history of East Asian civilization. History of Chinese history, including the Han dynasty (206 BC - 220 BC) is the longest and covers the period of the Chinese empire and unification. Hinduism (or Hinduism,   ;  Hinduism,  or   ) is one of the three principal religions in the Indian subcontinent, together with Buddhism and Jainism.

Liberation theology is a Christian theological approach emphasizing the liberation of the oppressed. In certain contexts, it engages socio-economic analyses, with "social concern for the poor and political liberation for oppressed peoples." In other contexts, it addresses other forms of inequality, such as race or caste.Liberation theology is best known in the Latin American context, especially within Catholicism in the 1960s after the Second Vatican Council, where it became the political praxis of theologians such as Gustavo Gutiérrez, Leonardo Boff, and Jesuits Juan Luis Segundo and Jon Sobrino, who popularized the phrase "preferential option for the poor".

In quantum mechanics, counterfactual definiteness (CFD) is the ability to speak "meaningfully" of the definiteness of the results of measurements that have not been performed (i.e., the ability to assume the existence of objects, and properties of objects, even when they have not been measured). The term "counterfactual definiteness" is used in discussions of physics calculations, especially those related to the phenomenon called quantum entanglement and those related to the Bell inequalities. In such discussions "meaningfully" means the ability to treat these unmeasured results on an equal footing with measured results in statistical calculations.

The lion (Panthera leo) is a large cat of the genus Panthera native to Africa and India. It has a muscular, deep-chested body, short, rounded head, round ears, and a hairy tuft at the end of its tail. It is sexually dimorphic; adult male lions are larger than females and have a prominent mane. It is a social species, forming groups called prides. A lion's pride consists of a few adult males, related females, and cubs. Groups of female lions usually hunt together, preying mostly on large ungulates.

The Bussard ramjet is a theoretical method of spacecraft propulsion proposed in 1960 by the physicist Robert W. Bussard, popularized by Poul Anderson's novel Tau Zero, Larry Niven in his Known Space series of books, Vernor Vinge in his Zones of Thought series, and referred to by Carl Sagan in the television series and book Cosmos.Bussard proposed a ramjet variant of a fusion rocket capable of reasonable interstellar travel, using enormous electromagnetic fields (ranging from kilometers to many thousands of kilometers in diameter) as a ram scoop to collect and compress hydrogen from the interstellar medium.

Cell division is the process by which a parent cell divides into two or more daughter cells . Cell division is the most fundamental biological process, responsible for the formation of every living cell, including all eukaryotic cells, and for a wide array of other cellular processes, including mitosis and the production of cell membrane and nuclear membrane protein. Claudio Arrau , also known as Largo, (; born October 12, 1953) is a Brazilian actor, singer, television personality, and television producer. He has been active in Brazilian culture and politics since the 1970s.

The Story of the Chevalier des Grieux and Manon Lescaut  is a novel by Antoine François Prévost. Published in 1731, it is the seventh and final volume of Mémoires et aventures d'un homme de qualité (Memoirs and Adventures of a Man of Quality).The story, set in France and Louisiana in the early 18th century, follows the hero, the Chevalier des Grieux, and his lover, Manon Lescaut. Controversial in its time, the work was banned in France upon publication. Despite this, it became very popular and pirated editions were widely distributed.

Cannabis  is a genus of flowering plants in the family Cannabaceae. The number of species within the genus is disputed. Three species may be recognized: Cannabis sativa, Cannabis indica, and Cannabis ruderalis; C. ruderalis may be included within C. sativa; all three may be treated as subspecies of a single species, C. sativa; or C. sativa may be accepted as a single undivided species. The genus is widely accepted as being indigenous to and originating from Asia.The plant is also known as hemp, although this term is often used to refer only to varieties of Cannabis cultivated for non-drug use.

George Catlett Marshall Jr.  (December 31, 1880 – October 16, 1959) was an American army officer and statesman. He rose through the United States Army to become Chief of Staff under Presidents Franklin D. Roosevelt and Harry S. Truman, then served as Secretary of State and Secretary of Defense under Truman. Winston Churchill lauded Marshall as the "organizer of victory" for his leadership of the Allied victory in World War II. After the war, he spent a frustrating year trying and failing to avoid the impending civil war in China.

Adoption is a process whereby a person assumes the parenting of another , usually a child , from that person's biological parents . Adoptive parents are typically people who are already parents or who would be parents if they had not adopted a child. Adoption can result in the child being legally adopted or it can result in a child being adopted by a step-parent or step-brother or sister. Adrenal gland (abbreviated  ) is the internal hormone-secreting gland in the neck of the animal. It is located at the base of the kidneys, and can be divided into two main groups: the medulla and adrenal medulla.

Hazardous waste is waste that has substantial or potential threats to public health or the environment.Characteristic hazardous wastes are materials that may have explosive, toxic, or caustic or other hazardous effects. Hemoglobin ( ) is the oxygen-carrying protein of red blood cells. It is an organic molecule (oxygen-containing polymer) containing two amino acids, glycine and serine. It plays an important role in cellular respiration, energy metabolism, and blood clotting, and contributes to   hemoglobin content.Hemoglobin exists as a globular protein, termed haemoglobin, and two membrane-embedded globules: haemocyanin. These globules have two hydrophilic heads, one of which faces the cell membrane.

Bi-curious is a term for a person , usually someone who is a heterosexual , who is curious or open to sexual experiences or relationships outside their gender. A bi-curious person is often a person who identifies as transgender or bisexual, but it can describe a person who identifies with a non-normative gender, identifies with the same gender as a romantic partner or has an interest in more than two genders.Bi-curious is a type of sexual orientation. It differs from heterosexuality in that it does not always involve an explicit sexual attraction towards the same sex; it might simply be a general curiosity or interest in sex.

A pegmatite is an igneous rock showing a very coarse texture , with large interlocking crystals usually greater in size than a few millimetres in diameter and often with numerous smaller crystals forming clusters. It may have an iron-nickel (ferromagnetic) magnetite mineralization at its base that is partially magnetized at high ambient temperatures.Pegmatites are common in igneous rocks. George Bernard Shaw (;  25 June 1882 – 14 February 1964) was an English playwright, essayist, journalist, and novelist. His major works were plays, novels, short stories, and screenplays, and his play The Lion in Winter was adapted into a Hollywood film directed by George Cukor.

Budapest ( , ; ) is the capital and most populous city of Hungary . It is the ninth-largest city in Central Europe. Budapest is located along the Danube and is the second-largest river port in the EU. It is one of the world's oldest continually inhabited cities.Hungary is Europe's largest democracy and the second democracy in Central Europe after Czechoslovakia, and the fifth in the European Union, after the UK, France and Spain. The constitution provides for pluralism, and the country was ranked 17th in the 2017 Democracy Index published by the European Commission.

Alain Marie Pascal Prost (born 24 February 1955) is a French retired racing driver. A four-time Formula One Drivers' Champion, from 1987 until 2001 he held the record for most Grand Prix victories until Michael Schumacher surpassed Prost's total of 51 victories at the 2001 Belgian Grand Prix. In 1999, Prost received the World Sports Award of the Century in the motor sport category.Prost discovered karting at the age of 14 during a family holiday. He progressed through motor sport's junior ranks, winning the French and European Formula Three championships, before joining the McLaren Formula One team in 1980 at the age of 24.

Emissions trading is a market-based approach to controlling pollution by providing economic incentives for reducing the emissions of pollutants. The concept is also known as cap and trade (CAT) or emissions trading scheme (ETS). Carbon emission trading for  and other greenhouse gases has been introduced in China, the European Union and other countries as a key tool for climate change mitigation. Other schemes include sulfur dioxide and other pollutants.In an emissions trading scheme, a central authority or governmental body allocates or sells a limited number (a "cap") of permits that allow a discharge of a specific quantity of a specific pollutant over a set time period.

The European Organization for Nuclear Research , known as CERN ( ; ; derived from the name ) , is a European Union organization responsible for the CERN research center in Geneva, Switzerland. Founded in 1954 as the European Atomic Energy Community, it is today an international research institute.CERN's research programs focus on fundamental physics, high-energy physics, and space science, and also cover a variety of other areas, such as the use of nuclear power.The European Commission (the European Union executive branch) is responsible for policy development, policy implementation, funding and coordination.

The University of California, Los Angeles (UCLA) is a public land-grant research university in Los Angeles, California. UCLA’s academic roots were established in 1882 as a teachers college then known as the southern branch of the California State Normal School (now San José State University). This school was absorbed with the official founding of UCLA as the Southern Branch of the University of California in 1919, making it the second-oldest of the 10-campus University of California system (after UC Berkeley).UCLA offers 337 undergraduate and graduate degree programs in a wide range of disciplines, enrolling about 31,600 undergraduate and 14,300 graduate and professional students.

Pope Leo II ( – 28 June 683) was the bishop of Rome from 17 August 682 to his death. He is one of the popes of the Byzantine Papacy. Described by a contemporary biographer as both just and learned, he is commemorated as a saint in the Roman Martyrology on 28 June (3 July, pre-1970 calendar).Early careerLeo was a Sicilian by birth, the son of a man named Paul. He may have ended up being among the many Sicilian clergymen in Rome due to the attacks of the Caliphate on Sicily in the mid-7th century.

The lungs are the primary organs of the respiratory system in humans and most animals including a few fish , such as lungfish and lobsters . In humans, breathing takes place through the nose and mouth, or the trachea. The two major airways are the alveolar and pleural spaces in the head and neck. Air is circulated by the bronchi to the alveoli in the tissues of the lungs, where the gas exchange takes place between the gases inhaled from the lungs and gases expelled during exhalation.The airways themselves are divided into two parts, the mediastinal and pulmonary.

The following outline is provided as an overview of and topical guide to the history of South Asia:History of South Asia – South Asia includes the contemporary political entities of India, Pakistan, Bangladesh, Nepal, Afghanistan, Bhutan, and the island nations of Sri Lanka and the Maldives.ChronologyJames Mill (1773–1836), in his The History of British India (1817), distinguished three phases in the history of India, namely Hindu, Muslim and British civilisations. This periodisation has been influential, but has also been criticised for the misconceptions it gave rise to.

The striatum, or corpus striatum (also called the striate nucleus), is a nucleus (a cluster of neurons) in the subcortical basal ganglia of the forebrain. The striatum is a critical component of the motor and reward systems; receives glutamatergic and dopaminergic inputs from different sources; and serves as the primary input to the rest of the basal ganglia.Functionally, the striatum coordinates multiple aspects of cognition, including both motor and action planning, decision-making, motivation, reinforcement, and reward perception. The striatum is made up of the caudate nucleus and the lentiform nucleus.

Milan Kundera (, ; born 1 April 1929) is a Czech writer who went into exile in France in 1975, becoming a naturalised French citizen in 1981. Kundera's Czechoslovak citizenship was revoked in 1979; he received his Czech citizenship in 2019. He "sees himself as a French writer and insists his work should be studied as French literature and classified as such in book stores".Kundera's best-known work is The Unbearable Lightness of Being. Prior to the Velvet Revolution of 1989, the communist régime in Czechoslovakia banned his books. He leads a low-profile life and rarely speaks to the media.

Year 926 (CMXXVI) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  Spring – The Italian nobles turn against King Rudolph II of Burgundy and request that Hugh of Provence, the effective ruler of Lower Burgundy, be elected as king of Italy. Rudolph's father-in-law Duke Burchard II of Swabia is ambushed and killed near Novara, by the henchmen of Archbishop Lambert of Milan. Rudolph, disillusioned by the news, returns to Burgundy to protect himself. Hugh has himself crowned King of Italy.

A seed is an embryonic plant enclosed in a protective outer covering. The formation of the seed is part of the process of reproduction in seed plants, the spermatophytes, including the gymnosperm and angiosperm plants.Seeds are the product of the ripened ovule, after fertilization by pollen and some growth within the mother plant. The embryo develops from the zygote, and the seed coat from the integuments of the ovule. Seeds have been an important development in the reproduction and success of gymnosperm and angiosperm plants, relative to more primitive plants such as ferns, mosses and liverworts, which do not have seeds and use water-dependent means to propagate themselves.

Year 1036 ( MXXXVI ) was a leap year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) during the year 1036 CE. The year began on a Thursday at 0400, the beginning of the  Julian calendar.The Julian calendar was eventually replaced by the Gregorian calendar and has been in common use since the mid-19th century. Jazz guitar is a popular form of American popular music. It began in Harlem, New York, in the late 1930s; by 1939 it had become a popular form of American pop music in the United States, Britain, Europe and Latin America.

A half reaction ( or half-cell reaction ) is either the oxidation or reduction reaction component of a redox reaction, the latter being known as a quinoxyl radical (Q.R.). The reaction is described in its oxidation half-reaction , where the reduction half-reaction describes the opposite reaction, where the oxidation of the reducing agent converts an acid to an alkaline, reducing solution. In mathematics, a group is a collection of entities of an algebraic structure (sometimes called a structure), together with associated properties or operations. General group theory is the branch of mathematics concerned with group representations and group operations on those representations.

Avignon ( , ; ; or , ; ) is the prefecture of the Vaucluse department in the Provence-Alpes-Côte d'Azur department of France, and the capital city of the Alpes-Maritimes region.Vaucluse is one of the regions most heavily affected by earthquakes, mainly the Alpes-Maritimes, which is the only part of France that has such a level of seismic risk.The prefecture is the administrative centre for the region of Provence-Alpes-Côte d'Azur and includes the Alpes-Maritimes.The Alpes-Maritimes region is the second most populous in France, the most populated of the Western Provence region (after Provence) and the second most populated province in France after Alsace-Lorraine.

Chrysippus of Soli (; , ;  ) was a Greek Stoic philosopher. He was a native of Soli, Cilicia, but moved to Athens as a young man, where he became a pupil of Cleanthes in the Stoic school. When Cleanthes died, around 230 BC, Chrysippus became the third head of the school. A prolific writer, Chrysippus expanded the fundamental doctrines of Zeno of Citium, the founder of the school, which earned him the title of Second Founder of Stoicism.Chrysippus excelled in logic, the theory of knowledge, ethics, and physics.

SPARC ( Scalable Processor Architecture ) is a reduced instruction set computing ( RISC ) instruction set architecture originally developed by DEC and later licensed to the XScale Technologies. Scalable Processor Architecture (SPA) supports a large number of processor threads at the same time.SPA was an evolution of XScale's earlier instruction set processor (ISA) RISC instruction set architecture, which also supported a large number of processor threads, but at significantly higher latency and lower performance than SPA.Early development and designThe original design was created by XScale Technologies in 1987 under the auspices of DEC's Computer Systems Division.

New Zealand consists of more than six hundred islands, mainly remnants of a larger land mass now beneath the sea. New Zealand is the seventh-largest island nation on earth, and the third-largest located entirely in the Southern Hemisphere. The following is a list of islands of New Zealand.Each of the two largest islands – where most of the human population lives – has two official names, in English and in the Māori language. They are the North Island or Te Ika-a-Māui and the South Island or Te Waipounamu. Various Māori iwi sometimes use other names, with some preferring to call the South Island Te Waka o Aoraki.

The Himalayas , or Himalaya ( ; Sanskrit : , `` snow '' , `` dwelling '' , `` abode ''), also known simply as the Himalayas or the Himalaya region, is the highest region of the earth. It includes the northernmost region of Eurasia and the highest mountain range in the world, known as the Hindu Kush Mountains. It spans roughly from south to north from the eastern boundary of the Tibetan plateau, in China, to the western boundary of the Bhutan Himalayas, in Nepal.The Himalayas range roughly from north to south from south-west to north-east.

Ravenna ( , , also ; ) is the capital city of the Province of Ravenna, in the Emilia-Romagna region of Northern Italy. It was the capital city of the Western Roman Empire from 402 until the empire collapsed in 476. It then served as the capital of the Ostrogothic Kingdom until it was re-conquered in 540 by the Byzantine Empire. Afterwards, the city formed the centre of the Byzantine Exarchate of Ravenna until the last exarch was executed by the Lombards in 751.Although it is an inland city, Ravenna is connected to the Adriatic Sea by the Candiano Canal.

The IAI RQ-5 Hunter unmanned aerial vehicle (UAV) was originally intended to serve as the United States Army's Short Range UAV system for division and corps commanders. It took off and landed (using arresting gear) on runways. It used a gimbaled EO/IR sensor to relay its video in real time via a second airborne Hunter over a C-band line-of-sight data link. The RQ-5 is based on the Hunter UAV that was developed by Israel Aerospace Industries.Design and developmentSystem acquisition and training started in 1994 but production was cancelled in 1996 due to concerns over program mismanagement.

The European Men's Handball Championship is the official competition for senior men's national handball teams of Europe and takes place every two years since 1994, in the even-numbered year between the World Championship. In addition to crowning the European champions, the tournament also serves as a qualifying tournament for the Olympic Games and World Championship. The most successful team is Sweden who have won five titles. Spain, however, have won most medals.HistoryIn 1946, the International Handball Federation was founded by eight European nations, and though non-European nations competed at the World Championships, the medals had always been taken by European nations.

Metaphone is a phonetic algorithm, published by Lawrence Philips in 1990, for indexing words by their English pronunciation. It fundamentally improves on the Soundex algorithm by using information about variations and inconsistencies in English spelling and pronunciation to produce a more accurate encoding, which does a better job of matching words and names which sound similar. As with Soundex, similar-sounding words should share the same keys. Metaphone is available as a built-in operator in a number of systems.Philips later produced a new version of the algorithm, which he named Double Metaphone.

Hoysala architecture is the building style in Hindu temple architecture developed under the rule of the Hoysala Empire between the 11th and 14th centuries, in the region known today as Karnataka, a state of India. Hoysala influence was at its peak in the 13th century, when it dominated the Southern Deccan Plateau region. Large and small temples built during this era remain as examples of the Hoysala architectural style, including the Chennakesava Temple at Belur, the Hoysaleswara Temple at Halebidu, and the Kesava Temple at Somanathapura. Other examples of Hoysala craftsmanship are the temples at Belavadi, Amruthapura, Hosaholalu, Mosale, Arasikere, Basaralu, Kikkeri and Nuggehalli.

Stephanie Lynn Nicks ( born May 26 , 1948 ) is an American singer , songwriter , and producer known for writing and performing the Grammy Award winning songs "Walk on the Wild Side" (1963), "Free Fallin'" (1967), and "Wish You Were Here" (1974), the film soundtrack for which she wrote the lyrics. She has also produced the music for television shows such as The Love Boat and The Dick Van Dyke Show.Nicks also served as producer on the film Star Trek: First Contact (1994), for which she did not write a song.

Brighella (in Bergamasque dialect: Brighèla) is a comic, masked character from the Italian theatre style Commedia dell'arte. His early costume consisted of loosely fitting, white smock and pants with green trim and was often equipped with a  (also  or , depending on region) or slap stick, or else with a wooden sword. Later he took to wearing a sort of livery with a matching cape. He wore a greenish half-mask (traditionally olive-green) displaying a look of preternatural lust and greed. It is distinguished by a hook nose and thick lips, along with a thick twirled mustache to give him an offensive characteristic.

Squid are cephalopods in the superorder Decapodiformes with elongated bodies , large eyes , eight arms and two tentacles . The most commonly seen species of squid, the giant squid, is the largest invertebrate animal in the world.
