It lies in the Arctic Circle and forms an arc connecting the Arctic Ocean with the North Atlantic and North Pacific Oceans. The Arctic Ocean is the most northerly of all the oceans of Earth and is the most sparsely populated ocean area on Earth.

Giovanni Paisiello (or Paesiello; 9 May 1740 – 5 June 1816) was an Italian composer of the Classical era, and was the most popular opera composer of the late 1700s. His operatic style influenced Mozart and Rossini, and his music was championed by Haydn and Beethoven.LifePaisiello was born in Taranto in the Apulia region and educated by the Jesuits there. He became known for his beautiful singing voice and in 1754 was sent to the Conservatorio di S. Onofrio at Naples, where he studied under Francesco Durante, and eventually became assistant master.

was the 68th emperor of Japan, according to the traditional order of succession.Go-Ichijō's reign spanned the years from 1016 through 1036.This 11th century sovereign was named after Emperor Ichijō and go- (後), translates literally as "later;" and thus, he is sometimes called the "Later Emperor Ichijō", or, in some older sources, may be identified as " Emperor Ichijō, the second. "BiographyBefore his ascension to the Chrysanthemum Throne, his personal name (imina) was Atsuhira -shinnō (敦成親王). He was also known as Atsunari-shinnō.Atsuhira was the second son of Emperor Ichijō.

The Illustrated Man is a 1951 collection of 18 science fiction short stories by American writer Ray Bradbury. A recurring theme throughout the stories is the conflict of the cold mechanics of technology and the psychology of people. It was nominated for the International Fantasy Award in 1952.The unrelated stories are tied together by the frame story of "The Illustrated Man", a vagrant former member of a carnival freak show with an extensively tattooed body whom the unnamed narrator meets. The man's tattoos, allegedly created by a time-traveling woman, are individually animated, and each tells a different tale.

Mercury (;  ) is a major god in Roman religion and mythology, being one of the 12 Dii Consentes within the ancient Roman pantheon. He is the god of financial gain, commerce, eloquence, messages, communication (including divination), travelers, boundaries, luck, trickery, and thieves; he also serves as the guide of souls to the underworld.In Roman mythology, he was considered to be either the son of Maia, one of the seven daughters of the Titan Atlas, and Jupiter, or of Caelus and Dies.

Gender is the range of characteristics pertaining to femininity and masculinity and differentiating between them. Depending on the context, this may include sex-based social structures (i.e. gender roles) and gender identity. Most cultures use a gender binary, having two genders (boys/men and girls/women); those who exist outside these groups may fall under the umbrella term non-binary. Some societies have specific genders besides "man" and "woman", such as the hijras of South Asia; these are often referred to as third genders (and fourth genders, etc.).

The Stone Roses were an English rock band formed in Manchester in 1983 . One of the pioneering groups of punk rock and the first of the English alternative groups to use a studio, the band became an international sensation when they released their eponymous debut album in 1984 and became the first British band to achieve worldwide commercial success when the album went gold in the United States. It also won the first ever British single of the year, " I'm With You ", as well as a Grammy Award for Best New Artist and Best Rock Album.

The M109 is an American 155 mm turreted self-propelled howitzer, first introduced in the early 1960s to replace the M44. It has been upgraded a number of times, most recently to the M109A7. The M109 family is the most common Western indirect-fire support weapon of maneuver brigades of armored and mechanized infantry divisions.The M109 has a crew of four: the section chief/commander, the driver, the gunner, and the ammunition handler/loader. The chief or gunner aims the cannon left or right (deflection) and up and down (quadrant).The British Army replaced its M109s with the AS-90.

The Boeing CH-47 Chinook is a tandem rotor helicopter developed by American rotorcraft company Vertol and manufactured by Boeing Vertol from 1981 to 2005. The helicopter was developed as a low-altitude and slow-speed transport helicopter for use by military and civil personnel. It was primarily used by U.S. and Canadian armed services. The Boeing KC-10 Extender is a commercial fixed-wing long-range transport aircraft designed to transport up to nine passengers. The aircraft is used for aerial refueling in remote areas and to carry cargo, personnel, and other equipment to the airfield in remote areas. The aircraft is powered by one or more Pratt & Whitney R-2700 turboshaft engines.

Pope John XXII ( ; 1244 – 4 December 1334 ) , born Jacques Duèze ( or d'Euse ) , was a Franciscan missionary priest and member of the papal Council of the Lateran in the Lateran Cathedral. He was the nephew of Louis IX of France, and later King of France. His father was John of Navarre, a son of Louis the Pious and Marie of Valois.Early lifeand educationEarly yearsHe was born in Nîmes on 13 July 1244. He went to the Dominican Order in Navarre, and then to the College of Nîmes.

Sparta ( Doric Greek : Σπάρτα , Spártā ; Attic Greek : Σπάρτη , Spártē ) was a prominent city-state during the Roman Empire and first part of Western Roman Empire, situated on the Dnieper River near modern-day Chernihiv. It was known as Sparta until the 4th century. It was the second-largest and the most important Roman provincial town of the 1st century, after Rome. It was founded in the 3rd and 3rd centuries by the Romans as a colony of Greek colonists, and became the most important place of Greek cultural influence. Its name was derived from the word "sparta", meaning "stone".

Year 930 ( CMXXX ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) and finishing on Sunday.The year 930 is a century that is the first one without a new moon, with the year ending in a leap year. It is also the first in the Common Era , the millennium in the Julian calendar.The year 930 marked the return to the Gregorian calendar in Western Christendom, which was superseded by the Julian calendar in 1452. Edmond de Vigenere (; 4 November 1715 – 21 December 1797) was a Belgian statesman.

The Buran program (, , "Snowstorm", "Blizzard"), also known as the "VKK Space Orbiter programme" , was a Soviet and later Russian reusable spacecraft project that began in 1974 at the Central Aerohydrodynamic Institute in Moscow and was formally suspended in 1993. In addition to being the designation for the whole Soviet/Russian reusable spacecraft project, Buran was also the name given to Orbiter K1, which completed one uncrewed spaceflight in 1988 and was the only Soviet reusable spacecraft to be launched into space. The Buran-class orbiters used the expendable Energia rocket as a launch vehicle.

Year 1025 (MXXV) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  December 15 – Byzantine Emperor Basil II ("Bulgar Slayer") dies in Constantinople after a 50-year reign. Never married, he is succeeded by his brother and co-emperor Constantine VIII who becomes sole ruler of the Byzantine Empire. Constantine calls the Sicilian invasion off. Catapan Basil Boioannes diverts the Byzantine expeditionary force already assembled on Calabria to join the siege of Capua. Europe  April 18 – Bolesław I the Brave is crowned in Gniezno as the first king of Poland.

The PDP-7 was a minicomputer produced by Digital Equipment Corporation as part of the PDP series. Introduced in 1964, shipped since 1965, it was the first to use their Flip-Chip technology. With a cost of , it was cheap but powerful by the standards of the time. The PDP-7 is the third of Digital's 18-bit machines, with essentially the same instruction set architecture as the PDP-4 and the PDP-9.HardwareThe PDP-7 was the first wire-wrapped PDP. The computer had a memory cycle time of  and an add time of . I/O included a keyboard, printer, paper-tape and dual transport DECtape drives (type 555).

Kevin James Anderson (born March 27, 1962) is an American science fiction author. He has written spin-off novels for Star Wars, StarCraft, Titan A.E. and The X-Files, and with Brian Herbert is the co-author of the Dune prequel series. His original works include the Saga of Seven Suns series and the Nebula Award-nominated Assemblers of Infinity. He has also written several comic books, including the Dark Horse Star Wars series Tales of the Jedi written in collaboration with Tom Veitch, Dark Horse Predator titles, and The X-Files titles for Topps.

A radionuclide ( radioactive nuclide , radioisotope or radioactive isotope ) is a nuclide that has excess nuclear energy , called excess energy , that cannot be directly released into the environment because its energy is used to initiate or sustain radioactive decay, rather than being used by the nucleus to initiate or sustain spontaneous fission, or simply to increase the energy of its nucleus. This is a common feature in most elements (except for beryllium-10), with the exception of iodine-131 in thorium-232. The term "radiation" is used when the excess nuclear energy is radiated, for instance, in the form of gamma-ray bursts.

The putamen ( ; from Latin , meaning `` nutshell '' ) is a round structure located at the base of the brain and located at the bottom of the frontal lobe, just above the forehead. It is one of the most frequently investigated regions in neuroanatomical studies of human brain development. Its function is unknown but it has been proposed to be related to emotional processing and empathy, and it plays a role in several psychiatric disorders, such as anxiety, mood disorders, schizophrenia, and ADHD. It is the largest structure in the brain, and the largest volume of the brain is contained within its ventricles.

Eagle is the common name for many large birds of prey of the family Accipitridae . Eagles belong to several families of the order Theropodidae. An eagle is an extremely large raptor with wingspans up to a meter (3.3 ft), including its feet, that has been known to weigh as much as 5 tons (4.3 metric tonnes). In its native North America, the bald eagle is considered to be one of the most dangerous predators in North America, and one of the three most endangered raptors (along with the osprey and the California condor) worldwide.

Lumbar disc disease is the drying out of the spongy interior matrix of an intervertebral disc in the spine. Many physicians and patients use the term lumbar disc disease to encompass several different causes of back pain or sciatica. In this article, the term is used to describe a lumbar herniated disc. It is thought that lumbar disc disease causes about one-third of all back pain.SymptomsPain, loss of muscle strength and loss of touch sensation may occur if this herniation causes the compression of the most proximal part of the nerve closely neighbouring the intervertebral disc material.

Theodoret of Cyrus or Cyrrhus (;  AD 393 –  458/466) was an influential theologian of the School of Antioch, biblical commentator, and Christian bishop of Cyrrhus (423–457). He played a pivotal role in several 5th-century Byzantine Church controversies that led to various ecumenical acts and schisms. He wrote against Cyril of Alexandria's 12 Anathemas which were sent to Nestorius and did not personally condemn Nestorius until the Council of Chalcedon. His writings against Cyril were included in the Three Chapters Controversy and were condemned at the Second Council of Constantinople.

The Maunder Minimum , also known as the `` prolonged sunspot minimum '' , was a period around 1645 to 1715 in the northern hemisphere during which solar activity was relatively low. It is one of several periodic solar cycles, the others being the Sunspot number cycle, Sunspot cycle 23, and Sunspot cycle 27. Medievalism is an academic term that derives from the French term "medievale", meaning "learned" and "civilized", originally coined in the seventeenth century to denote the intellectual and cultural tradition in the Renaissance period.

William I (Willem Frederik, Prince of Orange-Nassau; 24 August 1772 – 12 December 1843) was a Prince of Orange, the King of the Netherlands and Grand Duke of Luxembourg.He was the son of the last Stadtholder of the Dutch Republic, who went into exile to London in 1795 because of the Batavian Revolution. As compensation for the loss of all his father's possessions in the Low Countries, an agreement was concluded between France and Prussia in which William was appointed ruler of the newly created Principality of Nassau-Orange-Fulda in 1803; this was however short-lived and in 1806 he was deposed by Napoleon.

Bristol  is a city, ceremonial county and unitary authority in England. Situated on the River Avon, it is bordered by the ceremonial counties of Gloucestershire, to the north; and Somerset, to the south. Bristol is the most populous city in South West England.The wider Bristol Built-up Area is the eleventh most populous urban area in the United Kingdom.Iron Age hill forts and Roman villas were built near the confluence of the rivers Frome and Avon, and around the beginning of the 11th century, the settlement was known as Brycgstow (Old English "the place at the bridge").

The Alcubierre drive , Alcubierre warp drive , or Alcubierre metric ( referring to metric tensor ) , is a theoretical electromagnetic propulsion scheme proposed in the 1980s. It posits that an accelerated, relativistic particle is capable of using its own internal gravitational field to propel it in any direction, and that such an engine could create the desired acceleration for a specified speed. The proposed method was first published in 1987, with further developments by D. A. Landau in 1990. The drive is based on a concept first proposed by Dutch physicist Frank Wilczek in 1970.

Depleted uranium ( DU ; also referred to in the past as Q-metal , depletalloy or D-38 ) is uranium oxide that has been depleted to one-sixth its original weight, and is therefore inert and highly toxic. In the military, it is used primarily as armor piercing ammunition and as the explosive payload in artillery shells and anti-armor rockets. DU is also used in rocket propelled grenades, bombs, and other projectiles intended for use against ground targets. DU is the most widely used of the non-fissile nuclear materials, used in more than 80 countries and used in all types of munitions except nuclear submarines.

was the 75th emperor of Japan, according to the traditional order of succession.Sutoku's reign spanned the years from 1123 through 1142.GenealogyBefore his ascension to the Chrysanthemum Throne, his personal name (his imina) was Akihito (顕仁). Sutoku was the eldest son of Emperor Toba. Some old texts say he was instead the son of Toba's grandfather, Emperor Shirakawa.Chūgū: Fujiwara no Kiyoko (藤原 聖子) later Kōkamon'in (皇嘉門院), Fujiwara Tadamichi’s daughter Hyounosuke-no-Tsubone (兵衛佐局), Minamoto Masamune's adopted daughter First son: Imperial  (1140–1162).

Year 1068 (MLXVIII) was a leap year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  January 1 – Empress Eudokia Makrembolitissa, wife of the late Emperor Constantine X, marries General Romanos Diogenes (a member of a prominent Cappadocian family) – who is proclaimed co-emperor as Romanos IV of the Byzantine Empire. Autumn – Romanos IV begins a campaign against the Seljuk Turks, leading a Byzantine expeditionary force (which is in poor condition). He is successful in recapturing the fortress city of Hieropolis (modern-day Manbij) near Aleppo in northern Syria.

Turtles are an order of reptiles known as Testudines, characterized by a shell developed mainly from their ribs. Modern turtles are divided into two major groups, the side-necked turtles and hidden neck turtles which differ in the way the head retracts. There are 360 living and recently extinct species of turtles, including tortoises and terrapins. They are found on most continents, some islands and much of the ocean. Like other reptiles, birds, and mammals, they breathe air and do not lay eggs underwater, although many species live in or around water.

Hilbert's paradox of the Grand Hotel  (colloquial: Infinite Hotel Paradox or Hilbert's Hotel) is a thought experiment which illustrates a counterintuitive property of infinite sets. It is demonstrated that a fully occupied hotel with infinitely many rooms may still accommodate additional guests, even infinitely many of them, and this process may be repeated infinitely often. The idea was introduced by David Hilbert in a 1924 lecture "Über das Unendliche", reprinted in , and was popularized through George Gamow's 1947 book One Two Three... Infinity.The paradoxConsider a hypothetical hotel with a countably infinite number of rooms, all of which are occupied.

William Harrison Riker ( September 22 , 1920 – June 26 , 1993 ) was an American political scientist who specialized in American foreign policy. Riker was born in St. Louis, Missouri. George W. Bush's father, George Herbert Walker Bush Sr., was a US Senator from Texas from 1973 to 1979, the second son of Prescott Bush. The George W. Bush Presidential Center, formerly located on the campus of Texas Southern University (now Southern Methodist University), is a university-run educational and research facility situated in downtown Dallas, Texas, and is administered by the Texas Southern University Foundation.

In linguistics , an adjective ( abbreviated ) is a word that modifies a noun or noun phrase or describes the quality of a noun, and describes what the adjective is denoting. The word is defined as part of a more general noun or noun phrase.The most common adjective is "attractive" which refers to a person, object, place, situation or quality.An adjective is usually not a noun, but may be an adverb modifying the noun or adjective.The adjectival form of the word is often written as adjective – noun.Adjectives may be combined to form larger, compound words.

The Bell UH-1 Iroquois (nicknamed "Huey") is a utility military helicopter powered by a single turboshaft engine, with two-bladed main and tail rotors. The first member of the prolific Huey family, it was developed by Bell Helicopter to meet a 1952 US Army requirement for a medical evacuation and utility helicopter, and first flew in 1956. The UH-1 was the first turbine-powered helicopter produced for the United States military, and more than 16,000 have been built since 1960.The Iroquois was originally designated HU-1, hence the Huey nickname, which has remained in common use, despite the official redesignation to UH-1 in 1962.

was the 70th emperor of Japan , according to the traditional order of succession.Go-Reizei 's reign spanned the years 1045–1068.This monarch was the first emperor of Japan to rule from a Buddhist shrine; however, his coronation was the first coronation in centuries to take place on a new capital built in Kyoto, an important Buddhist centre. Gödel's final proof of the correctness of the Gödelian incompleteness theorems  of set theory. The proof is in a proof of the Gödel conjecture of set theory that has not yet been published, but appeared in the proceedings of one of the Gödel conferences.

Barbecue or barbeque (informally BBQ in the UK and US, barbie in Australia and braai in South Africa) is a term used with significant regional and national variations to describe various cooking methods which use live fire and smoke to cook the food. The term is also generally applied to the devices associated with those methods, the broader cuisines that these methods produce, and the meals or gatherings at which this style of food is cooked and served. The cooking methods associated with barbecuing vary significantly but most involve outdoor cooking.The various regional variations of barbecue can be broadly categorized into those methods which use direct and those which use indirect heating.

The National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration (NOAA  ) is an American scientific and regulatory agency within the United States Department of Commerce that forecasts weather, monitors oceanic and atmospheric conditions, charts the seas, conducts deep sea exploration, and manages fishing and protection of marine mammals and endangered species in the U.S. exclusive economic zone.Purpose and functionNOAA's specific roles include: Supplying Environmental Information Products. NOAA supplies to its customers and partners information pertaining to the state of the oceans and the atmosphere, such as weather warnings and forecasts via the National Weather Service. NOAA's information services extend as well to climate, ecosystems, and commerce.

Dekker's algorithm is the first known correct solution to the mutual exclusion problem in concurrent programming. The solution is attributed to Dutch mathematician Th. J. Dekker by Edsger W. Dijkstra in an unpublished paper on sequential process descriptions and his manuscript on cooperating sequential processes. It allows two threads to share a single-use resource without conflict, using only shared memory for communication.It avoids the strict alternation of a naïve turn-taking algorithm, and was one of the first mutual exclusion algorithms to be invented.OverviewIf two processes attempt to enter a critical section at the same time, the algorithm will allow only one process in, based on whose turn it is.

Phenylalanine ( symbol Phe or F ) is an essential α-amino acid with the formula . It can be viewed as the building block of proteins.Phenylalanine serves as an intermediate in amino acid transport in living cells, in particular the transport of ammonia and nitrite (NH 3 ) into the blood. Philips (; , ; , ) is a global leader in television, home entertainment and digital broadcasting. The company is headquartered in Eindhoven, and operates in more than 60 countries, and is listed on the Amsterdam and Hong Kong stock exchanges.

The Bussard ramjet is a theoretical method of spacecraft propulsion proposed in 1960 by the physicist Robert W. Bussard , and named after the mathematician, physicist and philosopher who formulated the equation of motion involved. It uses a device called a ramjet to move propellant, usually an ionized propellant mixture, through an ionized plasma. Bussard ramjet propulsion was originally designed to propel ion engines for rocketry, and later to power a satellite in orbit around the planet Earth, but it could be adapted to propel spacecraft beyond low Earth orbit, for example as a means of interstellar travel.

The Bell OH-58 Kiowa is a family of single-engine , single-rotor , military helicopters used for observation , utility , and tactical roles. It is a twin-engine helicopter with a tandem rotor design that was developed and manufactured by Lockheed in cooperation with the United States Army Air Force (USAAF). The Bell OH-58A Kiowa is the American designation and designation for the helicopter.The first prototype of the OH-58A Kiowa was completed in 1969 and flew its first flight the same year. A total of 19 prototypes were produced from 1970 through 1973 with the first three production models being delivered in 1978.

The Northrop Grumman RQ-4 Global Hawk is a high-altitude, remotely-piloted surveillance aircraft. It was initially designed by Ryan Aeronautical (now part of Northrop Grumman), and known as Tier II+ during development. The RQ-4 provides a broad overview and systematic surveillance using high-resolution synthetic aperture radar (SAR) and electro-optical/infrared (EO/IR) sensors with long loiter times over target areas. It can survey as much as  of terrain per day, an area the size of South Korea or Iceland.The Global Hawk is operated by the United States Air Force (USAF).

In mathematics , a Möbius strip , band , or loop ( , ; ) , also spelled Mobius or band, is an irregularly-arranged, continuous and continuous line segment, formed by the repeated crossing of two perpendicular line segments, usually of equal length but sometimes with different lengths. Möbius strips are frequently found in geology, biology and mathematics. In mathematics, a Möbius strip is the sum of all the Möbius sets.Möbius strips can be described in more detail. For simplicity, they are often represented with a simple rectangle with three points on the length axis.

The year 2000 in Israel and Palestine marked the beginning of the al-Aqsa Intifada leading to a number of Palestinian and Israeli deaths.TimelineJanuary - 28 September (12 Palestinians)Up to 28 September 12 Palestinian were killed by the Israeli army in the occupied territories.February (death toll: 3, all of which Israeli civilians)  February 9: Dov and Gabriella Weiss of Giv'at Ze'ev, an Israeli settlement outside of Jerusalem, were found bludgeoned to death in their home. Police confirmed the attack was by militants.September (death toll: 19 - 17 Palestinians, 2 Israeli military forces)  September 27: an Israeli soldier killed in Gaza Strip.

Year 1164 ( MCLXIV ) was a leap year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) with no days before or after March 20th. In addition, the months of March, April, and May have no days in the month. The Middle East was a part of the Mediterranean Basin during the Greco-Roman period of antiquity, from about the 5th century BCE until approximately the 1st century CE. It was divided in roughly the following fashion: Egypt, Syria, Jordan, Lebanon, Israel, and the Gaza Strip.

Keep the Aspidistra Flying , first published in 1936 , is a socially critical novel by George Orwell . It was written in 1936 as a critique of totalitarianism and as part of a political project called 'Animal Farm'. It was published when Orwell's politics had begun to align with that of Trotsky and Stalin and as a prelude to the writing of his novel 1984.In the novel, a small group of animals escape from a totalitarian state run by pigs in a farm-like setting called Aspidistra, where they live in idleness and ignorance.

In chemistry, a nucleophile is a chemical species that forms bonds with electrophiles by donating an electron pair. All molecules and ions with a free pair of electrons or at least one pi bond can act as nucleophiles. Because nucleophiles donate electrons, they are Lewis bases. Nucleophilic describes the affinity of a nucleophile to bond with positively charged atomic nuclei. Nucleophilicity, sometimes referred to as nucleophile strength, refers to a substance's nucleophilic character and is often used to compare the affinity of atoms. Neutral nucleophilic reactions with solvents such as alcohols and water are named solvolysis.

Indonesian is the official language of Indonesia . It is a standardized variety of Malay , an Austronesian language that shares the same language family as Malay, Austronesian, and Sinhalese. It has many features of both of these languages, including phonology, syntax, writing, and pronunciation. The history of a nation or region is the story of events that take place in a particular area or time, and how they influenced and changed the development of the people and culture of that area or time. History is recorded from the beginning of time up until the present day by written records.

Psilocybin is a naturally occurring psychedelic prodrug compound produced by more than 200 species of fungi . The most potent species is Amanita muscaria, which contains psilocin and psilocybin. It is used in a number of ways, but is most commonly used as an entheogen and as a psychoactive component of the magic mushroom (Mycena). In mathematics, a line segment (also called a segment) is the segment of a polygon, or a polygon's segment of the plane that is bisected by the polygon. A polygon can be divided into two segments that are a unit circle.

Bristol is a city , ceremonial county and unitary authority in England . Situated on the River Avon , it is bordered by Wiltshire, Buckinghamshire and Buckinghamshire County. The city is located at the northern end of Bristol, at the northern end of the river Avon. Bristol has a population of around 723,000, and is England's fifth largest city by population. Brussels is a city, administrative unit and one of the EU's four permanent members, and is its capital and largest city. It is located at the heart of the European Union .

Giovanni Pacini (17 February 17966 December 1867) was an Italian composer, best known for his operas. Pacini was born in Catania, Sicily, the son of the buffo Luigi Pacini, who was to appear in the premieres of many of Giovanni's operas. The family was of Tuscan origin, living in Catania when the composer was born.His first 25 or so operas were written when Gioachino Rossini dominated the Italian operatic stage. But Pacini's operas were "rather superficial", a fact which, later, he candidly admitted in his Memoirs.

Classless Inter-Domain Routing (CIDR ) is a method for allocating IP addresses and for IP routing. The Internet Engineering Task Force introduced CIDR in 1993 to replace the previous classful network addressing architecture on the Internet. Its goal was to slow the growth of routing tables on routers across the Internet, and to help slow the rapid exhaustion of IPv4 addresses.IP addresses are described as consisting of two groups of bits in the address: the most significant bits are the network prefix, which identifies a whole network or subnet, and the least significant set forms the host identifier, which specifies a particular interface of a host on that network.

William Tyndale (; sometimes spelled Tynsdale, Tindall, Tindill, Tyndall;  – ) was an English biblical scholar and linguist who became a leading figure in the Protestant Reformation in the years leading up to his execution. He is well known as a translator of the Bible into English, and was influenced by the works of prominent Protestant Reformers such as Erasmus of Rotterdam and Martin Luther.Tyndale's translation of the Bible was used for subsequent English translations, including the Great Bible and the Bishops' Bible, authorized by the Church of England.

Year 874 ( DCCCLXXIV ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Monday, October 23, 875. The year 875 was declared by the pope as having the same year as the year 872 of the Greek Empire. The year was recognized in Greece and Italy in 871. Danish ( ; ;  ,  ,  , ) is a Baltic language spoken on the islands of the North Sea (Denmark and Greenland). The native language of Denmark is modern Danish, but is closely related to Old Norse and Old High German.

The bowline ( or ) is an ancient and simple knot used to form a fixed loop at the end of a rope, used to fasten or tie to a fixed object. Bowlines are primarily used for fishing. Barley (; ; ) is a grass-based cereal that originated in Western Eurasia, though it is now also cultivated in parts of Africa, the Middle East and North America, and is widely used in North America in baked goods such as breads, cakes, crackers, pancakes, doughnuts, waffles, pastry and breadsticks.

Monte Cassino ( today usually spelled Montecassino ) is a rocky hill about southeast of Rome , in the Latin-speaking part of Italy. It was named after the Roman general Cassius Marcellus and the town of Montecassino, in Italy, where he fought his most famous battles.The name "Cassino" derives from the Romano-British word "cassino", meaning "red hill". Calories are an essential measure of how much energy is available in the body, used by the body's various systems to perform physical and chemical tasks, such as generating heat and chemical reactions.

William I ( Willem Frederik , Prince of Orange-Nassau ; 24 August 1772 – 12 December 1843 ) was a Dutch politician and a member of the first Royal Dutch Republic.He was the youngest of two sons of King Willem II of the Netherlands and Princess Caroline of Hoek van Holland. He attended the Royal Military Academy at Krommenie, but did not graduate in 1796 and took part in a military campaign in the West Indies in 1797. After the death of King William IV, he was made regent of the Dutch colony of New Amsterdam.

A complex system is a system composed of many components which may interact with each other . Examples of complex systems include biology, society, the natural world and human health and well-being. Complex systems include ecosystems, economic systems, organizations (e.g. governments), and biological and social interactions. Complexity is a measure of how many parts or components of a system are involved in the interaction, and how they interact together. Computers are used in almost all areas of daily life. They perform a variety of tasks, from simple arithmetic and word-processing to complex calculations and complex mathematics.

Pope Leo XI (; 2 June 153527 April 1605), born Alessandro Ottaviano de' Medici, was head of the Catholic Church and ruler of the Papal States from 1 April 1605 to his death. His pontificate is one of the briefest in history, having lasted under a month. He was from the prominent House of Medici originating from Florence. Medici's mother opposed his entering the priesthood and sought to prevent it by having him given secular honours, but after her death he eventually was ordained a priest in 1567.

Strasbourg ( , , ; ; , ) is the prefecture and largest city of the Grand Est region of Burgundy and one of the principal metropolitan administrative districts of Burgundy, occupying the northeastern end of the Rhône Valley. Its location along the river Rhône helps in the transport of goods to Burgundy's ports in France and the Channel Islands. Its capital and largest city is Strasbourg. As the seat of the regional government, Strasbourg is the administrative centre of Burgundy and the region's economic, cultural and administrative centre, and the economic hub of Burgundy, France.

In the administrative divisions of France , the department is one of the three levels of government under the national executive: "administration" is a term used to describe the various governmental and administrative functions in a particular administrative division of France.Administrative divisions within France are grouped into administrative divisions into which a region of France, such as Île-de-France or Languedoc, can be divided. Alcohol is a psychoactive substance (a psychoactive agent that affects the body, mind, or emotions) which is used as either a drug or a recreational substance. Alcohol is a beverage that may be consumed by itself or with other food and drink.

In their most common sense , the terms thought and thinking refer to conscious cognitive processes that can happen independently of the brain's ability to understand and generate them, and are not restricted to conscious, intentional, intentional-seeming activity. Other definitions may include thinking in terms of motor, sensory, sensory-motor, cognitive-motor or sensory-cognitive processes that are independent of the brain's ability to process them, or thinking in terms of mental representations or concepts in the brain.A thought is a state or change that a person or animal may experience when they think about one or more stimuli.

Giuseppe Saverio Raffaele Mercadante (baptised 17 September 179517 December 1870) was an Italian composer, particularly of operas. While Mercadante may not have retained the international celebrity of Gaetano Donizetti or Gioachino Rossini beyond his own lifetime, he composed as prolific a number of works as either; and his development of operatic structures, melodic styles and orchestration contributed significantly to the foundations upon which Giuseppe Verdi built his dramatic technique.BiographyEarly yearsMercadante was born illegitimate in Altamura, near Bari in Apulia; his precise date of birth has not been recorded, but he was baptised on 17 September 1795.

A finger is a limb of the body and a type of digit , an organ of manipulation and sensation. The three-toed sloth shares many physical features with its closely related cousin, the lemur, but its fingers are smaller and have three toes instead of four. In addition to being the largest living primates, sloths are also the only living relatives of modern humans, as their common ancestor lived some 200,000 years ago in Asia and Africa. In the United States, the federal government is governed by Congress, which sets policy and makes laws, and the President who is responsible for enforcing those laws in the federal courts.

Central Park is an urban park in New York City located between the Upper West and Upper East Sides of Manhattan. It is the most popular park in the United States.The park borders the Manhattan Island, which it is located on. It is bordered by Columbus Avenue to the northeast and the West Side Highway to the west, and the Bronx River to the east and north. The B-29 Superfortress (sometimes called "Superfortress"), also called the "Superfortress", was an American tactical bomber and strategic bombing platform designed during World War 2 by Consolidated B-24 Liberators and Boeing.

The overhand knot , also known as a knot and half knot , is one of the most fundamental knots in figure drawing, having been known since antiquity. It is an overhand knot that forms a closed loop when passed over its open end. The overhand knot was known as the first figure knot because its appearance on an ancient drawing of the universe was the first clue that this knot was an ancient knot.It is usually made of two loops—one on the outside and one on the inside—and is used to symbolize a closed loop or a closed system.

Carnival is a Western Christian festive season that occurs before the liturgical season of Lent . The main events typically include parades and religious processions, a variety of other activities including concerts, dancing, street performances, fireworks, fireworks shows, and carnival-related contests and competitions. It is traditionally marked by the public display of religious icons, particularly of Jesus and the Virgin Mary. Carnival season, also called the festive season, is one of the two seasons of European summer (the other being autumn) when the celebration of the Christmas season takes place.

A software bug is an error , flaw or fault in computer software that causes it to produce an incorrect result. The result of the error is no longer useful, and the software is broken.This term is often used when referring to an unintentional bug, such as a software bug or a programming error. In programming languages, these errors are often called bugs, and are often called "errors" or "bugs" by programmers (although they may also be known as "bugs". ); they are often not recognized as such until they are found and fixed in the long run.

Year 897 (DCCCXCVII) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  Spring – King Lambert II travels to Rome with his mother, Queen Ageltrude and brother Guy IV, Lombard duke of Spoleto, to meet Pope Stephen VI to receive reconfirmation of his imperial title. Guy is murdered on the Tiber by agents of Alberic I, a Frankish nobleman with political interests. He seizes Spoleto (possibly at the instigation of King Berengar I) and sets himself up as duke.

Martin Heidegger (; ; 26 September 188926 May 1976) was a German philosopher who is best known for contributions to phenomenology, hermeneutics, and existentialism. He is among  the most important and influential philosophers of the 20th century.In Heidegger's fundamental text Being and Time (1927), "Dasein" is introduced as a term for the type of being that humans possess. Dasein has been translated as "being there". Heidegger believes that Dasein already has a "pre-ontological" and non-abstract understanding that shapes how it lives. This mode of being he terms "being-in-the-world".

Gerard Adams ( ; born 6 October 1948 ) is an Irish republican politician who was the president of Sinn Féin from 1979 to 1984, and again from 1992 to 1999. He is considered to be a founding figure of Irish republicanism. Adams is the last surviving leader of the 1916 Rising and founder of the Provisional IRA.BiographyEarly yearsEarly lifeHe was born in County Waterford in the Midlands of Ireland to an Anglo-Irish family. His family was Catholic and Irish, but he left home to live and study in America in the 1960s. He came to the United States in 1970.

Thermonuclear fusion is the process of atoms combining or “ fusing ” together with huge amounts of heat . There are two types of fusing: thermonuclear and fusion power.In nuclear fusion, the nucleus of atoms of a given element is replaced by another atom and its nuclei are fused with the nucleus of the lighter atom. Thermonuclear fission is the splitting of a neutrally bound nucleus into two smaller, lighter nuclei, releasing heat.Fission is the splitting of a nucleus into smaller, lighter atoms. General Electric Company, officially General Electric (1867–1966), was an American company headquartered in Schenectady , New York, from 1869 to 1966.

Year 884 (DCCCLXXXIV) was a leap year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  March 1 – Diego Rodríguez Porcelos, count of Castile, founds and repopulates (repoblación) Burgos and Ubierna (Northern Spain), under the mandate of King Alfonso III of Asturias. Summer – King Carloman II reverts to the former fall-back of 'pay and pray', buying (with Danegeld) a truce at Amiens, while he raises 12,000 lbs of silver for the Vikings to depart. December 12 – Carloman II dies after a hunting accident.

Lanford Wilson ( April 13 , 1937March 24 , 2011 ) was an American playwright . His work , as well as other theater-influenced works such as The Pirates of Penzance , was influenced by American culture. Wilson also wrote for television and film.Early life and educationLifeWilson was born in Lanford, Connecticut. His mother, Sarah, was of Irish descent. His father, Henry Wilson, Jr. was a banker who was also a prominent member of society in his day.EducationWilson graduated from Yale University in 1948 with a degree in English literature and philosophy. Wilson also spent time teaching philosophy and English at Yale in the late 1940s.

Year 874 (DCCCLXXIV) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  Salomon, duke ('king') of Brittany, is murdered by a faction which includes his son-in-law Pascweten and Gurvand, son-in-law of late ruler Erispoe. After Salomon's death they divide the country, and Pascweten and Gurvand co-rule Brittany. Svatopluk I, ruler (knyaz) of Great Moravia, concludes a peace treaty at Forchheim (Northern Bavaria). He is able to expand his territories outside the Frankish sphere, and subjugates the Vistulans.Kirschbaum 2007, p. 121.

The Story of the Chevalier des Grieux and Manon Lescaut is a novel by Antoine François Prévost . Published in 1825, it became a bestseller and one of the most popular works in 1837.The novel is set in Paris during the reign of the Marquise of Montpensier. It tells the story of Manon, one of the Chevaliers des Grieux (women-at-arms) of King Louis XVI and Queen Marie Antoinette, during the Revolution of 1789. Chiếm Bộn Hành ( , , ) is an English singer, songwriter, and record producer from Manchester.

Bread is a staple food prepared from a dough of flour (usually wheat) and water, usually by baking. Throughout recorded history and around the world, it has been an important part of many cultures' diet. It is one of the oldest human-made foods, having been of significance since the dawn of agriculture, and plays an essential role in both religious rituals and secular culture.Bread may be leavened by naturally occurring microbes (e.g. sourdough), chemicals (e.g. baking soda), industrially produced yeast, or high-pressure aeration, which creates the gas bubbles that fluff up bread.

Patch collecting or badge collecting ( also , scutelliphily , from Latin scutellus meaning little shield , and Greek phileein , meaning guardian) is the act of collecting coins or other objects to display in a display case, often attached to a table, usually as a memento, to represent the value of the object.Collectors usually collect coins, stamps or other pieces of memorabilia that are collectible, such as coins or stamps issued by foreign governments, as well as coins and other items which are valuable to collectors.A collector who has made good money in the field may seek to invest his earnings in a trust that will collect more coins.

Concurrent Versions System (CVS, also known as the Concurrent Versioning System) is a revision control system originally developed by Dick Grune in July 1986.CVS operates as a front end to RCS, an earlier system which operates on single files. It expands upon RCS by adding support for repository-level change tracking, and a client-server model.Released under the terms of the GNU General Public License, CVS is free software.Design CVS operates as a front end to Revision Control System (RCS), an older version control system that manages individual files but not whole projects.

A musician is a person who composes , conducts , or performs music . According to the United States Employment Tax (U.S. federal tax laws), music is a professional occupation, meaning that it is a trade and business. There are also some exemptions and tax treatment for performers. Haiti (; Hérault and French: ), officially the Republic of Haiti, is a country located in West Africa to the west of South America in the Caribbean Sea. It shares borders with the Dominican Republic, Haiti, and Cuba. It borders the Dominican Republic to the south.

Twenty Thousand Leagues Under the Seas  is a classic science fiction adventure novel by French writer Jules Verne.The novel was originally serialized from March 1869 through June 1870 in Pierre-Jules Hetzel's fortnightly periodical, the . A deluxe octavo edition, published by Hetzel in November 1871, included 111 illustrations by Alphonse de Neuville and Édouard Riou. The book was widely acclaimed on its release and remains so; it is regarded as one of the premier adventure novels and one of Verne's greatest works, along with Around the World in Eighty Days and Journey to the Center of the Earth.

The Little Ice Age (LIA) was a period of regional cooling, particularly pronounced in the North Atlantic region, that occurred after the Medieval Warm Period. It was not a true ice age of global extent. The term was introduced into scientific literature by François E. Matthes in 1939. The time period has been conventionally defined as extending from the 16th to the 19th centuries, but some experts prefer an alternative timespan from about 1300 to about 1850.The NASA Earth Observatory notes three particularly cold intervals. One began about 1650, another about 1770, and the last in 1850, all of which were separated by intervals of slight warming.

The word  comes from the Japanese word for logographic characters of the Chinese script, which were made a major part of the Japanese writing system along with the syllabic scripts of hiragana and katakana. More specifically, it refers to that set of Chinese characters directly incorporated into the written Japanese language with often Japanese pronunciation, inclusive of those few characters invented in Japan based on character components derived from other Chinese characters.The term kanji literally means "Han characters", and this word is spelled in Japanese using the same characters as traditional Chinese in reference to the character writing system, which is known as hanzi .

Lucia di Lammermoor is a dramma tragico (tragic opera) in three acts by Italian composer Gaetano Donizetti. Salvadore Cammarano wrote the Italian-language libretto loosely based upon Sir Walter Scott's 1819 historical novel The Bride of Lammermoor.Donizetti wrote Lucia di Lammermoor in 1835, when he was reaching the peak of his reputation as an opera composer. Gioachino Rossini had recently retired and Vincenzo Bellini had died shortly before the premiere of Lucia leaving Donizetti as "the sole reigning genius of Italian opera". Not only were conditions ripe for Donizetti's success as a composer, but there was also a widespread interest in the history and culture of Scotland.

Eastern Europe is the eastern region of Europe . There is no consistent definition of the precise area it covers, but a common assumption is that it is in Eastern Europe along the border of Poland and Czechoslovakia in the North, and Slovakia and Romania in the South. The European Union (EU) is an intergovernmental political, economic, and military organisation founded in 1957, with an initial budget of €10bn. The Union has 27 member countries, with the remaining 15 being former constituent parts, which joined in 2004. The EU is currently a political, economic, and military organisation comprising both member states and non-member states.

In the Ancient Greek religion, Hestia (; , "hearth" or "fireside") is the virgin goddess of the hearth, the right ordering of domesticity, the family, the home, and the state. In Greek mythology, she is the firstborn child of the Titans Cronus and Rhea.Customarily, in Greek culture, Hestia received the first offering at every sacrifice in the household. In the public domain, the hearth of the prytaneum functioned as her official sanctuary, and, when a new colony was established, a flame from Hestia's public hearth in the mother city would be carried to the new settlement.

Patch collecting or badge collecting (also, scutelliphily, from Latin scutellus meaning little shield, and Greek phileein meaning to love) is the hobby of collecting patches or badges.Souvenir patchesSouvenir patches are usually shield-shaped and generally contain a coat of arms, a map or a miniature view. The patches can be made of any material, but are usually woven or embroidered fabric, though they can also be made from paper or, increasingly, plastic.Other types of collectible patches include police or service patches, space mission patches, Scout patches, fashion patches, political and sports stickers, walking stick labels, car window pennants, and pin badges.

was a Japanese television cooking show produced by Fuji Television. The series, which premiered on October 10, 1993, was a stylized cook-off featuring guest chefs challenging one of the show's resident "Iron Chefs" in a timed cooking battle built around a specific theme ingredient. The series ended on September 24, 1999, although occasional specials were produced until 2002. The series aired 309 episodes. Repeats are regularly aired on the Food Network in Canada, the Cooking Channel in the United States, and on Special Broadcasting Service in Australia.

Fermat's principle, also known as the principle of least time, is the link between ray optics and wave optics. In its original "strong" form, Fermat's principle states that the path taken by a ray between two given points is the path that can be traveled in the least time. In order to be true in all cases, this statement must be weakened by replacing the "least" time with a time that is "stationary" with respect to variations of the path — so that a deviation in the path causes, at most, a second-order change in the traversal time.

Columbia Business School (CBS) is the business school of Columbia University in the City of New York in Manhattan, New York City. Established in 1916, Columbia Business School is one of six Ivy League business schools and is one of the oldest business schools in the world. In 2022, it was ranked as the 2nd best business school.History The school was founded in 1916 with 11 full-time faculty members and an inaugural class of 61 students, including 8 women. Banking executive Emerson McMillin provided initial funding in 1916, while A. Barton Hepburn, then president of Chase National Bank, provided funding for the School's endowment in 1919.

Nansen passports , originally and officially stateless persons passports , were internationally recognized refugee travel documents from 1922 to 1938, and then, from 1946 to 1952. These were the passports of Norwegian citizens who had fled their homes during the First World War and who sought refuge in other countries. The earliest known use of a nderson's passport was by Otto Nansen of Denmark in 1913. The Netherlands  is a country in the north of North Africa. It occupies the easternmost portion of the island of the Netherlands, along the Dutch provinces of Groningen, Zuid-Holland and Zeeland, and bordering Belgium and Luxembourg in the West.

Show jumping, is a part of a group of English riding equestrian events that also includes dressage, eventing, hunters, and equitation. Jumping classes are commonly seen at horse shows throughout the world, including the Olympics. Sometimes shows are limited exclusively to jumpers, sometimes jumper classes are offered in conjunction with other English-style events, and sometimes show jumping is but one division of very large, all-breed competitions that include a very wide variety of disciplines. Jumping classes may be governed by various national horse show sanctioning organizations, such as the United States Equestrian Federation in the USA or the British Showjumping Association in Great Britain.

Montague Rhodes James  (1 August 1862 – 12 June 1936) was an English author, medievalist scholar and provost of King's College, Cambridge (1905–1918), and of Eton College (1918–1936). He was Vice-Chancellor of the University of Cambridge (1913–15).James's work as a medievalist and scholar is still highly regarded, but he is best remembered for his ghost stories, which some consider among the best in the genre. He redefined the ghost story for the new century by abandoning many of the formal Gothic clichés of his predecessors and using more realistic contemporary settings.

Edward Teller ( ; January 15 , 1908 – September 9 , 2003 ) was a Hungarian-American theoretical physicist who worked for more than 40 years at Los Alamos National Laboratory. In 1962, he co-founded the New Mexico Institute for Nuclear Physics, where he led a team that discovered fission at the Trinity and Hanford Nuclear Weapons Plant.He is the only person to receive the Nobel Prize for Physics twice, in 1954 and 1965.Early life and educationTeller was born in Hungary in 1908. At the age of 12, he emigrated from his home country to Germany, where he had family.

Tristan Tzara (; ; born Samuel or Samy Rosenstock, also known as S. Samyro;  – 25 December 1963) was a Romanian and French avant-garde poet, essayist and performance artist. Also active as a journalist, playwright, literary and art critic, composer and film director, he was known best for being one of the founders and central figures of the anti-establishment Dada movement. Under the influence of Adrian Maniu, the adolescent Tzara became interested in Symbolism and co-founded the magazine Simbolul with Ion Vinea (with whom he also wrote experimental poetry) and painter Marcel Janco.

Tristan Tzara ( ; ; born Samuel or Samy Rosenstock , also known as S. Samyro ; – 25 December 1925 – 2 January 2007) was an Israeli author and philosopher who authored a wide variety of books on religion and metaphysics.He is widely regarded as one of the foremost Western exponents of existentialism, and as the author of several books, including his most influential, The Sorrows of Young Werther (1947).Early lifeTzara was born on 25 December 1925 into a devoutly religious Jewish family. His father was a member of the Yeshiva of Vilna.

On May 25, 1865, in Mobile, Alabama, in the Southern United States, an ordnance depot or "magazine" exploded, killing some 300 persons. This event occurred just after the end of the American Civil War, during the occupation of the city by victorious Federal troops.The depot was a warehouse on Beauregard Street, where the troops had stacked some 200 tons of shells and powder. Some time in the afternoon of May 25, a cloud of black smoke rose into the air and the ground began to rumble. Flames shot up into the sky and bursting shells were heard throughout the city.

In music performance and notation , legato ( ; Italian for `` tied together '' ; French lié ; German ), often shortened to  or  ( ) is a method of playing music where an alternating series of notes are played in order, rather than by an individual note.Legato has been described as "the quintessential form of Western classical music" in the 19th and early 20th centuries, and "among the most essential aspects of the Romantic style". Legato was also used by other composers and artists, including composers of Romanticism, such as Ludwig van Beethoven and Franz Liszt.

Domenico Gaetano Maria Donizetti ( 29 November 1797 – 8 April 1848 ) was an Italian composer , best known for his music for piano and organ. Donizetti was the son of a wealthy family and attended the Royal Conservatory, Milan, at the time of the First Italian Republic. He studied with Antonio Vivaldi and was considered to be the best organist of his time; however, during his time with Vivaldi, he also wrote music for the organ. Donizetti studied at the Collegio Italiano in Florence. He began his career as a violinist, and by 1798 had become a concertmaster.

Australian Signals Directorate ( ASD ; until 2013 : Defence Signals Directorate , DSD ) is the Australian government agency responsible for the national security of Australia. The primary responsibility of the ASD is to provide intelligence, surveillance and reconnaissance, and communications security (C2ISR). The Australian Transport Safety Bureau (ATSB; previously Transport Accident Investigation Branch; ATAIB) is the national safety agency responsible for investigating the causes and consequences of transport-related accidents and incidents in Australia. The role of the ATAIB differs significantly from that of its predecessor the Australian Transport Safety Commission (ATSC).

Kenneth Charles Williams ( 22 February 1926 – 15 April 1988 ) was an English actor . He was best known for his leading role in the British TV soap Coronation Street from 1967 to 1997. He also appeared in a variety of stage productions, including the British Royal Court Theatre and the West End. Williams received an honorary OBE for services to the theatre in 1994, and a CBE in 1997.BiographyWilliams was born in South London, the eldest of two brothers, but was raised by his parents in Jamaica. He studied drama at South London Polytechnic before moving to London and working as a stage actor and director.

Classless Inter-Domain Routing ( CIDR ) is a method for allocating IP addresses and for IP routing . The Internet is a network of networks connected by network routing. An IP address is a unique number assigned to an IP packet that uniquely identifies an IP datagram within the datagram routing network. IP addresses are globally unique and assigned by the ARPANET (also known as the ARPAnet). An interplanetary spacecraft (also called an interplanetary probe) is any spacecraft that is sent to an orbiting destination. This includes both spacecraft (such as a spacecraft carrying a satellite) and spacecraft-to-satellite (SDB) missions.

was the 68th emperor of Japan , according to the traditional order of succession.Go-Ichijō 's reign spanned the years from 24 November 1871 until his death in 1908. He was the first emperor in the imperial family to marry a concubine, his wife, Nōbō. He also became the first emperor ever to have a foreign wife, Shōhoku.Born to the imperial family in Edo, Heisei , he was the eighth emperor of Japan.He was the first emperor to adopt a female heir, Shōhoku. He also was the first emperor to appoint a consort as regent to take his place after death.

Near Earth Asteroid Rendezvous – Shoemaker (NEAR Shoemaker), renamed after its 1996 launch in honor of planetary scientist Eugene Shoemaker, was a robotic space probe designed by the Johns Hopkins University Applied Physics Laboratory for NASA to study the near-Earth asteroid Eros from close orbit over a period of a year. It was the first spacecraft to successfully orbit an asteroid and also land on an asteroid. In February 2000, the mission succeeded in closing in with the asteroid and afterwards orbited it several times. On February 12, 2001, the mission succeeded in touching down on the asteroid.

Dresden (, ; Upper Saxon: Dräsdn; ) is the capital city of the German state of Saxony and its second most populous city, after Leipzig. It is the 12th most populous city of Germany, the fourth largest by area (after Berlin, Hamburg and Cologne), and the third most populous city in the area of former East Germany, after Berlin and Leipzig. Dresden's urban area comprises the towns of Freital, Pirna, Radebeul, Meißen (Meissen), Coswig, Radeberg and Heidenau and has around 790,000 inhabitants.

Catalase is a common enzyme found in nearly all living organisms exposed to oxygen ( such as bacteria , plants , algae , cyanobacteria , fungi , and even certain eukaryotic cells), and in many non-biological systems (such as the nucleic acids that make up DNA, RNA and the DNA in e.g. yeast, bacteria, and plants) as well. Most organisms use adenylate cyclase for the conversion of sugars to ADP and P i .Adenylate cyclase also is found in mitochondria and is thus the rate-limiting enzyme for energy production in the cell, as well as being an essential part of many redox reactions.

Cambridge is a university city and the county town of Cambridgeshire , England , on the River Cam approximately north of the city centre.Cambridge has a population of  in 2011.Cambridge is the administrative centre of Oxfordshire , England , and a county town of East Sussex . It is the second-smallest county town in England, and the third-smallest in Britain, after Shropshire and Warwickshire , and the ninth smallest in the United Kingdom.Camb.ˈkam ( IPA: [ˈkəm] ; ,  , ) is an official language in Cambridge, a city in Cambridgeshire in England, as well as in Shropshire and Warwickshire, and the county and local authorities of Oxfordshire.

Fishing is the activity of trying to catch fish . Fish are often caught in the wild but may also be caught in fishing nets . There are many kinds of fishing, the most common of which is net fishing, which involves using a fishing net to capture a variety of aquatic organisms, such as plankton and fish. The Farsi language is the official language of Iran, Afghanistan, Iraq, and most of the Persian Gulf . It is one of the five official languages of the Islamic Republic of Iran, the country's official language.

In mathematics, the Dirac delta distribution ( distribution), also known as the unit impulse symbol, is a generalized function or distribution over the real numbers, whose value is zero everywhere except at zero, and whose integral over the entire real line is equal to one.The current understanding of the impulse is as a linear functional that maps every continuous function to its value at zero, or as the weak limit of a sequence of bump functions, which are zero over most of the real line, with a tall spike at the origin.

A shaped charge is an explosive charge shaped to focus the effect of the explosive's energy. Different types of shaped charges are used for various purposes such as cutting and forming metal, initiating nuclear weapons, penetrating armor, or perforating wells in the oil and gas industry.A typical modern shaped charge, with a metal liner on the charge cavity, can penetrate armor steel to a depth of seven or more times the diameter of the charge (charge diameters, CD), though greater depths of 10 CD and above have been achieved.

Lewiston is a city and the county seat of Nez Perce County, Idaho, United States, in the state's north central region. It is the second-largest city in the northern Idaho region, behind Coeur d'Alene, and ninth-largest in the state. Lewiston is the principal city of the Lewiston, ID-WA Metropolitan Statistical Area, which includes all of Nez Perce County and Asotin County, Washington. As of the 2020 census, the population of Lewiston was 34,203 up from 31,894 in 2010.Lewiston is located at the confluence of the Snake River and Clearwater River,  upstream and southeast of the Lower Granite Dam.

Yorkshire pudding is a baked pudding made from a batter of eggs, flour, and milk or water. A common English side dish, it is a versatile food that can be served in numerous ways depending on its ingredients, size, and the accompanying components of the meal. As a first course, it can be served with onion gravy. For a main course, it may be served with meat and gravy, and is part of the traditional Sunday roast, but can also be filled with foods such as bangers and mash to make a meal.

Juan Moreno y Herrera–Jiménez (born 30 July 1948), known as Jean Reno , is a French actor of Andalusian Spanish origin. He has worked in American, French, English, Japanese, Spanish and Italian movie productions; Reno appeared in films such as Crimson Rivers, Godzilla, The Da Vinci Code, Mission: Impossible, The Pink Panther, Ronin, Les Visiteurs, Wasabi, The Big Blue, Hector and the Search for Happiness and Léon: The Professional.Early lifeReno was born Juan Moreno y Herrera-Jiménez in Casablanca, Morocco. His parents were Spanish, natives of Sanlúcar de Barrameda and Jerez de la Frontera in Andalucia.

Cambridge  is a university city and the county town of Cambridgeshire, England, on the River Cam approximately  north of London. At the United Kingdom Census 2011, the population of the Cambridge built-up area (which is larger than the remit of Cambridge City Council) was 158,434 including 29,327 students. Cambridge became an important trading centre during the Roman and Viking ages, and there is archaeological evidence of settlement in the area as early as the Bronze Age. The first town charters were granted in the 12th century, although modern city status was not officially conferred until 1951.The University of Cambridge was founded in 1209.

Year 1054 ( MLIV ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) in the Roman Catholic and Eastern Orthodox Churches, the Gregorian Reform, and the Church of England.In the Roman Catholic calendar, it is the first week of July, the first Sunday of Lent and the first day of Advent. In astronomy, a hyperbola is a flattened hyperbola. The term is used in a variety of different ways in different fields. In mathematics, a hyperbola is a curve that is tangent at the origin, or in a spherical geometry, at the point of the hyperbola in spherical geometry.

The putamen (; from Latin, meaning "nutshell") is a round structure located at the base of the forebrain (telencephalon). The putamen and caudate nucleus together form the dorsal striatum. It is also one of the structures that compose the basal nuclei. Through various pathways, the putamen is connected to the substantia nigra, the globus pallidus, the claustrum, and the thalamus, in addition to many regions of the cerebral cortex. A primary function of the putamen is to regulate movements at various stages (e.g. preparation and execution) and influence various types of learning.

Flavius Odoacer ( ;  – 493 AD), also spelled Odovacer or Odovacar , was a soldier and statesman of barbarian background, who deposed the child emperor Romulus Augustulus and became King of Italy (476–493). Odoacer's overthrow of Romulus Augustulus is traditionally seen as marking the end of the Western Roman Empire as well as Ancient Rome.Though the real power in Italy was in his hands, he represented himself as the client of the emperor in Constantinople, Zeno. Odoacer often used the Roman honorific patrician, granted by Zeno, but was referred to as a king  in many documents.

A verb is a word ( part of speech ) that in syntax conveys an action ( bring , read, think, sing) or an effect (do something) or both. It is an infix or prefix indicating action or effect in an independent clause. Verbs are sometimes combined with adjectives to form a word with an inflectional suffix or prefix ending in 's; this is called a prefix or an affix.Phrases, sentences, or phrases are made up of a noun, adjective, adverb, or adverb phrase, plus the infinitive and a coordinating conjunction (and).

The M18A1 Claymore is a directional anti-personnel mine developed for the United States Armed Forces . Its inventor , Norman Chaffee, developed the mine during World War II when he was in charge of the construction of German anti-tank weapons at the Ordnance Department's Aberdeen Proving Grounds.Chaffee was working on other projects when he returned to Germany, including an anti-personnel mine with a faster firing rate, and he submitted both to the United States Army. In December 1943, Chaffee filed an application for the patent with the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office, which approved it in July of the same year.

Stevana `` Stevie '' Case ( born 1976–1977 ) is an American businesswoman . She is known for competing in the World's Finest Challenge swimsuit competition with her husband in 1984, 1986 and 1987 and in the Miss America Pageant in 1996 and the Miss America Teen World pageant in 1999, and in the Miss America pageant itself from 1976 to 2002. She was named Miss America in 1996, 2002, 2008, and 2016. She is the third-highest-paid model of all time, earning an estimated net worth of $100 million as of 2010.

The subset sum problem (SSP) is a decision problem in computer science. In its most general formulation, there is a multiset  of integers and a target-sum , and the question is to decide whether any subset of the integers sum to precisely . The problem is known to be NP-complete. Moreover, some restricted variants of it are NP-complete too, for example: The variant in which all inputs are positive. The variant in which inputs may be positive or negative, and . For example, given the set , the answer is yes because the subset  sums to zero.

In mathematics, a Möbius strip, band, or loop ( , ; ), also spelled Mobius or Moebius, is a surface with only one side (when embedded in three-dimensional Euclidean space) and only one boundary curve. The Möbius strip is the simplest non-orientable surface. It can be realized as a ruled surface. Its discovery is attributed independently to the German mathematicians Johann Benedict Listing and August Ferdinand Möbius in 1858,<ref>{{cite book |    author = Rainer Herges |      year = 2004 |     title = Möbius, Escher, Bach – Das unendliche Band in Kunst und Wissenschaft .

Enriched uranium is a type of uranium in which the percent composition of uranium-235 ( written 235U ) has been enriched by adding a number of isotopes of uranium-235, typically 238U and 239Pu . The uranium-235 atoms have become fused and are no longer separated by the atomic nucleus.The enriched uranium is radioactive. The East Africa Rift Valley, commonly referred to as the Rift Valley or simply the Rift, is a mountainous region in East Africa consisting of a series of basins and tributaries, which together form the Nyanza-Mwaura basin and extend south-east of the Rift Valley.The area is of geological importance because of its geographical and geomorphological position.

Year 870 (DCCCLXX) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  August 8 – Treaty of Meerssen: King Louis the German forces his half-brother Charles the Bald to accept a peace treaty, which partitions the Middle Frankish Kingdom into two larger east and west divisions. Louis receives most of Austrasia (which evolves into the Kingdom of Germany), and Charles receives territory in Lower Burgundy (which evolves into the Kingdom of France). However, large parts of the Frisian coast are under Viking control.

In Euclidean geometry , an affine transformation , or an affinity ( from the Latin , affinis , `` connected with '') between vectors, describes a change in a point's position and velocity by the displacement of another vector with the same magnitude in the direction opposite the displacement. The term also refers to any transformation in two or more vectors whose values change in relation to the vectors to which they are applied. A transformation is also sometimes called a displacement, a displacement, or a displacement matrix . In vector algebra, the matrix is often denoted by  .

Dementia manifests as a set of related symptoms , which usually surface when the brain is damaged by injury or disease. It typically occurs as a result of a decline in the function of specific brain regions and is associated with cognitive, behavioral, or emotional disturbance. It can occur with other cognitive impairments, such as memory loss, learning difficulties, or mood swings. There are many different types of dementia and the majority of people with the condition develop the disorder before age 60 years.The causes of dementia are still under scientific debate and the cause or causes of Alzheimer's disease and other forms of dementia are not fully understood.

The National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration ( NOAA ) is an American scientific and regulatory agency within the United States Department of Commerce. It has an annual budget of more than $2.4 billion, which is spread across the Department of Commerce, U.S. Coast Guard, and the National Science Foundation. It also has the responsibility for conducting research on sea-surface temperature, the climate, meteorology, oceanography, and marine science. It also monitors climate change in order to determine the effects and future of such changes. It also develops and implements weather forecasting, maritime weather prediction, and meteorology models.

David is a masterpiece of Renaissance sculpture , created in marble between 1501 and 1504 by the Italian artist Michelangelo Buonarroti in the Villa Borghese. David was the most important statue of its time, and a central figure in a series by the same artist, commissioned to celebrate the coronation of Louis XIII in 1510. A digital camera is any device with an image capture sensor that takes a picture every time an object, such as a light or a car, is in focus. Digital cameras generally have a larger sensor for taking larger photos.

Yucatán (, also , , ;  ), officially the Free and Sovereign State of Yucatán, is one of the 32 states which comprise the Federal Entities of Mexico. It is divided into 106 municipalities, and its capital city is Mérida.It is located on the north part of the Yucatán Peninsula. It is bordered by the states of Campeche to the southwest and Quintana Roo to the southeast, with the Gulf of Mexico off its north coast.Before the arrival of Spaniards to the Yucatán Peninsula, the name of this region was Mayab.

The Palmer Raids were a series of raids conducted in November 1919 and January 1920 by the United States Department of the Interior's United States Marshals Service to apprehend federal employees suspected of committing crimes against government property and the people who worked for them.The United States Marshals Service (USMS) carried out the raids, using federal agents as informers and informers as well as the help of private citizens. Philosophy of Religion is one of the four main areas of study within the fields of religion and theology (the others being Theology and Ethics).

The Collatz conjecture in mathematics asks whether repeating two simple arithmetic operations will eventually transform every positive integer into one. It  concerns sequences of integers in which each term is obtained from the previous term as follows: if the previous term is even, the next term is one half of the previous term. If the previous term is odd, the next term is 3 times the previous term plus 1. The conjecture is that these sequences always reach 1, no matter which positive integer is chosen to start the sequence.The conjecture is named after mathematician Lothar Collatz, who introduced the idea in 1937, two years after receiving his doctorate.

A complex system is a system composed of many components which may interact with each other. Examples of complex systems are Earth's global climate, organisms, the human brain, infrastructure such as power grid, transportation or communication systems, complex software and electronic systems, social and economic organizations (like cities), an ecosystem, a living cell, and ultimately the entire universe.Complex systems are systems whose behavior is intrinsically difficult to model due to the dependencies, competitions, relationships, or other types of interactions between their parts or between a given system and its environment.

An ion thruster, ion drive, or ion engine is a form of electric propulsion used for spacecraft propulsion. It creates thrust by accelerating ions using electricity.An ion thruster ionizes a neutral gas by extracting some electrons out of atoms, creating a cloud of positive ions. These ion thrusters rely mainly on electrostatics as ions are accelerated by the Coulomb force along an electric field. Temporarily stored electrons are finally reinjected by a neutralizer in the cloud of ions after it has passed through the electrostatic grid, so the gas becomes neutral again and can freely disperse in space without any further electrical interaction with the thruster.

A political prisoner is someone imprisoned for their political activity . The political offense is not always the official reason for the imprisonment. Often, political offenders are imprisoned for other reasons as well. A political party is a political organization formed for political purposes to promote or oppose candidates for any political office and for the election or defeat of one or more candidates to such office. Political parties generally operate under the control of a political party committee (party central committee or party committee).Party committees are usually independent of a particular candidate or party and operate independently within the same political party.

Relative density , or specific gravity , is the ratio of the density ( mass of a unit volume ) at one place to the density ( mass of a unit volume) at another place. It is a relative measure of density, since density changes according to the ratio of different bodies' densities, and is a measure of the pressure of water or other liquid at a particular place. A unit is commonly called a "cubic meter" in modern measurements and units, and in some units is referred to as a "cu meter".

Hoysala architecture is the building style in Hindu temple architecture developed under the rule of the Hoysala Empire between the 12th century BC and the 17th century AD. The term Hoysalae is a transliteration of the Hoysalese name for their empire.Hoysalese architecture is characterized by the absence of external ornamentations and elaborate decorations. The style was characterized by simplicity, simplicity, simplicity, simplicity; simplicity and simplicity. Hygrophilia, in biology, the capacity of a particular population to experience strong and repeated sexual arousal by the scent of a member of another group (i.e. scent-obsessive).
