The history of Burgundy stretches back to the times when the region was inhabited in turn by Celts, Romans (Gallo-Romans), and in the 5th century, the Roman allies the Burgundians, a Germanic people originating in Bornholm (Baltic Sea), who settled there and established the Kingdom of the Burgundians.This Burgundian kingdom was conquered in the 6th century by another Germanic tribe, the Franks, who continued the kingdom of Burgundy under their own rule.Later, the region was divided between the Duchy of Burgundy (to the west) and the County of Burgundy (to the east).

New Zealand consists of more than six hundred islands , mainly remnants of a larger land mass now beneath the South Pacific. The principal island of New Zealand is Lake Wakatipu, located on the north coast. Other major islands include the South Island and the North Island. New Zealand is separated from the Pacific by South America, as is Australia from the South Pacific. New Zealand is the sixth-largest island in the southern hemisphere, after the other five countries of the southern hemisphere: Australia , New Zealand , South Africa , and the United States .

Kannada (; ಕನ್ನಡ, ; less commonly known as Kanarese) is a Dravidian language spoken predominantly by the people of Karnataka in the southwestern region of India. The language is also spoken by linguistic minorities in the states of Maharashtra, Andhra Pradesh, Tamil Nadu, Telangana, Kerala and Goa; and also by Kannadigas abroad. The language had roughly 43 million native speakers by 2011. Kannada is also spoken as a second and third language by over 12.9 million non-native speakers in Karnataka, which adds up to 56.9 million speakers.

In quantum mechanics , counterfactual definiteness ( CFD ) is the ability to speak `` meaningfully '' of the definiteness of the future state of a system. It can be defined as the state of the system for which the system's future action is neither determined nor modified by its past state. The notion is related to that of causality (as in causality postulate ), but differs from it in that the state of the system may not be determined to any particular extent by its past state. Denis Diderot  (January 28, 1778 – November 18, 1794) was an eighteenth-century French philosopher and writer.

Kingston is the capital and largest city of Jamaica, located on the southeastern coast of the island. It faces a natural harbour protected by the Palisadoes, a long sand spit which connects the town of Port Royal and the Norman Manley International Airport to the rest of the island. In the Americas, Kingston is the largest predominantly English-speaking city south of the United States.The local government bodies of the parishes of Kingston and St. Andrew were amalgamated by the Kingston and St. Andrew Corporation Act of 1923, to form the Kingston and St. Andrew Corporation (KSAC).

Thetis (;  ), is a figure from Greek mythology with varying mythological roles. She mainly appears as a sea nymph, a goddess of water, or one of the 50 Nereids, daughters of the ancient sea god Nereus.When described as a Nereid in Classical myths, Thetis was the daughter of Nereus and Doris, and a granddaughter of Tethys with whom she sometimes shares characteristics. Often she seems to lead the Nereids as they attend to her tasks. Sometimes she also is identified with Metis.Some sources argue that she was one of the earliest of deities worshipped in Archaic Greece, the oral traditions and records of which are lost.

Year 1025 ( MXXV ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) on a Friday in November.The year 1025 was not a leap year in the Gregorian calendar, rather it was counted from the year 1552 (the Gregorian Calendar was introduced in 1582), and began a new year. H. R. Hadden (; October 27, 1890 – November 25, 1973) was an American astronomer and author, best known for inventing and designing his eponymous telescope. He was one of the founders of the astronomy profession.

The Circus Maximus (Latin for "largest circus"; Italian: Circo Massimo) is an ancient Roman chariot-racing stadium and mass entertainment venue in Rome, Italy. In the valley between the Aventine and Palatine hills, it was the first and largest stadium in ancient Rome and its later Empire. It measured  in length and  in width and could accommodate over 150,000 spectators. In its fully developed form, it became the model for circuses throughout the Roman Empire. The site is now a public park.Events and uses The Circus was Rome's largest venue for ludi, public games connected to Roman religious festivals.

(All Women Do It, or The School for Lovers), K. 588, is an opera buffa in two acts by Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart. It was first performed on 26 January 1790 at the Burgtheater in Vienna, Austria. The libretto was written by Lorenzo Da Ponte who also wrote Le nozze di Figaro and Don Giovanni.Although it is commonly held that  was written and composed at the suggestion of the Emperor Joseph II, recent research does not support this idea. There is evidence that Mozart's contemporary Antonio Salieri tried to set the libretto but left it unfinished.

Mobile Bay is a shallow inlet of the Gulf of Mexico , lying within the state of Alabama in the United States of America. As of 2016, it was the ninth-largest estuary in the world by area and the fourth-largest estuary in the United States by area. It also forms part of the Bay of the Ozarks.The Gulf of Mexico is a region that covers an area of approximately 4,944,000 square kilometres (1,532,000 square miles), or 6.6% of the United States.The Gulf of Mexico, or simply the Gulf, is the most extensive waterway in the world.

Steven C. McConnell is an author of software engineering textbooks such as Code Complete, Rapid Development, and Software Estimation. He is cited as an expert in software engineering and project management.Career McConnell graduated with a bachelor's degree in philosophy,  minoring in computer science, at Whitman College in Walla Walla, Washington, and a master's degree in software engineering from Seattle University. He then pursued a career in the desktop software industry, working at Microsoft, Boeing, the Russell Investment Group and several other Seattle area firms. At Microsoft, McConnell worked on TrueType as part of Windows 3.1.

The Ante-Nicene Fathers , subtitled `` The Writings of the Fathers Down to A.D. 325 '' , is a collection of writings of the Greek, Latin, Arabic, Armenian, Coptic, Ethiopic, Coptic Ethiopic, Syriac, and Ethiopic Coptic churches that have been ascribed to the apostles. It has been a significant addition to the canon of the Christian canon and has formed the basis for much of what has been written on the subjects of the Christian faith in the Western Christian world. It was compiled in the late 2nd century and published in the first third of the 3rd century CE.

Pope Leo II ( – 28 June 683 ) was the bishop of Rome from 17 August 682 to his death and the first pope from Rome. He is remembered as the first Roman Catholic to be elected pontiff. Leo's father was a Roman citizen who served as the bishop of Trier. Leo spent the early years of his life in Rome and then later in the Roman province of Pannonia. In astronomy, an occultation is an occurrence in which the Sun passes behind, or occultates a bright object. The process is similar to a transit of a star, but occurs at a greater angle.

Pope Leo V was the bishop of Rome and nominal ruler of the Papal States from July 903 to his death in February 904. He was pope during the period known as the Saeculum obscurum, when popes wielded little temporal authority.Leo V was born at a place called Priapi, near Ardea. Although he was a priest when he was elected pope following the death of Pope Benedict IV (900–903), he was not a cardinal priest of Rome.During his brief pontificate, Leo granted the canons of Bologna a special bull (epistola tuitionis) where he exempted them from the payment of taxes.

Erich Armand Arthur Joseph Hückel  (August 9, 1896, Berlin – February 16, 1980, Marburg) was a German physicist and physical chemist. He is known for two major contributions:The Debye–Hückel theory of electrolytic solutionsThe Hückel method of approximate molecular orbital (MO) calculations on π electron systems.Hückel was born in the Charlottenburg suburb of Berlin. He studied physics and mathematics from 1914 to 1921 at the University of Göttingen.On receiving his doctorate, he became an assistant at Göttingen, but soon became an assistant to Peter Debye at Zürich.

The unexpected hanging paradox or surprise test paradox is a paradox about a person 's expectations about the timing of the events of a given event. It arises when a person believes that two events will occur at roughly the same time, but that the one that happens first is unexpected, while the one that comes a bit after is expected. The International Criminal Court (ICC) is an international judicial body. It prosecutes individuals charged with genocide, crimes against humanity and war crimes for crimes committed in the former Yugoslavia, Rwanda, Cambodia and Sierra Leone.

The Sikorsky UH-60 Black Hawk is a four-blade, twin-engine, medium-lift utility helicopter manufactured by Sikorsky Aircraft. Sikorsky submitted the S-70 design for the United States Army's Utility Tactical Transport Aircraft System (UTTAS) competition in 1972. The Army designated the prototype as the YUH-60A and selected the Black Hawk as the winner of the program in 1976, after a fly-off competition with the Boeing Vertol YUH-61.Named after the Native American war leader Black Hawk, the UH-60A entered service with the U.S. Army in 1979, to replace the Bell UH-1 Iroquois as the Army's tactical transport helicopter.

Carnival is a Western Christian festive season that occurs before the liturgical season of Lent. The main events typically occur during February or early March, during the period historically known as Shrovetide (or Pre-Lent). Carnival typically involves public celebrations, including events such as parades, public street parties and other entertainments, combining some elements of a circus. Elaborate costumes and masks allow people to set aside their everyday individuality and experience a heightened sense of social unity. Participants often indulge in excessive consumption of alcohol, meat, and other foods that will be forgone during upcoming Lent.

A seed is an embryonic plant enclosed in a protective outer covering . The formation of the seed is part of an organism's growth cycle, which begins in the ovary during the process of ovulation or fertilisation.Seeds in general are classified as ovules, which are plant embryos enclosed within a single ovule, and seeds, which consist of the resulting ovules, which are seeds.Seed formation and development begins in the ovary and continues into the early embryo stage when cells of the ovary called the pronuclei divide. It is during this stage that new cells are produced, referred to as oogenesis.

Patrick Jake O'Rourke ( November 14 , 1947 – February 15 , 2022 ) was an American libertarian political satirist and author. He was born and raised in Chicago, Illinois. He grew up in and around the Second City, one of the first improv comedy theaters in the country, before moving to Los Angeles to work with Bill Hicks and Lenny Bruce. He also attended UC Santa Barbara and went to graduate school at UC Berkeley.O'Rourke had a successful career in stand up comedy, writing for shows like The Tonight Show with Johnny Carson, and he also did radio commentary for The Simpsons for several seasons.

Plotinus (; , Plōtînos;  – 270 CE) was a philosopher in the Hellenistic tradition, born and raised in Roman Egypt. Plotinus is regarded by modern scholarship as the founder of Neoplatonism. His teacher was the self-taught philosopher Ammonius Saccas, who belonged to the Platonic tradition. Historians of the 19th century invented the term "Neoplatonism" and applied it to refer to Plotinus and his philosophy, which was vastly influential during Late Antiquity, the Middle Ages, and the Renaissance. Much of the biographical information about Plotinus comes from Porphyry's preface to his edition of Plotinus' most notable literary work, The Enneads.

Norman Quentin Cook ( born Quentin Leo Cook ; 31st July 1963 ) , also known by his stage name Kool Keith (from the name Kool Keith) was an English rapper, record producer, and television presenter. He was a member of the hip hop group A Tribe Called Quest.Cook and his group first appeared as a group on BBC Radio 1 in April 1986, initially as an instrumental track. Kellie Leitch is a Canadian politician and candidate for the federal Conservative Party of Canada. She was born and raised in Ottawa, Ontario, Canada, and has lived there since she was 11 years old.

Year 1155 (MCLV) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  Siege of Tortona: German forces capture the citadel of Tortona (after a two-month siege). The city is razed to the ground, including the graves. June 18 – King Frederick I (Barbarossa) is crowned as Emperor of the Holy Roman Empire by Pope Adrian IV at St. Peter's Basilica in Rome. Arnold of Brescia is exiled by Adrian IV and forced to flee. He is arrested by imperial forces; hanged and his body burned at the stake in Rome.

The Australian Secret Intelligence Service  (ASIS) is the foreign intelligence agency of Australia, tasked with the covert collection of information overseas through personal contacts and other means of human intelligence. It is part of the Australian Intelligence Community and is also responsible for counter-intelligence and liaising with the intelligence agencies of other countries. ASIS was formed in 1952 but its existence remained secret within much of the government until 1972. ASIS is compared to the American CIA and the British MI6.ASIS is part of the Department of Foreign Affairs and Trade (DFAT) portfolio and has its headquarters in Canberra.

Great Barrier Island lies in the outer Hauraki Gulf , New Zealand , north-east of central Auckland . With an area of 16,300 km2, the Island is one of the world's largest and has a population of 2.7 million. It is the southernmost of the Pacific Islands, and has no permanent settlements. The Great Barrier Reef consists of more than 4,300 islands in the north-central Australian region, with each island consisting of a reef, cay, lagoon, or reef-dwelling invertebrate and plant species. The reef is a large, complex and important natural area of the world's oceans; the largest natural reef complex in the world.

Monte Cassino (today usually spelled Montecassino) is a rocky hill about  southeast of Rome, in the Latin Valley, Italy,  west of Cassino and at an elevation of . Site of the Roman town of Casinum, it is widely known for its abbey, the first house of the Benedictine Order, having been established by Benedict of Nursia himself around 529. It was for the community of Monte Cassino that the Rule of Saint Benedict was composed.The first monastery on Monte Cassino was sacked by the invading Lombards around 570 and abandoned. Of the first monastery almost nothing is known.

Adenine  (symbol A or Ade) is a nucleobase (a purine derivative). It is one of the four nucleobases in the nucleic acid of DNA that are represented by the letters G–C–A–T. The three others are guanine, cytosine and thymine. Its derivatives have a variety of roles in biochemistry including cellular respiration, in the form of both the energy-rich adenosine triphosphate (ATP) and the cofactors nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide (NAD), flavin adenine dinucleotide (FAD) and Coenzyme A. It also has functions in protein synthesis and as a chemical component of DNA and RNA.

Pope Leo VII (; died 13 July 939) was the bishop of Rome and nominal ruler of the Papal States from 3 January 936 to his death.Election Leo VII's election to the papacy in 936, after the death of Pope John XI, was secured by Alberic II of Spoleto, the ruler of Rome at the time. Alberic wanted to choose the pope so that the papacy would continue to yield to his authority. Leo was the priest of the church of San Sisto Vecchio in Rome, thought to be a Benedictine monk.

The Burrows–Wheeler transform ( BWT , also called block-sorting compression ) rearranges a character string into runs of similar characters, called chunks, according to a specific algorithm. Calculus, also called the theory of functions (and sometimes more accurately, the theory of limits), is a branch of mathematics in which the study of functions of a certain kind is concerned. The subject is especially important in algebra, geometry and number theory. In algebra, it is closely connected with the algebraic approach to analysis.Calculus can be used in many disciplines, including mathematics, physics and engineering.

Blake Edwards (born William Blake Crump; July 26, 1922 – December 15, 2010) was an American actor, film director, producer and screenwriter.Edwards began his career in the 1940s as an actor, but he soon began writing screenplays and radio scripts before turning to producing and directing in television and films. His best-known films include Breakfast at Tiffany's, Days of Wine and Roses, 10, Victor/Victoria, and the hugely successful Pink Panther film series with British actor Peter Sellers. Often thought of as primarily a director of comedies, he also directed several drama, musical, and detective films.

A software bug is an error, flaw or fault in computer software that causes it to produce an incorrect or unexpected result, or to behave in unintended ways. The process of finding and correcting bugs is termed "debugging" and often uses formal techniques or tools to pinpoint bugs. Since the 1950s some computer systems have been designed to deter, detect or auto-correct various computer bugs during operations.Most bugs arise from mistakes and errors made in either a program's design or its source code, or in components and operating systems used by such programs.

In electronics, a multiplexer (or mux; spelled sometimes as multiplexor), also known as a data selector, is a device that selects between several analog or digital input signals and forwards the selected input to a single output line. The selection is directed by a separate set of digital inputs known as select lines. A multiplexer of  inputs has  select lines, which are used to select which input line to send to the output.A multiplexer makes it possible for several input signals to share one device or resource, for example, one analog-to-digital converter or one communications transmission medium, instead of having one device per input signal.

The European Bank for Reconstruction and Development ( EBRD ) is an international financial institution founded in 1991 . As a leading multilateral development bank with offices in over 70 countries, it was the first multilateral financial institution established in the world to be based outside of its founding member state. The European Union (EU) is a member-state political union of 28 member-states based in the European Union. It is an economic union with the European Union and the Council of Europe. It also has links with its neighbours in Central and East Europe, the former Soviet Republics, as well as with several countries in Latin America.

The National Guard is a state-based military force that becomes part of the reserve components of the United States Army. The Guard was created as an independent service by the National Guard Article 165, and it was not created as part of the regular Army. John W. McAfee  (born July 12, 1954) is an American computer security consultant, computer software entrepreneur, and inventor of the McAfee anti-virus software. McAfee has created and marketed a series of computer security products and solutions, including McAfee Antivirus, McAfee LiveSafe, McAfee RapidFire, McAfee SafeSearch and McAfee Trace.

Alain Marie Pascal Prost ( born 24 February 1955 ) is a French retired racing driver . A four-time Formula 1 Champion, Prost is one of only two people, along with Jules Bianchi , to have been victorious in all four of Formula 1's Grand Prix series (1999–2013), and the first of only four people to have driven in all four championships. He also won a World Championship with Lotus in 1979, becoming the first person in Formula 1 history to be awarded the Driver and Team of the Season award twice. Prost retired in 2014 after a long-term battle with motor neurone disease.

Harlequin ( ; ; ) is the best-known of the zanni or comic servant characters from the Italian commedia dell'arte (Italian: comic opera) genre, particularly Italian versions in which the character is played by a singing or dancing performer.The term is a combination of "le ritardiere", an archaic form of "ritorno" meaning servant, and an old term for a zanni. The character originated as a character created by comic opera playwright Carlo Veronese in the late 1870s for the popular Italian comic opera, La nocezanne di Bizantino.

A U-Boot is a beer cocktail that is made by placing a shot of vodka into a glass of beer, typically a lager. It is popular in Germany, Poland, North Macedonia, and Flanders. In Germany, the liquor korn is sometimes used instead, while in Flanders and the Netherlands, jonge jenever is preferred.It is called a U-Boot (German abbreviation of Unterseeboot, "submarine") because the shot glass of vodka sinks to the bottom of the glass of beer. The shot glass then "surfaces" when the cocktail is drunk.Preparation Place a shot glass on upside down glass and fill it with vodka.

Scooby-Doo is an American animated franchise comprising many animated television series produced from 1969 to the present , as well as several feature films. It is based on the Hanna Barbera franchise.History The franchise started in the early 1960s during the early days of television, and was originally known as The Scooby and the Gang. The series started as two separate programs produced by Warner Bros. Television for CBS in the early 1960s. In 1966, CBS picked up both programs and turned the Scooby gang into a weekly series, which became a popular syndicated series on the WB network.

An adverb is a word or an expression that modifies a verb , adjective , another adverb , determiner , or other word. American English is an American-based dialect of English, created by speakers of the English-speaking British Commonwealth during the first two centuries after the Norman conquest of England in 1066, and maintained by their descendants throughout the twentieth century.The word American was first used by a British official to denote a person from the British Isles (as opposed to the continental British Isles), but quickly became widely used in the US to describe people from the US.

The Battle of Lechfeld was a series of military engagements over the course of three days from 10–12 August 955 between the Frankish Army under Duke William the Martel's troops and the Eastern Army under Emperor Otto I. It was the final major offensive of the Great Schism. The Blue Whale is a type of whale found in the waters around Japan. It is thought to have been introduced into Japan by a Korean ship in the 13th century. In the 19th century, the whale was popularised in Japanese folklore and myths, and it has since come to symbolize death and suicide.

Hex is a two player abstract strategy board game in which players attempt to connect opposite sides of a hexagonal grid in an effort to achieve points in various ways such as completing a line, clearing the board, advancing a group of resources or conquering a city. The player who completes the most lines on the board, wins. Hexen is a two-player game of strategy board games, in which players complete lines of hexagonal tiles, each of which is connected to every other. The game has a hexagonal board, in which players place their hexagons on adjacent rows or columns.

Pope Gregory VII ( ; 1015 – 25 May 1085 ) , born Hildebrand of Sovana , was head of the papal household for the first twenty-five years of his reign, and served as the Pope of the Roman Catholic Church from 827 until his death. He had been chosen as a cardinal by Pope John XXII on 1 November 1095 to fill the vacant seat left by the assassination of Gregory IX in October 1087, and took the title Pope Gregory X on 25 January 1111. He was named cardinal by the pope at his last canonization Mass in St. Peter's Basilica on 13 January 1138.

Giovanni Pacini ( 17 February 17966 December 1867 ) was an Italian composer , best known for his operas . He was born in Rome in 17966 and died there.BiographyPacini was born in Rome in 17966 and died in Rome in 1867. Anarchy (or anarcho-capitalism), sometimes abbreviated to anarchist , is a political and economic philosophy, especially one that advocates the absence of government regulation or intervention in the economic or social affairs of individuals, groups, and communities, in contrast with the state. It differs from classical liberalism in the emphasis it puts on decentralization and individualism, while classical liberalism favors the state regulation of the economy.

Tamar the Great ( , lit . `` King Tamar '' ) ( 1160 – 18 January 1213 ) reigned as the Holy Roman Empire's regent between 1168 and 1170, when his younger brother Conrad IV, known as the Holy Saxon, was crowned emperor. In 1181 he abdicated and became a monk of the Holy Mount in Jerusalem. He was then elected King of Jerusalem by the Jews in 1185 and was crowned emperor in 1198.Tamar's ascension came at a turbulent time. In 1155, during the reign of Holy Roman Emperor Conrad V, the Holy Roman Empire and the Carolingian Empire were on the verge of conflict.

Dorset (; archaically: Dorsetshire) is a county in South West England on the English Channel coast. The ceremonial county comprises the unitary authority areas of Bournemouth, Christchurch and Poole and Dorset. Covering an area of , Dorset borders Devon to the west, Somerset to the north-west, Wiltshire to the north-east, and Hampshire to the east. The county town is Dorchester which is  in the south. After the reorganisation of local government in 1974, the county's border was extended eastward to incorporate the Hampshire towns of Bournemouth and Christchurch.

The Northrop Grumman RQ-4 Global Hawk is a high-altitude , remotely-piloted surveillance aircraft . It was initially designed by Ryan Whitcomb and John Boyd for the U.S. Air Force and the United Kingdom's Ministry of Defense.The aircraft was first flown by a pilot in August 1991. It later entered service with the United States Air Force in January 1995, with the Air Force's 11th Rescue Squadron. In September 2002, the Air Force awarded the aircraft its Air Force Leadership Award, the first time a military aircraft has been awarded such an award for outstanding achievement during wartime.

Heliox is a breathing gas mixture of helium (He) and oxygen (O2).Heliox is a medical treatment for patients with difficulty breathing. The mixture generates less resistance than atmospheric air when passing through the airways of the lungs, and thus requires less effort by a patient to breathe in and out of the lungs.Heliox has been used medically since the 1930s, and although the medical community adopted it initially to alleviate symptoms of upper airway obstruction, its range of medical uses has since expanded greatly, mostly because of the low density of the gas.

Brave New World is a dystopian social science fiction novel by English author Aldous Huxley , written in 1931 and published in 1934. It was Huxley's second novel, following The Doors of Perception (1925), which is considered his greatest and most influential work, and it is one of his best-loved. It is one of the few novelistic works that is considered a classic today, and many contemporary writers cite it as a work they consider foundational to the development of speculative fiction as a whole.Set in a near-future near-future, the story begins in the year 1930, shortly before the outbreak of World War II.

The M102 is a light , towable 105 mm howitzer used by the United States Army in the Vietnam War and the Gulf War. It was intended to provide direct fire support, as well as artillery and antitank support, against fixed-wing aircraft and ground targets. The howitzer is equipped with a 30 mm automatic gun and can be used in an anti-armor role as well as in a self-propelled fire support role, in which it can be used by ground forces. The weapon can fire a total of about 8,250 rounds per minute.

George Catlett Marshall Jr. ( December 31 , 1880 – October 16 , 1959 ) was an American army officer who led troops in several wars against the Japanese from 1895 to 1945. He was born on December 31, 1880, in Boston, Massachusetts, to a prosperous family of German ancestry. At the age of 18, Marshall received his law degree from Boston University School of Law, and went on to study law at Boston University and Columbia University. He was a graduate student at Harvard when Japan began its colonization of Manchuria in 1895.

Antioch on the Orontes (; , Antiókheia hē epì Oróntou; also Syrian Antioch) was a Hellenistic city side of the Orontes River. Its ruins lie near the current city of Antakya, Turkey, to which the ancient city lends its name.Antioch was founded near the end of the fourth century BC by Seleucus I Nicator, one of Alexander the Great's generals. The city's geographical, military, and economic location benefited its occupants, particularly such features as the spice trade, the Silk Road, and the Royal Road. It eventually rivaled Alexandria as the chief city of the Near East.

The University of California , Los Angeles ( UCLA ) is a public land-grant research university in Los Angeles , California , the fourth largest university in the United States by enrollment. With an enrollment of over 43,800,000, UCLA is ranked as the second-largest public university in the United States and the fourth-largest system in the West, after UCLA in Los Angeles and Cal Poly-SLO in San Luis Obispo, California . The University of California, Los Angeles also has a major research center, the Robert A. Fink Center for New Venture, Innovation, and Entrepreneurship. The school is also affiliated with Stanford University.

The War Game is a 1966 British pseudo-documentary film that depicts a nuclear war and its aftermath. Written, directed and produced by Peter Watkins for the BBC, it caused dismay within the BBC and also within government, and was subsequently withdrawn before the provisional screening date of 6 October 1965. The corporation said that "the effect of the film has been judged by the BBC to be too horrifying for the medium of broadcasting. It will, however, be shown to invited audiences..."The film eventually premiered at the National Film Theatre in London, on 13 April 1966, where it ran until 3 May.

Year 931 ( CMXXXI ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) in the eleventh lunar month. This year's full moon occurred on 19 January . The year also included three new moons, and was the year in which the calendar began to move backwards by one lunar month (the next full moon in the year would fall on 29 July ), the first year it changed by one lunar month since 901. This change was due to changes to the lunar cycle and caused by a lunar eclipse in 907 BC.The year ended with a new moon.

In philosophy , systems theory , science , and art , emergence occurs when an entity is observed to have a certain property after its existence is inferred in a system of causally connected events. An example is that a car's engine starts and moves when a person puts in the key, and that the car accelerates when the key is released.In philosophy, systems theory , and the study of emergence , the concept of emergence is often described as a form of emergence in which a process, event, or process can exist in isolation from all the other elements of a given system.

The European Organization for Nuclear Research , known as CERN (; ; derived from the name ), is a European research organization that operates the largest particle physics laboratory in the world. Established in 1954, the organization is based in a northwest suburb of Geneva on the Franco–Swiss border and has 23 member states. Israel is the only non-European country granted full membership. CERN is an official United Nations Observer.The acronym CERN is also used to refer to the laboratory, which in 2019 had 2,660 scientific, technical, and administrative staff members, and hosted about 12,400 users from institutions in more than 70 countries.

`` The Ones Who Walk Away from Omelas '' is a 1973 work of short philosophical fiction by American writer John Brunner.PlotThe film tells the story of an alien named Pyle, whose ship has crashed in the desert, and of his attempts to establish a village on the planet Omelas. The story is told in first-person narration by a character named Pyle, who describes events as they occur to him. The Oracle of Delphi ( , ) is an ancient Athenian and Mycenaean city on the Ionian coast of Attica, located on the east coast of Attica.

In economics, inflation refers to a general progressive increase in prices of goods and services in an economy. When the general price level rises, each unit of currency buys fewer goods and services; consequently, inflation corresponds to a reduction in the purchasing power of money. The opposite of inflation is deflation, a sustained decrease in the general price level of goods and services. The common measure of inflation is the inflation rate, the annualised percentage change in a general price index.Prices will not all increase at the same rates. Attaching a representative value to a set of prices is an instance of the index number problem.

A nuclear thermal rocket ( NTR ) is a type of thermal rocket where the heat from a nuclear reaction generates thrust that is fed back into the nuclear reaction to power an upper stage rocket. The rocket's primary function is to place a propellant mass in a desired orbital location, typically to escape from Earth's gravitational pull, and to provide that mass with thrust to escape from Earth's atmosphere. A NTR can launch payloads of several hundred kilograms or more into low-earth orbit, where they have a perigee of roughly 1,100 kilometers and an apogee of about 3,600 kilometers.

Crocodiles ( family Crocodylidae ) or true crocodiles are large semiaquatic reptiles that live throughout the tropics in Africa , the Americas and Australia . All species are native to warm temperate water, although some species have been introduced to the tropics. They are found in tropical and temperate environments, including freshwater, brackish, salt, and brackish–marine habitats. Cryptography, also known as the study of secure communication, encryption, or digital security, is the study of systems that prevent, or at least make it difficult for an intruder to, gain access to confidential information.

Commander Keen is a series of side-scrolling platform video games developed primarily by id Software . The series consists of two main games and four sequels. The games were originally developed and published for the Atari 8-bit home console, but have gained significant sales in the following decades as they are ported to a wide variety of platforms, most notably PC, PlayStation and Nintendo GameCube.The series' first game was Commander Keen and the Space Mutants, which was released for MS-DOS and Windows in 1993, and later ported to the Nintendo GameCube and Sega Mega Drive/Genesis in 1996.

Clothing ( also known as clothes , apparel , and attire ) are items worn on the body . Typically, clothing does not serve as an integral part of clothing , rather, they serve as an accessory. Clothing includes clothing made of the same material as the wearer and any items worn with the body, such as boots, gloves, a hat, or a cap. It is also used to designate clothing worn indoors. A variety of other items that serve to cover or hide the human body may also be included in the definition of clothing, such as masks, scarves, or headwear.

His Dark Materials is a trilogy of fantasy novels by Philip Pullman consisting of Northern Lights ( 1995 ; published by Granta Books, New York), his sixth novel, and the prequel The Subtle Knife (1996; published by Little Brown and Co., New York), the second of these two books being published in May of this year. Aristotle  (; ; ) was a Greek polymath and natural philosopher. His major works include the On the Soul  and Nicomachean Ethics. His life was an important event in the Early Modern Period and is often considered the founding figure of Western science.

Nitrous oxide, commonly known as laughing gas, nitrous, or nos, is a chemical compound, an oxide of nitrogen with the formula . At room temperature, it is a colourless non-flammable gas, with a slight metallic scent and taste. At elevated temperatures, nitrous oxide is a powerful oxidiser similar to molecular oxygen.Nitrous oxide has significant medical uses, especially in surgery and dentistry, for its anaesthetic and pain reducing effects. Its colloquial name, "laughing gas", coined by Humphry Davy, is due to the euphoric effects upon inhaling it, a property that has led to its recreational use as a dissociative anaesthetic.

The granny knot is a binding knot, used to secure a rope or line around an object. It is considered inferior to the reef knot (square knot), which it superficially resembles. Neither of these knots should be used as a bend knot for attaching two ropes together.Etymology Called the "granny's knot" with references going back to at least 1849, the knot was so-called because it is "the natural knot tied by women or landsmen".TyingWhen attempting to tie a reef knot (square knot), it is easy to produce a granny knot accidentally.

Hildegard Frieda Albertine Knef (; 28 December 19251 February 2002) was a German actress, voice actress, singer, and writer. She was billed in some English-language films as Hildegard Neff or Hildegarde Neff.Early yearsHildegard Knef was born in Ulm in 1925. Her parents were Hans Theodor and Friede Augustine Knef. Her father, a condecorated First World War veteran, died of syphilis when she was only six months old, and her mother moved to Berlin and worked in a factory. Knef began studying acting at age 14 in 1940. She left school at 15 to become an apprentice animator with Universum Film AG.

Year 877 ( DCCCLXXVII ) was a common year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) with the Julian calendar. The year starts on the first leap day of the Gregorian calendar, which was introduced in 1682. The Earth (, , , ) is the primary body of the Solar System, the only planet to have an atmosphere and surface. It is the second-largest planet in the solar system, containing approximately the mass of Jupiter and a radius of 2,371 kilometres, making it one of the largest planets in our solar system and one of the most massive known objects in the universe.

Stephanie Lynn Nicks (born May 26, 1948) is an American singer, songwriter, and producer known for her work with the band Fleetwood Mac and as a solo artist.After starting her career as a duo with her then-boyfriend Lindsey Buckingham, releasing the album Buckingham Nicks to little success, Nicks joined Fleetwood Mac in 1975, helping the band to become one of the best-selling music acts of all time with over 120 million records sold worldwide. Rumours, the band's second album with Nicks, became one of the best-selling albums of all time, being certified 20× platinum in the US.

The PalmPilot Personal and PalmPilot Professional are the second generation of Palm PDA devices produced by Palm Inc (then a subsidiary of U.S. Robotics, later 3Com). These devices were launched on March 10, 1997.Accessories and pricingPalm also sold the 10201U modem at 14.4 kbit/s, introduced at a price of $129 (this modem is also compatible with the Palm III and Palm IIIx devices). An upgrade kit was also available, which allowed users of the earlier Pilot 1000/5000 devices to upgrade the OS, ROM, and RAM to match the PalmPilot Professional.

A museum ( ; plural museums or, rarely, musea) is a building or institution that cares for and displays a collection of artifacts and other objects of artistic, cultural, historical, or scientific importance. Many public museums make these items available for public viewing through exhibits that may be permanent or temporary. The largest museums are located in major cities throughout the world, while thousands of local museums exist in smaller cities, towns, and rural areas. Museums have varying aims, ranging from the conservation and documentation of their collection, serving researchers and specialists to catering to the general public.

Domenico Cimarosa (; 17 December 1749 – 11 January 1801) was an Italian composer of the Neapolitan school and of the Classical period. He wrote more than eighty operas, the best known of which is Il matrimonio segreto (1792); most of his operas are comedies. He also wrote instrumental works and church music.Cimarosa was principally based in Naples, but spent some of his career in various other parts of Italy, composing for the opera houses of Rome, Venice, Florence and elsewhere. He was engaged by the empress of Russia Catherine the Great as her court composer and conductor between 1787 and 1791.

Parasports are sports played by people with a disability , including physical and intellectual disabilities . Some parasports are forms of sport for disabled people that are popular with other people. Examples include wheelchair rugby , wheelchair basketball , wheelchair rugby , handball, wheelchair rugby league, wheelchair rugby union and wheelchair tennis.The sport is also often referred to as 'handball with wheels' or 'wheelbarrow cricket' (or sometimes simply 'cricket' or 'cricket') due to its origins in wheelbarrow sport.HistoryIn 1835, the first wheelchair rugby match was played at the annual Rugby Union Congress.

In music performance and notation, legato (; Italian for "tied together"; French lié; German gebunden) indicates that musical notes are played or sung smoothly and connected. That is, the player makes a transition from note to note with no intervening silence. Legato technique is required for slurred performance, but unlike slurring (as that term is interpreted for some instruments), legato does not forbid re-articulation.Standard notation indicates legato either with the word legato, or by a slur (a curved line) under notes that form one legato group.

Humour ( Commonwealth English ) or humor ( American English ) is the tendency of experiences to provoke laughter and to elicit enjoyment and relief. It is a common component of many forms of entertainment, such as entertainment shows, film, radio and television, comedy, satire, fiction, and even literature. Humour is a type of irony or satire in which characters are seen to use a form of mockery and irony to reveal their internal emotional and moral state, either in order to mock something or to gain a sense of enjoyment.

Year 1493 ( MCDXCIII ) was a common year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) in the Julian Calendar and ending on Saturday. It is also known as Year 1494 in the Gregorian Calendar and is known by the name of Year 1393 in the English Calendar. Year 1393 was the longest year since the first calculation was made. In computer science, file system access is the process of manipulating and retrieving data stored in a file system. File system access typically involves modifying, deleting, or moving data, as opposed to retrieving data as is done with other types of access.

Aden ( , ; Yemeni : ) is a city , and since 2015 , the temporary capital of Yemen, and the third largest city in the Arabian Peninsula, after Sanaa and Aden. The city was the seat of Al Qaeda in the Arabian Peninsula, a terrorist group designated a terrorist organisation by the United States and United Nations. In November 2014, after the death of Muhammad Ali Salman Al-Aiban, Aden's governor, the United States designated it the target of an air campaign, and in December 2016 it was the target of an intensified attack by Yemeni troops.

The granny knot is a binding knot , used to secure a rope or line around an object . It is an abbreviation for the French words for "giraffe knot". The exact meaning is unknown.It is traditionally tied at the bottom. Gravy  is a fluid used by birds and mammals in the digestive system to ferment. It consists of animal and plant matter. It has a distinctive taste, but can be flavored or colored. Gravy can be made of meat or plant matter; it does not have to be from an animal to be edible.

Thetis ( ; ) , is a figure from Greek mythology with varying mythological roles . She mainly appears as the wife of Poseidon ( , , ; ), mother of Heracles (Heracles), daughter of Eurynome (Eryne, ; , ) and wife of Polyphemus . The name Heracles has come to mean "champion of victory" or "heaven's champion". Hydrogen is the lightest element in the periodic table and a fundamental element of the chemical family Hydrogen . Hydrogen atoms are the simplest of the three types of atoms found in the periodic table, the hydrogen nucleus being the nucleus of most chemical elements.

The Sikorsky UH-60 Black Hawk is a four-blade , twin-engine , medium-lift utility helicopter manufactured by Sikorsky Aircraft . Sikorsky is one of the most successful helicopter manufacturers in the world. It was founded in 1926 and is based in New York City. The Black Hawk is the world's third most frequently produced helicopter and has a service life exceeding 100,000 hours.In addition, the Sikorsky UH-60 fleet has accumulated more than 1,600 flight hours.HistoryEarly developmentThe Black Hawk was developed as a replacement for the UH-1. The Black Hawk's primary role was to fly into remote regions and conduct humanitarian missions such as search and rescue and humanitarian disaster relief operations.

Thomas Becket , also known as Saint Thomas of Canterbury , Thomas of London and later Thomas à Becket (died 9 October 1216; age 80), was an English theologian and monk, known for his writings on the spiritual life.Born at Canterbury Abbey, Canterbury, Becket is also known to historians as one of the first English martyrs. His early life was spent at the Abbey of St. Mary Woolnoth, where he became a monk. He is said to have lived in isolation in his cell, reading and writing, until the death of his father, who was imprisoned in the abbey.

A gas nuclear reactor (or gas fueled reactor or vapor core reactor) is a proposed kind of nuclear reactor in which the nuclear fuel would be in a gaseous state rather than liquid or solid. In this type of reactor, the only temperature-limiting materials would be the reactor walls. Conventional reactors have stricter limitations because the core would melt if the fuel temperature were to rise too high. It may also be possible to confine gaseous fission fuel magnetically, electrostatically or electrodynamically so that it would not touch (and melt) the reactor walls.

General Dynamics Electric Boat (GDEB) is a subsidiary of General Dynamics Corporation. It has been the primary builder of submarines for the United States Navy for more than 100 years. The company's main facilities are a shipyard in Groton, Connecticut, a hull-fabrication and outfitting facility in Quonset Point, Rhode Island, and a design and engineering facility in New London, Connecticut.HistoryThe company was founded in 1899 by Isaac Rice as the Electric Boat Company to build John Philip Holland's submersible ship designs, which were developed at Lewis Nixon's Crescent Shipyard in Elizabeth, New Jersey.

Turandot ( , ; see below ) is an opera in three acts by Giacomo Puccini , posthumously completed by Giampiero Conti (1797–1861) in 1812. The story is set in Bari, a seaside town in Tuscany, Italy, and tells of the love affair between Pier Luca Bernini, a young but wealthy nobleman from Bari and a young peasant girl. It was later adapted into two operas in English, one in 1822 and the other in 1893, and then to a film version, starring Marisa Tomei, in 1978.

Linus Carl Pauling (; February 28, 1901 – August 19, 1994) was an American chemist, biochemist, chemical engineer,  peace activist, author, and educator. He published more than 1,200 papers and books, of which about 850 dealt with scientific topics. New Scientist called him one of the 20 greatest scientists of all time, and as of 2000, he was rated the 16th most important scientist in history. For his scientific work, Pauling was awarded the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in 1954. For his peace activism, he was awarded the Nobel Peace Prize in 1962.

In commutative algebra , the prime spectrum ( or simply the spectrum ) of a ring R is the set of all integers  such that no integer  modifies any other integer in R, with each integer  either prime or composite. It is usually written R = , or  mod , as in R =  mod . A group is a family of finite groups. Although there are several kinds of groups, the simplest are abelian groups, consisting of a subset of integers , and the groups  and  of . Abelian groups are commutative groups (or in topology, homomorphisms), and  can be viewed as a subgroup of .

A cigarette is a narrow cylinder containing burnable material, typically tobacco, that is rolled into thin paper for smoking. The cigarette is ignited at one end, causing it to smolder; the resulting smoke is orally inhaled via the opposite end. Cigarette smoking is the most common method of tobacco consumption. Manufacturers have described the cigarette as "a drug administration system for the delivery of nicotine in acceptable and attractive form." The term cigarette, as commonly used, refers to a tobacco cigarette, but the word is sometimes used to refer to other substances, such as a cannabis (Jazz) cigarette or an herbal cigarette.

is a Japanese manga series written and illustrated by Rumiko Takahashi . It was serialized in Big Comic Spirits from 1996 to 1996, and published in the magazine Bessatsu Friend from 2000 to 2001. It was a manga-only anthology title until 2003, before it was licensed for anime production by Sunrise. It is currently licensed for anime productions by Studio Ghibli. The manga was originally serialized in the magazine Weekly Shōnen Champion for 12 chapters from October 1996 to October 1997, and published in a combined book and DVD format in November 1998.

Triskaidekaphobia ( , ; ) is fear or avoidance of the number . It is also a reason for the fear of number, which can be a source of great joy and comfort, and may cause a sense of loss when the reason for fear or avoidance becomes clear.Symptoms and TypesAlthough there are many possible syndromes, the five most common ones are phobia, dread, anxiety and phobic disorder, or a combination of all five.Phobias are physical reactions to stimuli. In most cases they develop in response to an external force such as a fear of heights, an animal, or certain smells.

In economics , inflation refers to a general progressive increase in prices of goods and services in an economy . In some countries , it may be used to refer to the prices of consumer goods or the prices of financial services. In countries with high inflation such as India and Turkey, when measured against the exchange rate, prices have become progressively higher than they were previously. In computing, an arbitrary precision calculator is a device which is capable of performing any of a variety of operations on floating-point numbers in fixed decimal form, at the fixed decimal precision of the computer's system bus.

The PalmPilot Personal and PalmPilot Professional are the second generation of Palm PDA devices produced by Palm Inc ( then Palm Computing). The first generation was manufactured by Palm for Palm Pilot's launch in December 1999. It was a revolutionary product in many ways: it was the first PDA with an integrated touchscreen, allowing users to perform complex operations using gestures and voice.The first-generation Palm Pilot is still widely used today, and is still manufactured by Palm Inc. It is compatible with a number of Palm applications.The first-generation device featured a monochrome black and white screen with a 16-bit color graphics processor.

Tilburg is a city and municipality in the Netherlands , in the southern province of North Brabant . With a population of 7,000 in 2010, it is the third largest municipality in the province, and the fourth-largest in the Netherlands . The city is part of the Brabant region, and has a large international airport, with international flights to more than 200 destinations worldwide.Tilburg is in the middle of Brabant. It is located at the western edge of Brabant-Wallonie (Brabant municipality), the region that has long been the cultural heart of the city of Tilburg and the province.Tilburg has a long and colourful history and remains a city of contrasts.

The word comes from the Japanese word for logographic characters of the Chinese script , which were made a major part of ancient Chinese writing in the 8th century.HistoryThe earliest known written language is Proto-Canaanite (also known as Proto-Phoenician) which, along with Egyptian hieroglyphs and Linear B scripts, formed the base of Ancient Egypt's writing system, which developed from cuneiform in Mesopotamia after the Mesopotamian civilisations had collapsed around 2600 BC.The Ancient Egyptian script has been found to be based on the Elamite and Akkadian scripts. Al-Jawhar (Arabic: اجر طوار‎) is a large city in Syria.

The bowline ( or ) is an ancient and simple knot used to form a fixed loop at the end of a rope. It has the virtues of being both easy to tie and untie; most notably, it is easy to untie after being subjected to a load. The bowline is sometimes referred to as King of the knots because of its importance. Along with the sheet bend and the clove hitch, the bowline is often considered one of the most essential knots. The common bowline shares some structural similarity with the sheet bend. Virtually all end-to-end joining knots (i.e., bends) have a corresponding loop knot.

was the 75th emperor of Japan , according to the traditional order of succession.Sutoku 's reign spanned the years from 1638 to 1668, and from 1668 until his death at age 81. Sutoku was the last of the three emperors of the Tōkyō dynasty who reigned from the 11th century, and the last of the four emperor-to-be in Japan, following the death of the Empress Tokugawa Iemitsu.BiographyBorn in Kyoto, Sutoku served as governor of Nagasaki Province under Toyotomi Hideyoshi in 1632 and 1635. In 1636 he went to Nagasaki, and by 1640 he was governor of Izu Island (now Sasebo City in Nagasaki Prefecture).

Niacin, also known as nicotinic acid, is an organic compound and a form of vitamin B3, an essential human nutrient. It can be manufactured by plants and animals from the amino acid tryptophan. Niacin is obtained in the diet from a variety of whole and processed foods, with highest contents in fortified packaged foods, meat, poultry, red fish such as tuna and salmon, lesser amounts in nuts, legumes and seeds. Niacin as a dietary supplement is used to treat pellagra, a disease caused by niacin deficiency. Signs and symptoms of pellagra include skin and mouth lesions, anemia, headaches, and tiredness.

Pizza Hut is an American multinational restaurant chain and international franchise founded in 1958 in Wichita , Kansas by Dan Barber. The chain was originally known as Pizza Hut, Inc. It has since expanded to include over 800 locations in over 30 countries and territories, and employs over 100,000 people worldwide. Pork-free is the term used to describe any meatless food item. Pork-free food products are typically lower in fat, sodium, sugar and saturated fat than the standard products. They usually have fewer calories and fewer nutrients, such as fat and calories.

The Boston transportation system includes roadway, subway, regional rail, air, and sea options for passenger and freight transit in Boston, Massachusetts. The Massachusetts Port Authority (Massport) operates the Port of Boston, which includes a container shipping facility in South Boston, and Logan International Airport, in East Boston. The Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority (MBTA) operates bus, subway, short-distance rail, and water ferry passenger services throughout the city and region. Amtrak operates passenger rail service to and from major northeastern cities. A major bus terminal at South Station is served by varied intercity bus companies.

The Viking program consisted of a pair of identical American space probes, Viking 1 and Viking 2, which landed on Mars in 1976. Each spacecraft was composed of two main parts: an orbiter designed to photograph the surface of Mars from orbit, and a lander designed to study the planet from the surface. The orbiters also served as communication relays for the landers once they touched down.The Viking program grew from NASA's earlier, even more ambitious, Voyager Mars program, which was not related to the successful Voyager deep space probes of the late 1970s.

Columbina ( in Italian Colombina , meaning `` little dove '' ; in French and English Colombine ) is a large and prominent city located in the Val d'Aosta area of Sicily, a mountainous county in the central region of the Italian peninsula. It is a major metropolitan city of Sicily and a major tourist destination. Chester, officially the town of Chester, is the seat of the County of Chester, United Kingdom and a constituent county within the County of Westmorland and Lonsdale, United Kingdom. It was named in honor of King William the Lion-Hearted in 1181.

The BBC World Service is an international broadcaster owned and operated by the BBC , with funding from the British Government. It provides news and information to approximately 150 countries across the globe, in more than 60 different languages, as well as providing international radio broadcasts in more than 140 countries, and its radio services reach more than 120 million households globally. The Book of Mormon is a book in the Bible. It is an ancient text, written in ancient Egyptian and Akkadian cuneiform, from approximately 400 BCE to 100 CE.

Paclitaxel ( PTX ) , sold under the brand name Taxol among others , is a chemotherapy medication used to treat cancer. It is also used as an anticancer agent (anti-cancer) and as an immunomodulator for treating certain cancers. It inhibits the cyclin dependent kinase B pathway, a pathway involved in the growth and progression of cancer cells. It is also a non-competitive inhibitor of a protein called cyclin D2, and inhibits the gene transcription of cyclin-D2. Tobacco has been used in many forms, but the most widely used is the cigarette. It is an addictive drug that produces acute respiratory and central nervous system effects.

Mycenae ( ; or , Mykē̂nai or Mykḗnē ) is an archaeological site near Mykines in Argolis , north-eastern Peloponnese. The site is situated on the southern slope of Mount Agios, about half an hour drive from the town of Mykines. It is located in a plain, about 4.5km (3.2mi) south of the town. It lies on a hill that provides a panoramic view to the Peloponnese, the Greek mainland, and the Adriatic Sea. It is one of the world's largest Mycenaean archaeological excavations. It has become a place of pilgrimage for Mycenaeans.

Eugène Adrien Roland Georges Garros ( ; 6 October 1888 – 5 October 1918 ) was a French pioneering aviator who achieved the first successful solo transatlantic crossing of the Atlantic Ocean in 1903.Garros made his first attempt to fly over land in 1904, but the flight ended in a crash when his monoplane fell from the sky and smashed into a nearby house, killing Garros. Galilean logic, also known as classical logic, was a set theory based on classical mathematics that has been a part of logic for at least the last four hundred years and probably longer.

The following outline is provided as an overview of and topical guide to the history of South Asia : History of India
Sikhism, also known as Hindustani or Khalsaism, is a monotheistic religion that has its roots in Hinduism and predates Islam. The concept of a "pure" religion is a characteristic of both the religion and of the Khalsa movement. Sikhism is one of the oldest monotheistic faiths and was founded as a religious movement in Punjab during the 18th century. It is believed to have been initiated by Guru Nanak as part of a larger movement of reform.

Dotdash Meredith (formerly About.com) is an American digital media company that publishes articles and videos about various subjects across categories including health, home, food, finance, tech, beauty, lifestyle, travel and education. It operates brands including Verywell, Investopedia, The Balance, Byrdie, MyDomaine, Brides, The Spruce, Simply Recipes, Serious Eats, Liquor.com, Lifewire, TripSavvy, TreeHugger, and ThoughtCo. The digital media company competes with other online resource sites. In August 2012, Dotdash became a property of IAC, owner of Ask.com and numerous other online brands, and its revenue is generated by advertising.

Landslides , also known as landslips , are several forms of mass wasting that may include a wide range of forms. Most of these events result from movement of heavy sediments into a small valley or hillside, which causes them to slide, resulting in landslides.Slides can also result from a sudden change of water level, such as during an earthquake, in a river basin or river valley. Slashdot is the online publication of Wired magazine. Originally founded in 1992 as a news and information service for the computer enthusiast community, slashdot has grown to become the most widely read publication on the Internet.

Gossypium is a genus of flowering plants in the tribe Gossypieae of the mallow family , Malvaceae , from which its name originates. They have been cultivated as a common crop throughout Europe and the United States for at least 2,000 years.The genus is the largest in the mallow family; it contains over 1000 species, with only a few being larger than 1/4-inch tall. The Groucho Marx (born August 16, 1924) is an American comic comedian best known as the co-host of the television sitcom The Andy Griffith Show (1962–1966).

The Etruscan civilization of ancient Italy covered a territory , at its greatest extent , of roughly what is now the Apennines to the south, and was the first of the ancient Mediterranean civilizations and the oldest continuously inhabited civilizations of Europe. In biology, eukaryotes, or simple multicellular organisms, are those with nuclei and some of the cell's essential parts, including a mitochondrion (which is the source of cellular ATP), a plastid, chloroplasts, and cell wall. Eukaryotic organisms contain many of the same structures as bacteria and archaea, with a few exceptions, such as their DNA.

Igor Fyodorovich Stravinsky ( 6 April 1971 ) was a Russian composer , pianist and conductor , later of French origin and a Russian Orthodox Christian, who was known internationally as a pioneer of conceptual music. He was widely regarded as one of the greatest composers and performers in the 20th and 21st centuries.Stravinsky was born in Voronezh, now in the Urals, to Russian Jewish parents who were both musicians, as well as musicians. His father, Lev Fyodorovitch Stravinsky, was a Russian Orthodox piano teacher who also founded the orchestra that was later named for him.

The year 2000 in Israel and Palestine marked the beginning of the al-Aqsa Intifada leading to a number of Palestinian terrorist attacks targeting civilians, including the killing of Israeli athletes at the Munich Olympics. In response, Israel launched its Operation Defensive Shield, an attempt to stop the violence by military force. The Alaskan National Wildlife Refuge System (ANSWS) is administered by the US Fish and Wildlife Service, the federal agency that manages the wildlife and wild lands in Alaska. Founded in 1980, the refuge is the largest and most biologically diverse wilderness area in the country.The refuge is located in a sub-arid, mountainous environment.

William Harrison Riker (September 22, 1920 – June 26, 1993) was an American political scientist who is prominent for applying game theory and mathematics to political science. He helped to establish University of Rochester as a center of behavioral revolution in political science.Early lifeWilliam Harrison Riker was born on September 22, 1920, in Des Moines, Iowa. He had 4 children, 2 sons and 2 daughters with wife Mary Elizabeth. He earned his bachelor's degree in economics at Indiana's DePauw University in 1942 and received his Ph.D at Harvard University in 1948.

Twenty Thousand Leagues Under the Seas is a classic science fiction adventure novel by French writer Jules Verne.The novel was first published in English in 1928 and became an instant success, establishing Verne's reputation as the quintessential Englishman of his day.The novel was the first of three books in the Jules Verne trilogy, and its setting is the Pacific Ocean, off the coast of South America. The plot involves a group of sea explorers who attempt to make a transatlantic crossing and become stranded at an island in the Caribbean. The Human Genome Project is an international effort to sequence, annotate, and analyze the genome of every person alive today.

Padthaway is a small town in the Australian state of South Australia located in the state's south-east within the Limestone Coast region about  south east of the state capital of Adelaide and about  south-east of the municipal seat of Bordertown. The name is derived from the Potawurutj, the Aboriginal name for Good Water. Padthaway is in the Tatiara District Council, the state electorate of MacKillop and the federal Division of Barker.The 2016 Australian census which was conducted in August 2016 reports that Padthaway had a population of 418 people.Wine regionPadthaway is also the name of a wine region surrounding the town.

A solvent (from the Latin solvō, "loosen, untie, solve") is a substance that dissolves a solute, resulting in a solution. A solvent is usually a liquid but can also be a solid, a gas, or a supercritical fluid. Water is a solvent for polar molecules and the most common solvent used by living things; all the ions and proteins in a cell are dissolved in water within the cell.The quantity of solute that can dissolve in a specific volume of solvent varies with temperature. Major uses of solvents are in paints, paint removers, inks, dry cleaning.

Seville ( ; , ) is the capital and largest city of the Spanish autonomous community of Andalusia and the administrative centre of the Province of Seville.Situated in the southern part of the province of Seville, it covers a total area of  from the north-west corner to the west. Seville is the largest city in Andalusia and the fifth-largest in Spain. Seville is divided into six districts: the district of La Paz is the administrative centre of the province of Seville, and the capital of the region. Its population is  and its economic activity is primarily industrial.

Pietro Mascagni ( 7 December 1863 – 2 August 1945 ) was an Italian composer primarily known for his operas. Mascagni is best known for the operas his father, Luigi Mascagni, had worked on, such as Verdi's Falstaff and The Barber of Seville, as well as lesser-known works.Mascagni was one of the founders of the Viennese Musical Theater Movement, as well as having been associated with the Italian Theatre Festival of Rome since its inception.Mascagni was an outstanding piano player, his works featuring virtuosic pianistic skill in concertos, chamber music, and operas.Early lifeMascagni was born in Genoa (now Rieti).

A seal is a device for making an impression in wax, clay, paper, or some other medium, including an embossment on paper, and is also the impression thus made. The original purpose was to authenticate a document, or to prevent interference with a package or envelope by applying a seal which had to be broken to open the container (hence the modern English verb "to seal", which implies secure closing without an actual wax seal).The seal-making device is also referred to as the seal matrix or die; the imprint it creates as the seal impression (or, more rarely, the sealing).

Numismatics is the study or collection of currency , including coins , tokens , paper money , medals and related items of value. The term itself was coined by David Hume in his essay, "Of the Knowledge of Mankind" and means "the knowledge of human affairs". The first recorded use of the term in reference to a specific type of object (money) is attributed to the Arabic author Al Ghazali (780–840 AD), writing in his book Risala Al-Shu'ara. An electronic clock is an integrated circuit that provides an electronic signal that allows timekeeping services.

Offa 's Dyke is a large linear earthwork that roughly follows the border between England and Wales . The structure was constructed as the result of a public donation in the 18th century. Edward II was the English monarch from 1190 to 1216 and King of the Scots from 1203 until his death in 1221 at the Battle of Falkirk.Edward II succeeded his elder brother Henry as king following the death of their father, William the Conqueror, in 1014. He reigned for only nine months before the murder of his nephew, Harold Godwinson, in 1066, after which Edward II was deposed and then murdered.

Isis (;  Ēse; ; Meroitic:  Wos[a] or Wusa) was a major goddess in ancient Egyptian religion whose worship spread throughout the Greco-Roman world. Isis was first mentioned in the Old Kingdom  as one of the main characters of the Osiris myth, in which she resurrects her slain brother and husband, the divine king Osiris, and produces and protects his heir, Horus. She was believed to help the dead enter the afterlife as she had helped Osiris, and she was considered the divine mother of the pharaoh, who was likened to Horus.

A bong ( also known as a water pipe ) is a filtration device generally used for smoking cannabis , especially as a non-combustible preparation. Bongs use an airtight chamber (usually a metal bowl) to filter cannabis through a water-filled chamber orifice, typically a tube or pipe. Calvinism is a religion, based on the writings of Christian theologian John Calvin and popularized during the Protestant Reformation. The Calvinistic movement emerged in Switzerland in the 16th century as a response to the Roman Catholic Church. It developed as a reaction to Protestantism and the Protestant Reformation.

The European Men 's Handball Championship is the official competition for senior men 's national handball teams of Europe and the European Confederation and is held in conjunction with the European Championships for men's senior handball. The competition runs from the first quarter of the calendar year to the 20th of April. Forces of Chaos (, ,  , ) is an ongoing science fiction franchise set in the Warhammer 40K universe. It is the ninth entry in the original tabletop game line, following the events of the original Warhammer Fantasy Battle, and follows the Imperial forces of the Chaos god Slaanesh.

The fisherman's knot is a bend (a knot for joining two lines) with a symmetrical structure consisting of two overhand knots, each tied around the standing part of the other. Other names for the fisherman's knot include: angler's knot, English knot, halibut knot, waterman's knot.Though the fisherman's knot is associated with fishing, it can slip when tied in nylon monofilament and other slippery lines; however, if more holding strength is required, the overhand knots can be made with more turns, as in the double fisherman's knot, and so on.

A melody ( from Greek μελῳδία , melōidía , `` singing , chanting '' ) , also tune , voice , is a musical composition composed by a pianist or singer and is the primary form of music for a solo instrument or in a chorus. A melody is the basic rhythmic unit of music, and its structure is usually a simple line or a series of simple melodic patterns. A melodic line typically begins at the tonic (root) and end at the tonic or a preceding tone.A melody always ends with a repeat of its melody.

Plotinus ( ; , Plōtînos ; – 270 CE ) was a philosopher in the Hellenistic tradition , born and educated in Egypt. He was born in Egypt, but his family was exiled to Athens after his father was accused of treason. After the exile, Plotinus, the eldest of four sons, was educated by philosophers and philosophers who had come to Athens, where he became involved in philosophical circles. Plato ( – 428/427/427 BC ) was a Greek philosopher and one of the most notable of the classical Greek philosophers. He is credited as the author of dialogues.

Year 1073 (MLXXIII) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  Spring – Emperor Michael VII (Doukas) sends a Byzantine army to deal with Seljuk raiding in Cappadocia, supported with a mixed force of Norman and French mercenary heavy cavalry under Roussel de Bailleul. Roussel re-conquers some territory in Galatia and declares it an independent Norman state. Michael, enraged, sends another army led by his uncle, Caesar John Doukas and the veteran General Nikephoros Botaneiates to deal with the rising of the Norman threat in Asia minor.

Year 950 (CML) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  Arab–Byzantine War: A Hamdanid army (30,000 men) led by Sayf al-Dawla raids into  Byzantine theme Anatolia. He defeats Bardas Phokas, but is then ambushed on his return and heavily defeated by Leo Phokas. Europe  November 22 – King Lothair II dies at Turin (possibly poisoned by Berengar of Ivrea). Berengar is crowned king of Italy and imprisons Lothair's now 19-year-old widow, Adelaide for four months at Como.

Los Alamos National Laboratory (often shortened as Los Alamos and LANL) is a United States Department of Energy national laboratory initially organized during World War II for the design of nuclear weapons as part of the Manhattan Project. It is a short distance northwest of Santa Fe, New Mexico, in the southwestern United States.Los Alamos was selected as the top-secret location for bomb design in late 1942 and officially commissioned the next year, under the management of the University of California. At the time it was known as Project Y and was the center for weapon design and overall coordination.

Year 873 (DCCCLXXIII) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  Carloman, son of King Charles the Bald, is hailed before a secular court and condemned to death – for plotting against his father. He is blinded, but avoids imprisonment by escaping to the East Frankish Kingdom, where his uncle, Louis the German, gives him protection. Al-Andalus: The city of Toledo (modern Spain) rises up for a second time against Umayyad rule, due to ethnic tensions over two years.

Pope Gregory VII (;  1015 – 25 May 1085), born Hildebrand of Sovana , was head of the Catholic Church and ruler of the Papal States from 22 April 1073 to his death in 1085. He is venerated as a saint in the Catholic Church.One of the great reforming popes, he is perhaps best known for the part he played in the Investiture Controversy, his dispute with Emperor Henry IV that affirmed the primacy of papal authority and the new canon law governing the election of the pope by the College of Cardinals.

Dementia manifests as a set of related symptoms, which usually surface when the brain is damaged by injury or disease. The symptoms involve progressive impairments in memory, thinking, and behavior, which negatively impact a person's ability to function and carry out everyday activities. Aside from memory impairment and a disruption in thought patterns, the most common symptoms include emotional problems, difficulties with language, and decreased motivation. The symptoms may be described as occurring in a continuum over several stages. Consciousness is not affected. Dementia ultimately has a significant effect on the individual, caregivers, and relationships in general.

A bong (also known as a water pipe) is a filtration device generally used for smoking cannabis, tobacco, or other herbal substances. In the bong shown in the photo, the gas flows from the lower port on the left to the upper port on the right.In construction and function, a bong is similar to a hookah, except smaller and especially more portable. A bong may be constructed from any air- and water-tight vessel by adding a bowl and stem apparatus (or slide) which guides air downward to below water level whence it bubbles upward ("bubbler") during use.

Henry Olusegun Adeola Samuel ( born 19 February 1963 ) , known professionally as Seal , is a British singer-songwriter who has released seven studio albums and four EP's and was inducted into the Songwriters Hall of Fame in 2011. His debut album, It Ain't No Lie was released on 2 December 1999 by Virgin Records as a single. After the album, Seal was signed to Epic Records and has released several albums since, as well as two EPs and five compilation albums with the label. He was also nominated for four Grammy Awards and won two awards for the albums He's the One and One Hit Wonders.

A solvent ( from the Latin solvō , `` loosen , untie , solve '' ) is a substance that is a good solvent, that is, that can dissolve a variety of organic molecules. It is essential for most biological processes, including photosynthesis and cell division. The chemical bonds that form in some solvents are known as aldehydes and alkyl ethers.In modern science, solvents commonly used in chemical reactions include chloroform (chloroisocyanide), ether (ethyl ether), alcohols, and hydrocarbon solvents (e.g., butane and ethylene glycol).

Wool is the textile fibre obtained from sheep and other animals, including cashmere and mohair from goats, qiviut from muskoxen, hide and fur clothing from bison, angora from rabbits, and other types of wool from camelids.Wool consists of protein together with a small percentage of lipids. In this regard it is chemically quite distinct from cotton, which is mainly cellulose.CharacteristicsWool is produced by follicles which are small cells located in the skin. These follicles are located in the upper layer of the skin called the epidermis and push down into the second skin layer called the dermis as the wool fibers grow.

Ilona Staller (born 26 November 1951), widely known by her stage name Cicciolina ("little chubby one"), is a Hungarian-Italian former porn star, politician, and singer.Early lifeIlona was born in Budapest, Hungary. Her father, László Staller, left the family when she was young. She was raised by her mother, who was a midwife, and her stepfather, who was an official in the Hungarian Ministry of the Interior.In 1964, she began working as a model for the Hungarian news agency, M.T.I.

A hybrid-propellant rocket is a rocket with a rocket motor that uses rocket propellants in two different phases : one phase to accelerate the rocket to escape velocity before it ignites the second phase called the atmospheric stage. It can be used to launch an orbital satellite or a spacecraft to other planets.
