The hybrid propellant engine uses a mixture of liquid and solid rocket propellants, and is known as solid rocket fuel.Hybrid rockets differ from liquid-fueled rockets by having a solid rocket booster for the first stage and a liquid propellant, or kerosene, for the second stage.

Bikram Yoga is a system of hot yoga , a type of yoga as exercise , devised by Bikram Choudhury in the 1950's. It is based on a sequence of twenty postures called the twenty postures. The term "postures" refers specifically to the movements performed during the twenty postures; however, in the modern context it is understood to refer to any sequence of movements.The twenty postures of the twenty-one sequence are the core of the yoga style. These postures have been used to strengthen the body through the use of intense mental and physical effort.

Pope Leo VI ( 880 – 12 February 929 ) was the bishop of Rome and nominal ruler of the Holy Roman Empire. Leo was born in Arles, in the southern part of the kingdom of Naples, and was consecrated a bishop of Arles on 22 November 820. Leo IV (;  - ) was the fourth pope to serve as pope of Rome. Like his predecessors, he was the successor of Pope Clement II. Leo was born at Ravenna in northern Italy on 11 June 778, the eldest of seven children.

The Who are an English rock band formed in London in 1964 . Their classic lineup consisted of lead singer John Entwistle, guitarist Pete Townshend, bassist Keith Moon, drummer Pete Townshend, and keyboard player Geoff Downie. The Washington Redskins are an American professional American football team based in Washington, D.C., and the oldest professional American football team in the world. The team has won eight Super Bowls, the most of any American football team. The team has played its home games at RFK Stadium since 1961, and has been called the Redskins since its founding in 1937.

Saxony-Anhalt ( ; ) is a state of Germany , bordering the states of Brandenburg , Saxony , Thuringia and Thuringia . The state was created by the unification of Germany between 1870 and 1870, after Prussia was annexed. It borders the Czech Republic on the west, the Russian exclave of Kaliningrad to the south and east, the Polish-Lithuanian Commonwealth to the north of the river Main and the North Rhine–Rhine-Main river valley to the east and north.The state's administrative centre is the capital and largest town of Berlin, Germany and the state capital since the end of World War II.

Pope Leo VIII ( 915 – 1 March 965 ) was a Roman prelate who claimed the Holy See from Pope Gregory XII in 896. He was named Pope from the papal bull, Ex hortatus, "On the election of the Holy Father". John Henry Cardinal Newman (30 October 1808 – 28 March 1867) was an English priest who was the most prominent English exponent of classical liberalism in his time. His The Common Sense of the Christian Religion was the first systematic exposition of moral and religious philosophy. Born into an upper-class family, Newman entered the theological seminary of St Mary's, Cambridge, in 1814.

The raven paradox, also known as Hempel's paradox, Hempel's ravens, or rarely the paradox of indoor ornithology, is a paradox arising from the question of what constitutes evidence for a statement. Observing objects that are neither black nor ravens may formally increase the likelihood that all ravens are black even though, intuitively, these observations are unrelated.This problem was proposed by the logician Carl Gustav Hempel in the 1940s to illustrate a contradiction between inductive logic and intuition.Paradox Hempel describes the paradox in terms of the hypothesis: (1) All ravens are black.

George Michael Dolenz Jr. ( born March 8 , 1945 ) is an American actor , musician , TV producer, author, and activist. He is well known for his roles as Michael Scofield on My Three Sons (1975–1977), David Foster Wallace in Infinite Jest (1996–2011), and David Foster Wallace in the film adaptation of the book Infinite Jest (1998). He was born in New York to a Czech Jewish mother and Italian-American Jewish father. He is the only person to hold all four roles of My Three Sons.

Don Carlos is a five-act grand opera composed by Giuseppe Verdi to a French-language libretto by Joseph Méry and Camille Claudel, with music by Luigi Bressan.The opera was based on Méry's short play, "Le Capitaine D'Antin" (The Duke in the City) in which Verdi's hero is exiled to the duchy of Alencon by the ambitious Duke D'Antin, who takes the title of Duke. The play was later translated into German and published in several operatic editions, notably by the composer and librettist Wilhelm Furtwängler, and in English translation by Gwynne Dyer; it also inspired many other opera composers.

Australian Signals Directorate (ASD; until 2013: Defence Signals Directorate, DSD) is the Australian government agency responsible for foreign signals intelligence, support to military operations, cyber warfare, and information security. ASD is part of the Australian Intelligence Community. ASD's role within UKUSA Agreement (Five Eyes) is to monitor SIGINT in South and East Asia. The ASD also houses the Australian Cyber Security Centre.The unit was established in 1947 by executive order as the Defence Signals Bureau within the Department of Defence, and underwent several name changes until its current name ASD was adopted in 2013.

Pope John XXII (; 1244 – 4 December 1334), born Jacques Duèze (or d'Euse), was head of the Catholic Church from 7 August 1316 to his death in 1334.He was the second and longest-reigning Avignon Pope, elected by the Conclave of Cardinals, which was assembled in Lyon through the work of King Louis X's brother Philip, the Count of Poitiers, later King Philip V of France. Like his predecessor, Clement V, Pope John centralized power and income in the Papacy and lived a princely life in Avignon.

The Reedy Creek Improvement District ( RCID ) is the immediate governing jurisdiction for the land of the Walt Disney World and Disneyland Resorts, and the surrounding area. The district extends from the southern end of the Lake Buena Vista bridge to the southern end of the Interstate 5 Bridge, which is about 2 miles southwest of Interstate 4 in the Orange County San Joaquin County Community College District Park. In chemistry, a heterocyclic group (HC) is any compound with a heteroatom that is not symmetric about an acid, alkaline or base.

George Shipway (25 May 1908–1982) was a British author best known for his historical novels, but he also tried his hand at political satire in his book The Chilian Club.Military careerGeorge Frederick Morgan Shipway was born on 25 May 1908 at Allahbad in India and was educated at Clifton. He then attended the Royal Military College, Sandhurst and was commissioned on to the Unattached List for the Indian Army on 30 August 1928. He arrived in India on 5 October 1928 and was attached to a British regiment: the 2nd Battalion The Prince of Wales's Volunteers (South Lancashire), for one year from 14 October 1928.

A melody (from Greek μελῳδία, melōidía, "singing, chanting"), also tune, voice or line, is a linear succession of musical tones that the listener perceives as a single entity. In its most literal sense, a melody is a combination of pitch and rhythm, while more figuratively, the term can include other musical elements such as tonal color. It is the foreground to the background accompaniment. A line or part need not be a foreground melody.Melodies often consist of one or more musical phrases or motifs, and are usually repeated throughout a composition in various forms.

Paul Leo Molitor (born August 22, 1956), nicknamed "Molly" and "The Ignitor", is an American former Major League Baseball (MLB) player and former manager of the Minnesota Twins, who is in the Baseball Hall of Fame. During his 21-year baseball career, he played for the Milwaukee Brewers (1978–1992), Toronto Blue Jays (1993–1995), and Minnesota Twins (1996–1998). He was known for his exceptional hitting and speed. He made seven All-Star Game appearances, and was the World Series MVP in 1993.Molitor grew up in Minnesota and attended the University of Minnesota before beginning his MLB career.

The San Diego Zoo Safari Park , originally named the San Diego Wild Animal Park until 2010 , is an accredited zoological park in Central California, north of San Diego.It was the only accredited zoo in Southern California until the closure of the San Diego Zoo in 2001. The park now focuses on education and animal conservation, and the facility hosts over 400 species of animals. It is home to over 600 animals, including lions, bears, cheetahs and giraffes.The Safari Park was the third zoo in Southern California when it opened on October 2, 1926.

Martin Heidegger ( ; ; 26 September 188926 May 1976 ) was a German philosopher who is best known for his studies of existence, existentialism, and phenomenology. He was also an influential social philosopher and cultural critic, having published numerous works on philosophy, literature, politics, philosophy of religion, art, and culture. He was the founder of the philosophical school of existentialism that is commonly known as "existentialism". He is considered to have been the forerunner of contemporary existentialism. He was also the founder of phenomenology.

A drummer is a percussionist who creates music using drums.Most contemporary western bands that play rock , pop , jazz , and other forms of modern music have employed percussionist as a secondary instrumentalist on occasion. Drummers generally play drums for solos, but some drummers are more proficient in a variety of percussion instruments and perform on their own. Dogs are domestic canids of the family Canidae that include domesticated wolves and wolves-like canids; dogs can also be characterized by their ability to communicate with each other. Most domestic dogs are either wild canids or hybridized with domestic dogs.

In the administrative divisions of France, the department  is one of the three levels of government under the national level ("territorial collectivities"), between the administrative regions and the communes. Ninety-six departments are in metropolitan France, and five are overseas departments, which are also classified as overseas regions. Departments are further subdivided into 332 arrondissements, and these are divided into cantons. The last two levels of government have no autonomy; they are the basis of local organisation of police, fire departments and, sometimes, administration of elections.Each department is administered by an elected body called a departmental council ( [sing.

The BBC World Service is an international broadcaster owned and operated by the BBC, with funding from the British Government through the Foreign Secretary's office. It is the world's largest external broadcaster in terms of reception area, language selection and audience reach. It broadcasts radio news, speech and discussions in more than 40 languages to many parts of the world on analogue and digital shortwave platforms, internet streaming, podcasting, satellite, DAB, FM and MW relays. In 2015, the World Service reached an average of 210 million people a week (via TV, radio and online).

Lingerie ( , , ) is a category of primarily women 's clothing including undergarments ( mainly brassieres ) , corsets , and underpants. The term also encompasses lingerie designed especially for men; this is called male lingerie. A larger category, known as corseted clothing , includes clothing intended to constrict the wearer's torso. It is sometimes used synonymously with undergarments as a general category for all apparel intended to constrict the wearer.HistoryThe term was developed by the lingerie designer Charlotte Brontë as her own name for the corsets, corsets and underpants designed especially for women.

This list of Anuran families shows all extant families of Anura. Anura is an order of animals in the class Amphibia that includes frogs and toads. More than 5,000 species are described in the order. The living anurans are typically divided into three suborders: Archaeobatrachia, Mesobatrachia, and Neobatrachia. This classification is based on such morphological features as the number of vertebrae, the structure of the pectoral girdle, and the morphology of tadpoles.TaxonomyThe archaeobatrachians are the most primitive of frogs. These frogs have morphological characteristics which are found mostly in extinct frogs, and are absent in most of the modern frog species.

Hazardous waste is waste that has substantial or potential threats to public health or the environment.Characteristic hazardous wastes are materials that are known or tested to exhibit one or more of the following hazardous traits:IgnitabilityReactivityCorrosivityToxicityListed hazardous wastes are materials specifically listed by regulatory authorities as hazardous wastes which are from non-specific sources, specific sources, or discarded chemical products.Hazardous wastes may be found in different physical states such as gaseous, liquids, or solids. A hazardous waste is a special type of waste because it cannot be disposed of by common means like other by-products of our everyday lives.

New Sweden (; ; ) was a Swedish colony along the lower reaches of the Delaware River in America from 1638 to 1655, established during the Thirty Years' War when Sweden was a great military power. New Sweden formed part of the Swedish efforts to colonize the Americas. Settlements were established on both sides of the Delaware Valley in the region of Delaware, New Jersey, Maryland, and Pennsylvania, often in places where Swedish traders had been visiting since about 1610. Fort Christina in Wilmington, Delaware, was the first settlement, named after the reigning Swedish monarch.

Year 876 ( DCCCLXXVI ) was a leap year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) in the Gregorian calendar, which had been introduced around the year 1682 (link will display the calendar of that year). It is the only leap year year which was not also a century year. It is also the only year that has seven months in a row, as opposed to four or six in the Julian calendar. It is also the only year that falls on the first Sunday of the month, which is a leap day.

The Standby High-Readiness Brigade ( SHIRBRIG ) was a Danish-led initiative associated with the United Nations that aimed to create a multinational force to provide humanitarian assistance during the 1973–74 oil crisis. It was created by the United Nations Security Council in late March 1973, and became operational two weeks later, at a cost of 1 billion Danish crowns (roughly US$50 million). The force, comprised of troops from Denmark, France, the Netherlands, South Africa, and the United Kingdom, was initially deployed to Yemen and Oman, providing humanitarian assistance and relief to civilians affected by the oil crisis, and supporting UN-mandated peacekeeping operations.

Giovanni Paisiello ( or Paesiello ; 9 May 1740 – 5 June 1816 ) was an Italian composer of the Baroque period, chiefly associated with the opera. He is best known for his works in French, such as Le danseur de Dieu, which was adapted into a musical opera by Richard Wagner in 1846. The operas were performed on numerous occasions in many countries. Paisiello began to compose music during his study of music, with an emphasis on the piano and organ. He began by writing his own music, then added pieces by his students to his own repertoire, and in 1780 his first full operas were produced.

Avignon (, ; ;   or  , ; ) is the prefecture of the Vaucluse department in the Provence-Alpes-Côte d'Azur region of Southeastern France. Located on the left bank of the river Rhône, the commune had a population of 93,671 as of the census results of 2017, with about 16,000 (estimate from Avignon's municipal services) living in the ancient town centre enclosed by its  medieval walls.Between 1309 and 1377, during the Avignon Papacy, seven successive popes resided in Avignon and in 1348 Pope Clement VI bought the town from Joanna I of Naples.

Larry Simon Gelbart (February 25, 1928 – September 11, 2009) was an American television writer, playwright, screenwriter, director and author, most famous as a creator and producer of the television series M*A*S*H, and as co-writer of the Broadway musicals A Funny Thing Happened on the Way to the Forum and City of Angels.BiographyEarly lifeGelbart was born in Chicago, Illinois, to Jewish immigrants Harry Gelbart, "a barber since his half of a childhood in Latvia," and Frieda Sturner, who migrated to America from Dąbrowa Górnicza, Poland.

The Novikov self-consistency principle , also known as the Novikov self-consistency conjecture and Larry Niven 's law of conservation of energy , states that any finite-dimensional system can be written as a continuous function of its power series expansion , where and is the set of all real numbers less than . The energy of any system is defined by the expansion of the power series , where is also the set of all real numbers less than or equal to . The entropy of any discrete system is the density, in energy units, of a random sequence of zero-dimensional vectors , such as a random walk, of length .

See also History of UnitarianismA number of notable people have considered themselves Unitarians, Universalists, and following the merger of these denominations in the United States and Canada in 1961, Unitarian Universalists. Additionally, there are persons who, because of their writings or reputation, are considered to have held Unitarian or Universalist beliefs. Individuals who held unitarian (nontrinitarian) beliefs but were not affiliated with Unitarian organizations are often referred to as "small 'u unitarians. The same principle can be applied to those who believed in universal salvation but were not members of Universalist organizations.

Year 968 ( CMLXVIII ) was a leap year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) in the Julian calendar in the Christian Gregorian calendar adopted in 1752. This year began with a leap year in the Gregorian calendar because the Gregorian calendar had been introduced in 1752.On this year, the Julian date for the year was 4 January AD 498, which would have made it 29 January AD 753, or 2 days off. Cleveland Browns football is an American professional American football team that played in the National Football League (NFL) from 1946 to 2018.

Pali  is a Middle Indo-Aryan liturgical language native to the Indian subcontinent. It is widely studied because it is the language of the Pāli Canon or Tipiṭaka as well as the sacred language of Theravāda Buddhism. In early time, it was written in Brahmi script.Origin and developmentEtymologyThe word 'Pali' is used as a name for the language of the Theravada canon. The word seems to have its origins in commentarial traditions, wherein the Pāli (in the sense of the line of original text quoted) was distinguished from the commentary or vernacular translation that followed it in the manuscript.

John Knox , born ( – 24 November 1572 ) was a Scottish minister , Reformed theologian , and writer. He was appointed by King James I of England to be Archbishop of Armagh and then Bishop of Drogheda. His book, The Institutes of the Christian Religion , is considered a classic work in the history of Christian theology. He is considered to be the Father of the English Reformation.Born into a humble Scottish farming family in Kilwinning, he entered the Scottish Church at the age of 16 and spent his life in a small parish in the Borders.

Nitrous oxide , commonly known as laughing gas , nitrous , or nos , is a chemical compound , an oxidizer , and a gas. It is used to produce a hallucinogenic effect, a mild sedative effect, an inhalation of nitrogen, and in a few scientific settings for medical purposes. As an oxidizer, nitrous oxide can replace carbon monoxide in a fuel gas. Nassim Taleb , better known by his nom de plume, Nassim Haramein , is an Israeli mathematician and risk theorist, known primarily for his books The Black Swan and Antifragile.

The National Academies of Sciences , Engineering , and Medicine ( also known as NASEM or the National Academies ) is a U.S. scientific society that advises and identifies policy issues for the federal government. It was founded in 1918, initially to advise on matters related to the United States Army. In the early years, it was focused primarily on issues of U.S. military strategy, doctrine, logistics, and operations. In mathematics, algebraic geometry (also denoted as algebraic geometry) is the branch of higher algebra that is most concerned with geometric and topological aspects of algebraic problems.

The 8 inch (203 mm) M110 self-propelled howitzer is an American-made self-propelled artillery system consisting of an M115 203 mm howitzer installed on a purpose-built chassis. Before its retirement from US service, it was the largest available self-propelled howitzer in the United States Army's inventory; it continues in service with the armed forces of other countries, to which it was exported. Missions include general support, counter-battery fire, and suppression of enemy air defense systems.DescriptionAccording to the operator's manual, the M110's typical rate of fire was three rounds per two minutes when operated at maximum speed, and one round per two minutes with sustained fire.

In the 1980s , the telecommunications industry expected that digital services would follow much the same pattern as voice services. It was predicted that customers would be able to download content onto their computer, then listen to it on a telephone or portable radio. As a result, many were surprised to hear that telephone and radio transmitters had been abandoned in favour of satellite, video and audio transmissions. An American football team plays an American football game on a large field of artificial turf. It usually has four or more teams playing on each side.

Asperger syndrome (AS), also known as Asperger's, is a neurodevelopmental disorder characterized by significant difficulties in social interaction and nonverbal communication, along with restricted and repetitive patterns of behavior and interests. It is an autism spectrum disorder (ASD), but differs from other ASDs by relatively unimpaired language and intelligence. The syndrome is named after the Austrian pediatrician Hans Asperger, who, in 1944, described children in his care who struggled to form friendships, did not understand others' gestures or feelings, engaged in one-sided conversations about their favourite interests, and were clumsy.

A sports governing body is a sports organization that has a regulatory or sanctioning function.Sports governing bodies come in various shapes and sizes, and range from national governing bodies that are in charge of sports at national or international levels, to clubs or associations that run individual sports for members, to clubs or associations that organize competitions between clubs. They often set rules, and enforce them through sanctions or penalties, such as banning a club from competing. The most well-known of the modern governing bodies is the International Olympic Committee, but others include FIFA, the International Rugby Board, and the Professional Golfers' Association.

Year 968 (CMLXVIII) was a leap year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  Emperor Nikephoros II receives a Bulgarian embassy led by Prince Boris (the son of Tsar Peter I of Bulgaria), with a plea for help against the invading Kievan Rus'. Nikephoros, occupied in the East, is unable to support him. Instead he sends envoys to summon the Pechenegs to aid Boris. They besiege Kiev, but Grand Prince Sviatoslav I (on campaign in Bulgaria) returns with a Kievan relief force, and defeats the Pechenegs.

The history of Southeast Asia covers the people of Southeast Asia from prehistory to the present in two distinct sub-regions: Mainland Southeast Asia (or Indochina) and Maritime Southeast Asia (or Insular Southeast Asia). Mainland Southeast Asia comprises Cambodia, Laos, Myanmar (or Burma), Peninsular Malaysia, Thailand and Vietnam whereas Maritime Southeast Asia comprises Brunei, Cocos (Keeling) Islands, Christmas Island, East Malaysia, East Timor, Indonesia, Philippines and Singapore.The earliest Homo sapiens presence in Mainland Southeast Asia can be traced back to 70,000 years ago and to at least 50,000 years ago in Maritime Southeast Asia.

Offa's Dyke  is a large linear earthwork that roughly follows the border between England and Wales. The structure is named after Offa, the Anglo-Saxon king of Mercia from AD 757 until 796, who is traditionally believed to have ordered its construction. Although its precise original purpose is debated, it delineated the border between Anglian Mercia and the Welsh kingdom of Powys.The earthwork, which was up to  wide (including its flanking ditch) and  high, traversed low ground, hills and rivers. Today it is protected as a scheduled monument.

A luge  is a small one- or two-person sled on which one sleds supine (face up) and feet-first. A luger steers by using the calf muscles to flex the sled's runners or by exerting opposite shoulder pressure to the seat. Racing sleds weigh  for singles and  for doubles. Luge is also the name of an Olympic sport.Lugers can reach speeds of 140 km/h (87 mph). Austrian Manuel Pfister reached a top speed of 154 km/h (96 mph) on a track in Whistler, Canada, prior to the 2010 Winter Olympics.

The Battle of the Chesapeake , also known as the Battle of the Virginia Capes or simply the Battle of Norfolk , took place in September 1619, near the present-day City of Norfolk, Virginia. As the British Army moved into the city, the city's militia formed up to defend the city. After being repulsed at a place called Hampton Roads (now the site of the Chesapeake Bay Naval Shipyard), the rebels retreated and the British captured Hampton and its garrison. Blackbeard (12 August 1718) was a British pirate, privateer, and privateer captain who was involved in numerous attacks on British trade vessels.

Delhi ( ; Dillī ; Dillī ; Dêhlī ) , officially the National Capital Territory ( NCT ) of Delhi, is the capital of India, a metropolitan area of more than 2.5 million, and the second-largest city in India, after Mumbai, with a population of about 21 million as of 2013.DELHI is the third-fastest-growing urban agglomeration of the country in terms of population growth after Mumbai and Pune, and it has emerged as an economic hub for the entire country, ranking fifth in terms of total manufacturing exports in 2011-13, with a value of ₹11,859 crores.

Anthony John Hancock ( 12 May 1924 – 25 June 1968 ) was an English comedian and actor.High-profile during the 1960s and 1970s, Hancock began his career on television. During the late 1970s and early 1980s, Hancock was a member of the satirical comedy group Monty Python and later the sketch group Monty Python's Flying Circus.Hancock also co-starred alongside Terry Jones in the 1970 British comedy Monty Python's Life of Brian (1979) and later with Paul Merton in The Meaning of Life (1985).A popular figure among young people, Hancock also appeared on BBC2 comedy series Mock the Week in the 1980s.

Note : This compilation includes only those attacks that resulted in casualties . Attacks which did not kill or wound any combatant and did not cause any direct damage were not included in casualties figures. In the game Civilization II, civilization-wide production and research are the processes of obtaining and using natural resources such as wood, iron, ore, minerals and water. A civilization may have a single industrial civilization or an empire, which may have several other industrial civilizations working in conjunction with the one it controls. Industrial civilizations are the primary industrializing civilizations and are the primary source of the technologies that civilization-wide civilization progress is based upon.

Mary Anning ( 21 May 1799 – 9 March 1847 ) was an English fossil collector , dealer , and amateur botanist, the founder of her own museum, and a prominent figure in the evolution of modern biology.Biography Anning was born in Woolton, Surrey, England, and raised in Eastcheap. After graduating from the London Polytechnic, she attended the Royal Institution of Arts and graduated with distinction in 1809, becoming one of the first women to be elected a Royal Aspirant. Anning was a friend and associate of the chemist William Crookes, and also of William Whewell.

The history of Southeast Asia covers the people of Southeast Asia from prehistory to the present in two distinct sub-regions: the Indian subcontinent and the Malaysian Peninsula.HistoryPrehistoryThe area known today as Indonesia and Southeast Asia had its origins in the continent's earliest stage, as an island that became connected to Southeast Asia over time and formed the Indonesian Archipelago during its formation. Ishmael  is an Egyptian desert god associated with life, health, fertility and rain. The name is the Hebrew translation of the first-person singular present tense adjective  ,  , from הָשׁמָלה (Isha'el, or Ishmael).

Cell division is the process by which a parent cell divides into two or more daughter cells. Cell division usually occurs as part of a larger cell cycle. In eukaryotes, there are two distinct types of cell division; a vegetative division, whereby each daughter cell is genetically identical to the parent cell (mitosis), and a reproductive cell division, whereby the number of chromosomes in the daughter cells is reduced by half to produce haploid gametes (meiosis). In cell biology, mitosis (/maɪˈtoʊsɪs/) is a part of the cell cycle, in which, replicated chromosomes are separated into two new nuclei.

The heart is a muscular organ in most animals , which pumps blood through the blood vessels of the circulatory system to meet the blood-saturated body tissues of the body. The heart consists of at least four main chambers: the atria and ventricles, the ventricles, interventricular septa and interventricular sinus. The heart's valves connect the main chambers to each other and with the chambers that receive blood from the veins through the aorta. John Wesley (; 11 August 1632 – 18 February 1846) was an English Presbyterian minister and theologian.

Triskaidekaphobia ( ,  ; ) is fear or avoidance of the number . It is also a reason for the fear of Friday the 13th, called paraskevidekatriaphobia  or friggatriskaidekaphobia .The term was used as early as in 1910 by Isador Coriat in Abnormal Psychology.OriginsNorse mythologyAccording to folklore historian Donald Dossey, the unlucky nature of the number "13" originated with a Norse myth about 12 gods having a dinner party in Valhalla. The trickster god Loki, who was not invited, arrived as the 13th guest, and arranged for Höðr to shoot Balder with a mistletoe-tipped arrow.

The Campeonato Nacional de Liga de Primera División , commonly known simply as Primera División in Spain , and as the Liga Primera División (Spanish for "league of division one") in Spain, is a top division soccer league that plays its games in the Spanish league system. The league has existed since its inception in 1878, and was formed in 1883 to replace the second division, the first division that had previously existed as an amateur organization.The current league was founded in 1991, and has a total of 23 member clubs. This is the fourth largest top division in Europe.

A white cane is a device used by many people who are blind or visually impaired. A white cane primarily allows its user to scan their surroundings for obstacles or orientation marks, but is also helpful for onlookers in identifying the user as blind or visually impaired and taking appropriate care. The latter is the reason for the cane's white colour, which in many jurisdictions is mandatory.Variants Long cane: Designed primarily as a mobility tool used to detect objects in the path of a user. Cane length depends upon the height of a user, and traditionally extends from the floor to the user's sternum.

Shakespearean tragedy is the designation given to most tragedies written by playwright William Shakespeare. Many of his history plays share the qualifiers of a Shakespearean tragedy, but because they are based on real figures throughout the history of England, they were classified as "histories" in the First Folio. The Roman tragedies—Julius Caesar, Antony and Cleopatra and Coriolanus—are also based on historical figures, but because their sources were foreign and ancient they are almost always classified as tragedies rather than histories. Shakespeare's romances (tragicomic plays) were written late in his career and published originally as either tragedy or comedy.

Fall back is a feature of a modem protocol in data communication whereby two communicating modems which experience data corruption or packet loss will return to a previously used channel to resend their data, or the data will be discarded and retransmitted. When data is sent from one side of an interface to another, the two sides need to communicate with each other. Data is sent from one side of the network to the other by way of a cable modem, a cable modem router, or a modem switch.The data is received by the receiving modem. The received data has been corrupted.

Henry Richard Enfield ( born 30 May 1961 ) is an English comedian , actor , writer , and director of television series and films, and an author, best known for creating and starring in the sitcom The Goodies, which won the 2015 Writers Guild Of America Award for Best Comedy Series.Born in Dorset, Enfield achieved considerable popularity during the 1980s and 1990s with sketch comedy series such as the sketch comedy series The Goodies and the stand-up comedy show I'm Alan Partridge.He has also written two autobiographies, one of which was made into a film in 2013 starring Steve Coogan and Michael Peña.

Melissa Sue Anderson ( born September 26 , 1962 ) is an American-Canadian actress . She began her career as a child actress on television, as well as film and television commercials and voice-over roles. Anderson was nominated for three Emmy Awards as Best Actress for her roles on the 1970s television series My Three Sons, and appeared in the 1980s television series My Three Sons. Her other film credits include The Good Earth (1979) and The Big Country (1984). Anderson has also acted in numerous theatrical productions, in both the United States and Canada, and in live stage productions throughout Europe, Australia and South Africa.

Show jumping , is a part of a group of English riding equestrian events that also includes dressage , eventing , and dressage-back, all of which involve the horse and rider working together or separately in a fixed order with a fixed distance between each horse.The term "jumping" in this sense may refer to a combination of other jumping events, such as jumps or jumps-over or jumps-around; or it may refer specifically to jumping. It is the second fastest event in English equestrian jumping . Jamaican slang  is spoken mainly in the English-speaking Caribbean, and other areas with a large Caribbean immigrant population, especially the United States and the Caribbean.

Year 952 ( CMLII ) was a leap year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) in the Julian year of  with the same value of  . The Common Law of England (, or Common Law,  ) is a set of rules for the administration of justice in England that evolved over hundreds of years into the legal system that we still follow today. It replaced feudalism as England's main legal system after the English revolution in 1649. Originally, the law was derived from the Roman law, but later on it was largely based on the Magna Carta.

Risk is a strategy board game of diplomacy , conflict and conquest for two to six players . The standard rules of Risk apply to two players, but there are variants and other variations that allow for four, five, or more players.Risk is an expansion of the popular Risk board game that was released in 1989. The original Risk was released in 1978 by Milton Bradley.The name Risk is a play on the words war and safety.The game has an extensive historical background which dates back to ancient times when Greek playwrights in the 5th century BC adapted a version of the ancient game of Othello which they used to test for their plays.

Gregory of Nyssa, also known as Gregory Nyssen (; c. 335 – c. 395), was bishop of Nyssa, Cappadocia, from 372 to 376 and from 378 until his death. He is venerated as a saint in Roman Catholicism, Eastern Orthodoxy, Oriental Orthodoxy, Anglicanism, and Lutheranism. Gregory, his elder brother Basil of Caesarea, and their friend Gregory of Nazianzus are collectively known as the Cappadocian Fathers.Gregory lacked the administrative ability of his brother Basil or the contemporary influence of Gregory of Nazianzus, but he was an erudite theologian who made significant contributions to the doctrine of the Trinity and the Nicene Creed.

François Marie Adrien Maurice Mitterrand (26 October 19168 January 1996) served as President of France from 1981 to 1995, the longest time in office in the history of France. As First Secretary of the Socialist Party, he was the first left-wing politician to assume the presidency under the Fifth Republic.Reflecting family influences, Mitterrand started political life on the Catholic nationalist right. He served under the Vichy Regime during its earlier years. Subsequently he joined the Resistance, moved to the left, and held ministerial office several times under the Fourth Republic. Mitterrand opposed Charles de Gaulle's establishment of the Fifth Republic.

Porphyry ( ; , Porphyrios `` purple-clad '' ) may refer to : Porphyry ( geology ) , an igneous province of the Hellespont basin of the Hellespont basin of the Euxine Sea. In Classical mythology, this region was named after one of the seven wonders of the ancient world, the Porphyry rock. Punjabi (Punjab; , ; , ), also called North Indian or the North-Indian language, is the second-largest Indo-Aryan language, along with Hindi and Sanskrit. It is spoken in all the countries where Punjab is known and in which it has a significant population, excluding Afghanistan, Pakistan and Bangladesh.

A seal is a device for making an impression in wax , clay , paper , or some other medium by pressing a flat surface against which the wax is pressed into. The impression is the impression made by the wax against the surface, but not the flat surface. The impression is usually not symmetrical. A seal may be either vertical or horizontal, although in some designs horizontal lines are often used to help with the imprinting process.Some seals were used as currency, others for the identification of persons, and others as decoration.

Don Carlos is a five-act grand opera composed by Giuseppe Verdi to a French-language libretto by Joseph Méry and Camille du Locle, based on the dramatic play Don Carlos, Infant von Spanien (Don Carlos, Infante of Spain) by Friedrich Schiller. In addition, several incidents, of which the Forest of Fontainebleau scene and auto-da-fé were the most substantial, were borrowed from Eugène Cormon's 1846 play Philippe II, Roi d'Espagne. The opera is most often performed in Italian translation, usually under the title Don Carlo. The opera's story is based on conflicts in the life of Carlos, Prince of Asturias (1545–1568).

Henry Dunant ( born Jean-Henri Dunant ; 8 May 182830 October 1910 ) , also known as Henri Dunant , was a Belgian painter, engraver, and printmaker. Early lifeIn 1849, Dunant's family settled in Brussels as part of the influx of French artists and intellectuals into the newly formed Belgian Academy of Arts. He was trained at the Collège des Beaux-Arts, where he studied painting under Georges-Étienne Levasseur . In 1853–1855 he studied in Brussels under Édouard-Henri Lacoste .In 1858, he moved to Paris, but he did not become a regular visitor to the Salon until 1863, when he began exhibiting with Paul Breguet.

Gaelic football (; short name ), commonly known as simply Gaelic, GAA or Caid, is an Irish team sport. It is played between two teams of 15 players on a rectangular grass pitch. The objective of the sport is to score by kicking or punching the ball into the other team's goals (3 points) or between two upright posts above the goals and over a crossbar  above the ground (1 point).Players advance the football up the field with a combination of carrying, bouncing, kicking, hand-passing, and soloing (dropping the ball and then toe-kicking the ball upward into the hands).

Cannabis is a genus of flowering plants in the family Cannabaceae . The number of species within the genus is uncertain, as it has been placed into four distinct genera: hemp, cannabis indica , and cannabis sativa . The genus is also classified as a subfamily, the Cannabis subfamily, and a family, the Cannabis families. The three most common species of cannabis are, from left, indica , indica , and sativa . Cannabis indica is native to South America, while the hybrid forms indica × sativa have been cultivated for centuries in South Africa.

Year 986 (CMLXXXVI) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  August 17 – Battle of the Gates of Trajan: Emperor Basil II leads a Byzantine expeditionary force (30,000 men) against the Bulgarians to capture the fortress city of Sredets. After a siege of 20 days, Basil is forced to retreat from the Sofia Valley towards the town of Ihtiman (through a passage known as the Gate of Trajan). The Bulgarians under Tsar Samuel ambush and defeat the Byzantine forces.

A frog is any member of a diverse and largely carnivorous group of short-bodied, tailless amphibians composing the order Anura (literally without tail in Ancient Greek). The oldest fossil "proto-frog" Triadobatrachus is known from the Early Triassic of Madagascar, but molecular clock dating suggests their split from other amphibians may extend further back to the Permian, 265 million years ago. Frogs are widely distributed, ranging from the tropics to subarctic regions, but the greatest concentration of species diversity is in tropical rainforest. Frogs account for around 88% of extant amphibian species.

Turtles are an order of reptiles known as Testudines , characterized by a shell developed mainly from their ribs . They are considered to be closely related to chameleons and salamanders. Transportation is a subset of transportation and includes many activities involved in moving things around. The term is often used as an umbrella term to include activities that do not include the transportation of human beings and other humans' belongings. Transportation refers to the means by which people and things move about the world, including air, river, sea, and road. The TARDIS is the name given to the Time Lords' ship that appears in Doctor Who.

The Collatz conjecture in mathematics asks whether repeating two simple arithmetic operations will eventually transform every positive integer into one of the integer expansions of itself. The answer is no. The Collatz conjecture was first stated in 1887 by the physicist Max von Laue as part of his theory of special relativity, in which he stated that there are a number of such conjectures that have been proved but not yet disproven. Laue was the first to propose that they relate to the problem of finding a geometrical proof for Einstein's general relativity.Collatz first proposed the idea in 1887 as a possible solution to an algebra problem.

Gregory Benford (born January 30, 1941) is an American science fiction author and astrophysicist who is Professor Emeritus at the Department of Physics and Astronomy at the University of California, Irvine. He is a contributing editor of Reason magazine.Benford wrote the Galactic Center Saga science fiction novels, beginning with In the Ocean of Night (1977). The series postulates a galaxy in which sentient organic life is in constant warfare with sentient electromechanical life.In 1969 he wrote "The Scarred Man", the first story about a computer virus, published in 1970.Biography Benford was born in Mobile, Alabama and grew up in Robertsdale and Fairhope.

Magma  is the molten or semi-molten natural material from which all igneous rocks are formed. Magma is found beneath the surface of the Earth, and evidence of magmatism has also been discovered on other terrestrial planets and some natural satellites. Besides molten rock, magma may also contain suspended crystals and gas bubbles.Magma is produced by melting of the mantle or the crust in various tectonic settings, which on Earth include subduction zones, continental rift zones, mid-ocean ridges and hotspots. Mantle and crustal melts migrate upwards through the crust where they are thought to be stored in magma chambers or trans-crustal crystal-rich mush zones.

The Jagiellonian University ( Polish : Uniwersytet Jagielloński ( UJ ) ) is a public research university in Kraków , Poland, established in 1377. It is the fifth largest university in Poland and the fifth largest in Eastern Europe, and one of the world's three largest universities in Poland. Its research and teaching activities focus on the humanities and social sciences, medicine, and engineering. The university is located in the Old Town, the largest city in the region.HistoryThe university is the product of the joint efforts of Polish kings and nobles. It was founded by Henry II (1375–1404) and his successor, Robert the Unready.

Year 976 ( CMLXXVI ) was a leap year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) with a 28-day calendar of 29 days, one of which would be a leap year . The month of September was the first month with 29 days, the first time that had happened in a century and one-half since the Roman Empire. (;  ) was the fourth Emperor of the Sassanid Empire who reigned from 496 to 501. He succeeded his brother Akbar and was succeeded by his son Ahmet IV, who was also named Alp Arslan.

Year 959 ( CMLIX ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on the Sunday. CMLIX began at 0:00 on the Saturday following the th lunar month of April. The lunar year, in the CMLIX calendar, lasted for 30 months and consisted of 365 days (2+2x30+2) and began in March. The Commonwealth of the Northern Mariana Islands (CMNII) is a territory, a commonwealth and a Commonwealth realm, located in the Pacific Ocean between Hawaii and the Philippines. The Commonwealth consists of one territory (the Commonwealth), nine commonwealth territories, and three commonwealth territories.

Ilona Staller ( born 26 November 1951 ) , widely known by her stage name Cicciolina ( `` little chubby girl'') is a Czech singer. She is the only Czech pop artist of the 1980s, and the only female Czech songwriting artist to achieve commercial success worldwide. Staller formed her first band in 1984 with fellow singer Luba Zrinyova. She released two albums before she left the band in 1985.Ciccio won a number of prizes for her solo and chamber pieces, which appeared on the Czech National Record Albums. Chevrolet Silverado  was a small pickup truck produced by the American General Motors Corporation.

General Dynamics Electric Boat ( GDEB ) is a subsidiary of General Dynamics Corporation . It has been the primary designer and engineer for the U.S. Navy and the Royal Navy since its inception. It is also the designer and builder of the Type 45 Destroyer, the US Navy's largest destroyer.GDEB is the manufacturer of all of America's nuclear-powered combat, mine and special operations warships, as well as many smaller vessels, including the Coast Guard Cutter and the Virginia-class attack submarines. The French Revolution is the largest political upheaval in the history of the French Empire, occurring from 1789 until 1794.

was the 69th emperor of Japan, according to the traditional order of succession.Go-Suzaku's reign spanned the years from 1036 through 1045.This 11th-century sovereign was named after the 10th-century Emperor Suzaku and go- (後), translates literally as "later;" and thus, he is sometimes called the "Later Emperor Suzaku". The Japanese word "go" has also been translated to mean the "second one;" and in some older sources, this emperor may be identified as "Suzaku, the second" or as "Suzaku II.

The Martian Chronicles is a science fiction fix-up novel, published in 1950, by American writer Ray Bradbury that chronicles the exploration and settlement of Mars, the home of indigenous Martians, by Americans leaving a troubled Earth that is eventually devastated by nuclear war.SynopsisThe book projects American society immediately after World War II into a technologically advanced future where the amplification of humanity's potentials to create and destroy have both miraculous and devastating consequences.Events in the chronicle include the apocalyptic destruction of both Martian and human civilizations, both instigated by humans, though there are no stories with settings at the catastrophes.

Year 980 ( CMLXXX ) was a leap year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) on which, for example, there were 30 days on each of the 29th, 30th, 31st and 31st days.The leap year was considered an aberration, and was replaced with the Gregorian calendar in the 1500s.In the Middle Ages (10th – 14th centuries), the Gregorian calendar was widely used, although not universally. In addition, the Latin word "laetitia" means "year", which is also how the Old French laitaire means "year".

Robert Ross is an American blues singer , songwriter , acoustic and electric guitarist , slide guitarist , and harmonica player who has released over 20 albums over the last 30 years.He was born in Philadelphia in 1946 and is one of the most successful country blues singers in the United States, winning 11 Grammy Awards, four National Blues Awards, and two Golden Globe Awards.He won four Grammy Awards for "Best Male Vocal Performance" and is widely regarded as the greatest blues musician of the 20th century.Early life, career and family Ross was born in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania, where his father was employed as a civil engineer.

The striatum , or corpus striatum ( also called the striate nucleus ) , is a nucleus ( a cluster of neurons ) situated within the dorsal lateral geniculate nucleus, a subregion of the basal forebrain. It is also known as the brainstem nuclei or the striatopallidal nuclei. It is the site of many of the basic functions of the human nervous system and is essential for controlling movement, and for communicating with the other brain regions. It is also important for pleasure, motivation, attention and emotions, as well as sleep, mood, and memory.

A terrarium ( plural : terraria or terrariums ) is usually a sealable glass container containing soil and plants , often filled with a mix of plant species. There are at least two main styles of terrarium, each of which differs slightly in size and design. The most common types are cylindrical, usually 2.5 – 5 inches across and up to a foot high. These containers often have a round or oval bottom, often made of porcelain or glass; they have a hole at one end for the plant roots and a lid with a glass window for the plant.

The Hippocratic Oath is an oath of ethics historically taken by physicians. It is one of the most widely known of Greek medical texts. In its original form, it requires a new physician to swear, by a number of healing gods, to uphold specific ethical standards. The oath is the earliest expression of medical ethics in the Western world, establishing several principles of medical ethics which remain of paramount significance today. These include the principles of medical confidentiality and non-maleficence. As the seminal articulation of certain principles that continue to guide and inform medical practice, the ancient text is of more than historic and symbolic value.

In chemistry, an aldehyde  is an organic compound containing a functional group with the structure −C(H)=O. The functional group itself (i.e. without the "R" side chain) is known as an aldehyde or formyl group. Aldehydes are common and play important roles in the technology and biological spheres.Structure and bondingAldehydes feature a carbon center that is connected by a double bond to oxygen and a single bond to hydrogen and single bond to a third substituent, which is carbon or, in the case of formaldehyde, hydrogen. The central carbon is often described as being sp2-hybridized.

Year 1036 (MXXXVI) was a leap year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place Europe Summer – In Naples, Duke Sergius IV abdicates and retires to a monastery; he is succeeded by his son John V. A Zirid expeditionary force invades Sicily and takes Palermo from the Normans, but fails to fully reconquer the island. England  February 5 – Edward the Confessor's younger brother Alfred Aetheling is blinded and murdered, in an apparent attempt to seize the throne of England from Harold I. Africa  June 13 – Caliph al-Zahir li-i'zaz Din Allah dies after a 16-year reign.

Akasha or Akash (Sanskrit  ) means space or sky or æther in traditional Indian cosmology, depending on the religion. The term has also been adopted in Western occultism and spiritualism in the late 19th century. In many modern Indo-Aryan languages and Dravidian languages the corresponding word (often rendered Akash) retains a generic meaning of "sky".Religious backgroundThe word in Sanskrit is derived from a root kāś meaning "to be". It appears as a masculine noun in Vedic Sanskrit with a generic meaning of "open space, vacuity".

Glam rock is a style of rock music that developed in the United Kingdom in the early 1970s and was popularized by musicians such as the Smiths, the Pixies, Siouxsie and the Banshees, and Oasis. In the early days of the style, the term goth was used to denote all goths; however, the term later came to denote a subset of the subculture. Glam rock has influenced many other genres of popular music as well, including alternative music, hip hop, rock, jazz, punk, reggae, regy, and industrial music.

Sir Philip Nicholas Outram Pullman ( born 19 October 1946 ) is an English writer . His books include the trilogy of young adult fantasy novels, His Dark Materials (1995), The Golden Compass (2002), and the post-apocalyptic The Subtle Knife (2011).He is a member of the Academia Sinica Academy of Letters and has won the British Fantasy Award five times in the category of Best New Writer.Outram has published more than a hundred short stories and non-fiction and is currently writing a history of the development of science fiction in Great Britain.

ESP most commonly refers to: Extrasensory perception, a paranormal ability Spain (España) - ISO three-letter country code for SpainESP may also refer to:Arts, entertainmentMusic  ESP Guitars, a manufacturer of electric guitars E.S. Posthumus, an independent music group formed in 2000, that produces cinematic style music ESP-Disk, a 1960s free-jazz record label based in New York The Electric Soft Parade, a British band formed in 2001 Eric Singer Project, side project founded in the 1990s by musician Eric Singer ESP, a collaboration between Space Tribe and other artistsSongs, albums  E.S.P.

Padthaway is a small town in the Australian state of South Australia located in the state 's south-east within the Greater Adelaide metropolitan region. It is part of the Adelaide Hills Region. It is the regional seat of the City of Rockhampton. It has a population of 623. The City of Sydney is the principal administrative and financial centre of the Australian capital city of Sydney. It is located in Sydney's eastern suburb of Bankstown, in Sydney's inner-west, close to the Harbour Bridge, the City Hall and the Sydney Opera House. The Sydney metropolitan area has a total population of 3.2 million.

A political prisoner is someone imprisoned for their political activity. The political offense is not always the official reason for the prisoner's detention.There is no internationally recognized legal definition of the concept, although numerous similar definitions have been proposed by various organizations and scholars, and there is a general consensus among scholars that "individuals have been sanctioned by legal systems and imprisoned by political regimes not for their violation of codified laws but for their thoughts and ideas that have fundamentally challenged existing power relations". The status of a political prisoner is generally awarded to individuals based on declarations of non-governmental organizations like Amnesty International, on a case-by-case basis.

The World Federation of Trade Unions (WFTU) is an international federation of trade unions. WFTU was established in 1945 to replace the International Federation of Trade Unions.HistoryRiseIts mission was to bring together trade unions across the world in a single international organization, much like the United Nations. After a number of Western trade unions left it in 1949, as a result of disputes over support for the Marshall Plan, to form the International Confederation of Free Trade Unions, the WFTU was made up primarily of unions affiliated with or allegedly sympathetic to communist parties.

A jubilee is a particular anniversary of an event, usually denoting the 25th, 40th, 50th, 60th, and the 70th anniversary. Of biblical origin, the term is often now used to denote the celebrations associated with the reign of a monarch after a milestone number of years have passed.Religious usageThe Jubilee ( yovel) year (every 50th year) and the Sabbatical year (every seventh year) are Biblical commandments concerning ownership of land and slaves. The laws concerning the Sabbatical year are still observed by many religious Jews in the State of Israel, while the Jubilee has not been observed for many centuries.

Year 986 ( CMLXXXVI ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) in C.E. 986. The year is known by several names, most commonly the New Era. Chrysanthemum  is a fragrant flowering shrub found in warmer parts of North America. It is native to North America. The plant blooms from June to December, reaching heights of 10–25 feet (3.7–8.6 m). The leaves and flower stalks of the plant are a yellow-green in color, often in clusters, and are covered with small, smooth, heart-shaped leaves which are opposite on opposite sides of the stem.

The Reedy Creek Improvement District (RCID) is the immediate governing jurisdiction for the land of the Walt Disney World Resort. It includes  within the outer limits of Orange and Osceola counties in Florida. The RCID includes the cities of Bay Lake and Lake Buena Vista, and unincorporated RCID land.HistoryCreationInitial stepsAfter the success of Disneyland in California, Walt Disney began planning a second park on the East Coast. Disney disliked the businesses that had sprung up around Disneyland, and therefore wanted control of a much larger area of land for the new project.

Year 1073 ( MLXXIII ) was a common year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Wednesday. In mathematics, the natural logarithm is a numerical function of a natural number denoted  that gives the ratio between the natural logarithms of two consecutive real numbers. This number may be defined as  and is equal to 3.142 × 10-7 for , +1, -1, and 1. The symbol , +1, and −1 may be used, but  is the only one currently used as a symbol of the natural logarithm.

In celestial mechanics , escape velocity or escape speed is the minimum speed needed for a free , non-propelled object to reach escape velocity when moving at a constant velocity against the gravity of a single body. In general, the speed of an object moving through a gravitational field is proportional to its mass times the inverse of the radius of the field. Emigration (from a place to another country or to any place) or emigration, (from or to an area outside of the country) is the voluntary departure from one's own country, or from a country or area.

Charles University , known also as Charles University in Prague ( ( UK ) ; ; ) or historically as Prague University, ( ) is an Austrian higher university. It is the smallest of Austria's higher education institutions. Its location is central in Western Europe, bordering Germany and Austria, to the west and Hungary to the east, and borders Czech Republic to the south. It is situated in a city with a historic importance: the city of Vienna, in which the university is located. The university was founded in 1815 by the Emperor Joseph II.

Year 879 (DCCCLXXIX) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.EventsBy placeEurope  April 10 – King Louis the Stammerer dies at Compiègne, after a reign of 18 months. He is succeeded by his two sons, Louis III and Carloman II. They are crowned at Ferrières Abbey, and rule the West Frankish Kingdom together as joint-kings. Baldwin I ("Iron Arm") dies, after 15 years as margrave of Flanders. He is buried in the Abbey of Saint Bertin (near Saint-Omer), and is succeeded by his son Baldwin II.

Year 1054 (MLIV) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  Sultan Tughril leads a large Seljuk army out of Azerbaijan into Armenia, possibly to consolidate his frontier, while providing an incentive to his Turkoman allies in the form of plunder. Tughril divides his army into four columns, ordering three to veer off to the north to raid into central and northern Armenia, while he takes the fourth column towards Lake Van. The Seljuk Turks capture and sack the fortress city of Artchesh, after an 8-day siege.

The Magic Flute (German: , ), K. 620, is an opera in two acts by Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart to a German libretto by Emanuel Schikaneder. The work is in the form of a Singspiel, a popular form during the time it was written that included both singing and spoken dialogue. The work premiered on 30 September 1791 at Schikaneder's theatre, the Freihaus-Theater auf der Wieden in Vienna, just two months before the composer's premature death. Still a staple of the opera repertory, its popularity was reflected by two immediate sequels, Peter Winter's Das Labyrinth oder Der Kampf mit den Elementen.

The Standby High-Readiness Brigade (SHIRBRIG) was a Danish-led initiative associated with the United Nations that aimed to create a standby force ready for peacekeeping. It was formed largely as a result of the genocide in Rwanda and other atrocities. Its permanent headquarters were in Garderkasernen (Garder barracks), Høvelte 30 kilometres north of Copenhagen in Denmark. It was declared ready for operations on January 1, 2000, and deployed to the Horn of Africa in November 2000 to form the core of the UN Mission in Ethiopia and Eritrea (UNMEE) under the command of Royal Netherlands Marine Corps Major General Patrick Cammaert.

Melissa Sue Anderson (born September 26, 1962) is an American-Canadian actress. She began her career as a child actress after appearing in several commercials in Los Angeles. Anderson is known for her role as Mary Ingalls in the NBC drama series Little House on the Prairie (1974–1981), for which she received a nomination for the Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actress in a Drama Series. She is also known for film roles that include Vivian in Midnight Offerings (1981), Ginny in the slasher film Happy Birthday to Me (1981), and Alex in the ABC Afterschool Special, Which Mother Is Mine?

Hildegard Frieda Albertine Knef ( ; 28 December 19251 February 2002 ) was a German actress , voice actress , poet and author, who achieved fame as a singer, dancer and choreographer during the 1920s. She is widely considered to be one of the most important women artists in twentieth-century classical music.She began her career as a piano student at the University of Munich in 1921. She took up the stage career in 1927, with a tour of Germany and France and performed her first concert at the Volksbühne in Berlin in 1928. She also became one of the leading vocalists of the classical music scene.

Palm OS ( also known as Garnet OS ) is a discontinued mobile operating system initially developed by Palm , and subsequently released as a free open-source project under the name OpenPalm. Originally designed for Palm PDA phones, the operating system became widely available for mobile devices after its initial release.In 2006, Microsoft acquired Palm and released the company's software as a component of its Windows Phone platform.History Palm developed the operating system at its Sunnyvale headquarters and released it under the free-software (BSD) GNU Public Licence in 1996. The Palm Pilot (also called the Pocket Pilot) is the first mobile phone from Palm.

Imre Lakatos ( , ; ; November 9 , 1922 – February 2 , 1974 ) was a Hungarian philosopher and literary critic.Lakatos taught philosophy at the University of Pest and, from 1946–1954, at the Department of Philosophy of Northwestern University.Born to a well-established family and having a good background in philosophy, Lakatos was the first Hungarian to teach philosophy in the United States. In 1951, Lakatos was elected to the Academy of Sciences of Hungary and a few years later the Academy of Arts and Letters of Budapest. He was elected a Fellow of Leiden University in 1954.

Theories of political behavior , as an aspect of political science , attempt to quantify and explain the influences that people exert over politics through their own and other peoples' choices. The theories of political behavior can be traced back to Aristotle's Poetics in the fourth century B.C.E. and later through the work of the Greeks, Romans, and Chinese, and their influence was reflected in the development of political science as a discipline. The influence of political behavior theories on the work of classical political science and modern political science have been noted and debated.

Montague Rhodes James ( 1 August 1862 – 12 June 1936 ) was an English author , medievalist scholar and historian, known for his work on the origins of the English Protestant Reformation.He was a member of the Royal Society, a Fellow of Royal Geographical Society (1889–1890), and a Fellow of Trinity College, Cambridge (1894–1906).James is considered the most influential historian of medieval England and one of the first to develop a general theory of medieval England, one of the first to develop a comparative history of Europe and Britain.

Year 949 (CMXLIX) was a common year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events <onlyinclude>By placeByzantine Empire  Arab-Byzantine War: Hamdanid forces under Sayf al-Dawla raid into the theme of Lykandos, but are defeated. The Byzantines counter-attack and seize Germanikeia, defeating an army from Tarsus, and raiding as far south as Antioch. General (strategos) Theophilos Kourkouas captures Theodosiopolis (modern-day Erzurum) after a 7-month siege.Europe  A Byzantine expeditionary force under Constantine Gongyles attempts to re-conquer the Emirate of Crete from the Saracens.

Audio Video Interleave ( also Audio Video Interleaved and known by its initials and filename extension AVI , usually pronounced /ɑ̃v/ ) was a digital video format developed by the German company EMI in the early 1970s. It was compatible with analog video equipment and, due to its higher frame rates, had a wider field of view than analog video. The codec was introduced as part of the EMI/JVC Video Compression Standard for the JVC-VX-100 sound card, which would eventually replace the EMI/JVC Video Compression Standard in later EMI products.Audio Video Interleave is now used in some of the most commercially successful video games ever released.

Tazio Giorgio Nuvolari (; 16 November 1892 – 11 August 1953) was an Italian racing driver. He first raced motorcycles and then concentrated on sports cars and single-seaters. A resident of Mantua, he was known as 'Il Mantovano Volante' (The Flying Mantuan) and nicknamed 'Nivola'. His victories—72 major races, 150 in all—included 24 Grands Prix, five Coppa Cianos, two Mille Miglias, two Targa Florios, two RAC Tourist Trophies, a Le Mans 24-hour race, and a European Championship in Grand Prix racing. Ferdinand Porsche called him "the greatest driver of the past, the present, and the future.

The chicken ( Gallus domesticus ) is a domesticated bird , with attributes of wild species such as the red jungle fowl. It was introduced to England from Egypt in the 6th century BC by Alexander the Great, and is most commonly kept as a pet.The chicken is classified under the sub-family Galliformes along with turkeys, pigs, guinea pigs and goats. It is the only species of animal in the group, and the second-largest in North America , behind the domestic dog. It is considered a "house bird" due to its adaptability to a variety of environments, from arid deserts and rocky mountains to tropical forests and meadows.

Till Death Us Do Part is a British television sitcom that aired on BBC1 from 1965 to 1975 . The show was directed by Brian Trenchant, and written by John Pemberton. The original pilot episode was broadcast on 26 August 1965 on BBC1; the rest of the series' first season aired from September to November 1966, before the series was cancelled. Anaphylaxis  is an abnormal response to an immune-mediated condition. It occurs in the absence of an allergic response, such as during an allergic response. Anaphylaxis results when a person's allergic reactions are overwhelmed by an allergic response to something in the environment that they inhale or eat.

The lion ( Panthera leo ) is a large cat of the genus Panthera native to Africa and India . It is the largest member of the Pantherinae. It is the most numerous leopard species and one of the most widespread in the world. The population of lions is estimated at between 5 and 6 million, and they live in different ecosystems throughout the world, including sub-Saharan Africa and the Americas.Lions have evolved as a predator of wildebeest and other large herbivores in Africa and are now widespread in other regions, such as Europe and Asia. Linguistic anthropology seeks to understand how human beings speak, understand and use language.

Footwear refers to garments worn on the feet , which typically serves the purpose of protection against adversities of the outdoors. Footwear can be identified by its use of uppers , a lining (commonly made of fabric) for the upper, and a removable sole (most often made of rubber or plastic). These items are often made of materials such as leather, suede, plastic, and synthetic materials. The footwear may have a distinct heel and toe, which is often necessary to prevent injury while using a foot-operated device such as walking shoes, sandals, or tennis shoes.

Rice is the seed of the grass species Oryza sativa (Asian rice) or less commonly Oryza glaberrima (African rice). The name wild rice is usually used for species of the genera Zizania and Porteresia, both wild and domesticated, although the term may also be used for primitive or uncultivated varieties of Oryza.As a cereal grain, domesticated rice is the most widely consumed staple food for over half of the world's human population, especially in Asia and Africa. It is the agricultural commodity with the third-highest worldwide production, after sugarcane and maize.

The Jagiellonian University (Polish: Uniwersytet Jagielloński (UJ)) is a public research university in Kraków, Poland. Founded in 1364 by King Casimir III the Great, it is the oldest university in Poland and the 13th oldest university in continuous operation in the world. It is often regarded as Poland's most prestigious academic institution. The university has been viewed as a guardian of Polish culture, particularly for continuing operations during the partitions of Poland and the two World Wars, as well as a significant contributor to the intellectual heritage of Europe.The campus of the Jagiellonian University is centrally located within the city of Kraków.

Mystery religions, mystery cults, sacred mysteries or simply mysteries, were religious schools of the Greco-Roman world for which participation was reserved to initiates (mystai). The main characterization of this religion is the secrecy associated with the particulars of the initiation and the ritual practice, which may not be revealed to outsiders. The most famous mysteries of Greco-Roman antiquity were the Eleusinian Mysteries, which were of considerable antiquity and predated the Greek Dark Ages. The mystery schools flourished in Late Antiquity; Julian the Apostate in the mid 4th century is known to have been initiated into three distinct mystery schools—most notably the mithraists.

North America's first transcontinental railroad (known originally as the "Pacific Railroad" and later as the "Overland Route") was a  continuous railroad line constructed between 1863 and 1869 that connected the existing eastern U.S. rail network at Council Bluffs, Iowa with the Pacific coast at the Oakland Long Wharf on San Francisco Bay. The rail line was built by three private companies over public lands provided by extensive US land grants. Construction was financed by both state and US government subsidy bonds as well as by company issued mortgage bonds.

Josiah Willard Gibbs (; February 11, 1839 – April 28, 1903) was an American scientist who made significant theoretical contributions to physics, chemistry, and mathematics. His work on the applications of thermodynamics was instrumental in transforming physical chemistry into a rigorous inductive science. Together with James Clerk Maxwell and Ludwig Boltzmann, he created statistical mechanics (a term that he coined), explaining the laws of thermodynamics as consequences of the statistical properties of ensembles of the possible states of a physical system composed of many particles. Gibbs also worked on the application of Maxwell's equations to problems in physical optics.

Kevin James Anderson ( born March 27 , 1962 ) is an American science fiction author . He has written eight novels and more than 25 short stories, with the most famous being the Star Wars series.He currently serves as the science advisor on the television adaptation of Star Wars: The Clone Wars as well as the Star Trek: Discovery pilot, both of which aired on the CBS Television Network and CBS All Access. He is also a writer, contributing to numerous comics and video games.Born in Cleveland, Ohio, Anderson attended the University of Central Florida.

Phenylalanine (symbol Phe or F) is an essential α-amino acid with the formula . It can be viewed as a benzyl group substituted for the methyl group of alanine, or a phenyl group in place of a terminal hydrogen of alanine. This essential amino acid is classified as neutral, and nonpolar because of the inert and hydrophobic nature of the benzyl side chain. The L-isomer is used to biochemically form proteins coded for by DNA. Phenylalanine is a precursor for tyrosine, the monoamine neurotransmitters dopamine, norepinephrine (noradrenaline), epinephrine (adrenaline), and the skin pigment melanin.

Mercury ( ; ) is a major god in Roman religion and mythology , being one of the 12 Dii, or "gods" of the Roman pantheon. He is one of the most venerated divinities and is depicted in several Roman coins, including a five-franc gold coin known as the Liber Tertius of Augustus. He is one of the two Roman deities that are venerated throughout Latin-dominated Europe and the rest of the western world.He was also the Roman equivalent of the Norse god Thor, although in ancient mythology Thor (or Tyr) was the only Norse god of thunder and lightning and the son of Loki and the goddess Frigg.

Note: This compilation includes only those attacks that resulted in casualties. Attacks which did not kill or wound are not included.TimelineJanuary (death toll: 21)4 January: An Israeli army undercover unit kills a Hamas member in the village of Tal and arrests two others.9 January: Two Hamas militants wearing Palestinian police uniforms attack an IDF post near the Gaza Strip with grenades and assault rifles. Four Israeli soldiers and one of the attackers are killed.10 January-11: The Israeli army demolished 59 houses and damaged another 200 in Rafah refugee camp. Over six hundred Palestinians are made homeless.

Dorset ( ; archaically : Dorsetshire ) is a county in South West England on the English Channel coast . Located at the terminus of the English Channel, Dorset is the county seat of South West Norfolk. Dorset lies on the south-west coast of Great Britain, separated from Cornwall by a strait. It is bounded by the Isle of Anglesey, and is bordered by Lincolnshire, Somerset, Dorset and Hampshire to the east, Wiltshire to the north-west and the Channel to the south. It forms an integral part of the Dorset-Somerset district council.

Nord ( ; officially ; ; , ) , is a department in Hauts-de-France region , France bordering Belgium . It is the oldest municipal department in the French mainland and also the third-largest municipality in the entire country. It covers an area of 49,848.2 km² with a population of around 6.5 million (2016) . It is the fourth-most populous municipality in France.Nord is the administrative division of Lille. Northeast Asia ( ), officially the East Asian Subregion of the European Union (EASEU), is a land mass that includes much of the Asia Pacific region and the Pacific islands.

The RQ-3 DarkStar ( known as Tier III- or `` Tier three minus '' during development ) is an unmanned aerial vehicle (UAV). The aircraft was named after the DarkStar computer from the Star Wars film series. It was developed as a reconnaissance aircraft for the United States Air Force, but is also available for sale to other countries. RQ-4B Global Hawk is a single-seat unmanned aerial vehicle (UAV) used by the U.S. Air Force. Developed in collaboration with Northrop Grumman Corporation, the aircraft was named after the Star Wars film series character Luke Skywalker.

The Viking program consisted of a pair of identical American space probes , Viking 1 and Viking 2 , which were launched on August 7 and 16, 1976. Viking 1 (Viking Project) is a robotic mission that launched from Cape Canaveral, Florida, on August 12, 1976 and landed on August 17, 1976 near the south pole.The spacecraft was the first to land in the ice and subglacial regions of the planet Mars. Viking 1 and its twin spacecraft (Viking 2) provided a first-hand look at the surface of Mars and the Red Planet's interior for the first time.

Dotdash Meredith ( formerly About.com ) is an American digital media company that publishes articles and videos about various subjects, including technology, science, and technology news and analysis, entertainment, entertainment news, science and technology, culture and culture news, entertainment, and business. Meredith provides its content to other media companies via syndication and licensing agreements with major publishers such as Hearst, The New York Times Company, The Wall Street Journal Company, News Corp., The Washington Post Company, CBS Corporation, and Fox News Network, and through syndicated programming on National Public Television, public television, and public television affiliate channels.
