Sir Philip Nicholas Outram Pullman  (born 19 October 1946) is an English writer. His books include the fantasy trilogy His Dark Materials and The Good Man Jesus and the Scoundrel Christ, a fictionalised biography of Jesus. In 2008, The Times named Pullman one of the "50 greatest British writers since 1945". In a 2004 BBC poll, he was named the eleventh most influential person in British culture. He was knighted in the 2019 New Year Honours for services to literature.Northern Lights, the first volume in His Dark Materials, won the 1995 Carnegie Medal of the Library Association as the year's outstanding English-language children's book.

The Lhotshampa or Lhotsampa  people are a heterogeneous Bhutanese people of Nepalese descent. "Lhotshampa", which means "southern borderlanders" in Dzongkha, began to be used by the Bhutanese state in the second half of the twentieth century to refer to the population of Nepali origin in the south of the country. Starting in 2007, most of the Lhotshampas, or Bhutanese Refugees, were resettled to various countries, such as the United States, Canada, Australia, the United Kingdom, and other European countries. the number of Lhotshampa in Nepal is significantly lower than that in the United States and other countries where they have resettled.

The red slender loris ( Loris tardigradus ) is a small , nocturnal strepsirrhine primate native to the rainforests of Madagascar and other islands in the Indian Ocean, Asia and Africa.The lorises live in tropical rainforests and scrub-lands throughout their range. They range in color from brown, grey or black, depending on the season, with the largest specimens being about 2.5 feet (0.6 m) long, although the heaviest individual is about 1.8 feet (0.6 m). They are the only known member of the order Strigiformes, belonging to the suborder Acari.

Kristiansund ( , ; historically spelled Christianssund and earlier named Fosna ) is a municipality on the western coast of the island of Gotland, Sweden.The municipality comprises the town of Christiansborg and several surrounding hamlets that are connected by several main roads. It also has a number of small communities, of which Christiansborg Island and Christiansborg Villages in the east are the largest.Christianiansborg was founded by the Danish Kingdom in 866 as a royal residence. The town's castle, which dates from the 13th century, is the oldest standing structure in the municipality. Carmelites are an ancient Greek order of women dedicated to worship of Artemis, Goddess of the hunt.

A U-Boot is a beer cocktail that is made by placing a shot of vodka into a glass of beer and mixing. The combination creates a strong and complex alcoholic cocktail, and the name refers to this.The first known use of the term was in the book "The Art of Mixing Liquor," published in 1904.The name has been widely adopted to describe any strong alcoholic cocktail, although a U-Boot is still commonly referred to as a vodka martini, and the drink is often considered an imitation of a whisky cocktail, rather than a true vodka-based drink.

Year 873 ( DCCCLXXIII ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Monday, March 19, 873, at which year King John was killed. It is the fifth month of the Gregorian Calendar, and the third of the Julian Calendar . It was the final month of the third year of the eighth-century reign of King Henry the First of England, the first of Edward I, and the fifth of Richard II, who ruled from October 878 to September 880.HistoryThe Julian Calendar was used by the Catholic Church until 1752.

Garnets are a group of silicate minerals that have been used since the Bronze Age as gemstones and abrasives.All species of garnet occur in the form of a transparent, nearly translucent crystalline structure or as a matrix. They have a silicate structure, made up of a carbon lattice in which the atoms are arranged differently than the atoms in the corresponding mineral crystal. The silicate lattice consists of alternating alternating layers of a magnesium-silicate cation with a magnesium-magnesium cation, with the magnesium ions at the bottom and the magnesium atoms at the top. Gardasil is an antigens-producing recombinant protein (RFP) vaccine for HPV.

Year 950 ( CML ) was a common year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) on which the Pope was elected. The year is sometimes called the first of the "Great Year," and in modern usage is often identified with the Jubilee, which was celebrated every 25 years. Calendar dates are the days of the calendar year and the days of the month (see table ). The month of a day in the Gregorian or Julian calendar is a name for a group of consecutive days. The numbers 1-31 are the Gregorian days in the Gregorian Calendar.

Audio Video Interleave (also Audio Video Interleaved and known by its initials and filename extension AVI, usually pronounced ), is a proprietary multimedia container format and Windows standard introduced by Microsoft in November 1992 as part of its Video for Windows software. AVI files can contain both audio and video data in a file container that allows synchronous audio-with-video playback. Like the DVD video format, AVI files support multiple streaming audio and video, although these features are seldom used.Many AVI files use the file format extensions developed by the Matrox OpenDML group in February 1996.

The covalent radius , rcov , is a measure of the size of an atom that forms part of one of the crystal structures of an element. It is expressed in absolute units such as microns or angstroms and expresses relative to another atom or molecule, rather than in terms of atomic mass. In absolute units, and relative to another atom, an atom of unit radius corresponds to a unit mass. The value of rcov for any atom is called the atomic radius. It is often referred to as the atomic radius or atomic mass, and is often also called atomic radius or atomic mass.

Turandot ( , ; see below) is an opera in three acts by Giacomo Puccini, posthumously completed by Franco Alfano in 1926, and set to a libretto in Italian by Giuseppe Adami and Renato Simoni. Turandot best-known aria is "Nessun dorma", which became globally popular in the 1990s following Luciano Pavarotti's performance of it for the 1990 FIFA World Cup.Though Puccini first became interested in the subject matter when reading Friedrich Schiller's 1801 adaptation, he based his work more closely on the earlier play Turandot (1762) by Count Carlo Gozzi.

Toilet paper ( sometimes called toilet tissue ) is a tissue paper product primarily used to clean the anus and rectum. It is made of a mixture of water, starch or cellulose and is used to cleanse the anus or rectum of fecal matter, in order to prevent blockage. It can also help to prevent the spread of infection.The most common brand of toilet paper is toilet paper. It comes in white, blue and green. In the United Kingdom and Canada, it is referred to as paper, and is also manufactured by Lifestraw.

The Circus Maximus ( Latin for `` largest circus '' ; Italian : Circo Massimo ) is an ancient Roman circus built by Sulla in 74 A.D. at Rome in honor of his deceased son, Marcus Marcellus. As with other Roman theatres, it was built for the benefit of the rich and powerful. The Circus Maximus was an important source of entertainment in Rome during the later Republic, particularly during the Roman Empire and the later Imperial period. According to the Roman historian Lucian, Sulla planned on building the Circus Maximus for a lifetime of entertainment for Rome's elite, but he failed.

Rococo ( , also ) , less commonly Roccoco or Late Baroque , is an exceptionally ornamental and theatrical style of Spanish art that emerged in the early-seventeenth century. It is a type of Baroque ornament that arose in Italy around 1560, and that developed from the Italian "Romantico", which was derived from Italian Baroque forms. The principal styles of Spanish art of the Rococo and Baroque period include: Spanish painting from the Baroque period, which continued in the late seventeenth-century and the Baroque tradition (1701–1800). Spanish drawing (1600–1789), which flourished between 1612 and 1638 and was a major influence on American painting.

In their most common sense, the terms thought and thinking refer to conscious cognitive processes that can happen independently of sensory stimulation. Their most paradigmatic forms are judging, reasoning, concept formation, problem solving, and deliberation. But other mental processes, like considering an idea, memory, or imagination, are also often included. These processes can happen internally independent of the sensory organs, unlike perception. But when understood in the widest sense, any mental event may be understood as a form of thinking, including perception and unconscious mental processes.

The raven paradox , also known as Hempel 's paradox , Hempel 's ravens , or rarely the paradox of the ravens, is a puzzle that asks whether a raven will always stay in its nest. It is the title of an article written by Kurt Vonnegut in Cat's Cradle: A Novel, which has been adapted into a screenplay. The puzzle was proposed by John Hempel, professor of mathematics at MIT, who published his paper on the paradox in the Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the USA in 1968.

`` Wilhelmus van Nassouwe '' , usually known just as `` Wilhelmus '' ( ; ; English translation : ``Wilhelmus the Elder'' ) was an Anglo-Saxon bishop, poet, theologian, and politician. He died in AD 591 at the age of eighty-six and was buried at Leominster Abbey in the English Midlands, where he is believed to have been buried by his successor,  The Anglo-Norman historian Geoffrey of Monmouth claims that Wilhelmus was born in the English Midlands in AD 570.Wilhelmus spent the rest of his life travelling, writing and lecturing on theology, philosophy and history.

Year 976 (CMLXXVI) was a leap year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  January 10 – Emperor John I Tzimiskes dies at Constantinople, after returning from a second campaign against the Abbasids in Syria. He is buried in the Church of Christ Chalkites, and succeeded by his 18-year-old nephew Basil II, who becomes sole ruler of the Byzantine Empire. The administration remains in the hands of Basil Lekapenos (an illegitimate son of the late Emperor Romanos I). Europe  June – Emir Abu'l-Qasim launches a raiding expedition into Byzantine Italy from Sicily.

A drummer is a percussionist who creates music using drums.Most contemporary western bands that play rock, pop, jazz, or R&B music include a drummer for purposes including timekeeping and embellishing the musical timbre. The drummer's equipment includes a drum kit (or "drum set" or "trap set"), which includes various drums, cymbals and an assortment of accessory hardware such as pedals, standing support mechanisms, and drum sticks.Particularly in the traditional music of many countries, drummers use individual drums of various sizes and designs rather than drum kits.

Michael I ( ; 25 October 1921 – 5 December 2017) was the last King of Romania, reigning from 20 July 1927 to 8 June 1930 and again from 6 September 1940 until his forced abdication on 30 December 1947.Shortly after Michael's birth, his father, Crown Prince Carol of Romania, had become involved in a controversial relationship with Magda Lupescu. In 1925, Carol was pressured to renounce his rights to the throne and moved to Paris in exile with Lupescu. In 1927, Michael ascended the throne, following the death of his grandfather King Ferdinand I.

A knight's tour is a sequence of moves of a knight on a chessboard such that the knight visits every square exactly once. If the knight ends on a square that is one knight's move from the beginning square (so that it could tour the board again immediately, following the same path), the tour is closed (or re-entrant); otherwise, it is open.The knight's tour problem is the mathematical problem of finding a knight's tour. Creating a program to find a knight's tour is a common problem given to computer science students.

Poznań University of Technology, PUT (Polish name: Politechnika Poznańska) is a university in Poznań, Poland. Poznań University of Technology is known as one of the best technical universities in Poland. URAP ranked PUT as in top 6% of world universities and Webometrics ranked it at no. 842 in the world by Google citations for the year 2015. In 1995 it became the first Polish university to become a member of the Conference of European Schools for Advanced Engineering Education and Research (CESAER), an organization comprising the best technical universities in Europe.

Year 1158 (MCLVIII) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  Autumn – Emperor Manuel I (Komnenos) sets out from Constantinople at the head of a expeditionary army. He marches to Cillicia; and while the main army follows the coast road eastwards – Manuel hurries ahead with a force of only 500 cavalry. He manages to surprise King Thoros II (the Great), who has participated in the attack on Cyprus (see 1156). Thoros flees into the mountains and Cilicia is occupied by the Byzantines.

Pas-de-Calais ( , `` strait of Calais '' ; ; also ) is a department in northern France named after the port on the northern edge of the city. It has a population of 2,068,000 people, and is the administrative centre of the Dordogne region, and the only one of France's 14 departments to have been created by the First Republic.The administrative division is located close to the border to the United Kingdom, at the town of Pas-de-Calais-Picardie, along the French and English borders.The French administrative boundary in the department is the French/English Border. In theory, the entire department is included in the territory of the French state.

A drought is an event of prolonged shortages in the water supply, whether atmospheric (below-average precipitation), surface water or ground water. A drought can last for months or years, or may be declared after as few as 15 days. It can have a substantial impact on the ecosystem and agriculture of the affected region and harm to the local economy. Annual dry seasons in the tropics significantly increase the chances of a drought developing and subsequent bush fires. Periods of heat can significantly worsen drought conditions by hastening evaporation of water vapour.Drought is a recurring feature of the climate in most parts of the world.

Sparta (Doric Greek: Σπάρτα, Spártā; Attic Greek: Σπάρτη, Spártē) was a prominent city-state in Laconia, in ancient Greece. In antiquity, the city-state was known as Lacedaemon , while the name Sparta referred to its main settlement on the banks of the Eurotas River in Laconia, in south-eastern Peloponnese. Around 650 BC, it rose to become the dominant military land-power in ancient Greece.Given its military pre-eminence, Sparta was recognized as the leading force of the unified Greek military during the Greco-Persian Wars, in rivalry with the rising naval power of Athens.

D'Urville Island , Te Reo Māori name ( 'red heavens look to the south ' ) , is an island in the Bay of Plenty, and is the largest island of the North Island. The island is part of the Te Araroa group.HistoryThe earliest inhabitants are thought by some to date from the Mi'poko Age , when it was inhabited. The Dao is a character in the Daoism, the philosophy and religious systems of the Daoists. The Daoist concept of the Dao (sometimes written as dao) is central to the system of philosophy known as Daoism.

Concurrent Versions System ( CVS , also known as the Concurrent Versioning System ) is a revision control system originally designed for file version control systems (FVCS) and in particular for Unix–like operating systems. It allows developers to keep track of multiple branches of code at the same time by tracking changes made to the same source code file, which are added and removed simultaneously from all branches. It uses a merge-based model that allows the same file to be in multiple revisions by merging multiple files at once.This is the canonical implementation of the CVS specification, but it is not the only implementation that uses a merge based model.

Wool is the textile fibre obtained from sheep and other animals , including cashmere and mohair from goats , qiviut from alpaca . It is a strong, durable, and soft natural fibre that is widely used for various industrial and household purposes. The best quality wool is available from sheep that have been bred for at least 10 years in the UK and Ireland, or from a farm in Ireland. John Paul II (, ; 28 February 1894 – 20 February 2001) was a Roman Catholic cardinal and the Pope of the Roman Catholic Church from 1979 to his death in 2001.

A wide area network ( WAN ) is a telecommunications network that extends over a large geographic area . Wide area networks, in general, use multiple wireless radio access networks (RAS) to link multiple points across a larger area. Wide area networks are often referred to as Wide-Area Network Service ( WAN ) in some countries, which is the preferred term in the US.In general, WAN traffic is often referred to as "broadband", but it can also be referred to as "data transport", "data transfer", or "broadband", depending on the country.

Powaqqatsi ( or Powaqqatsi : Life in Transformation ) is a 1988 American non-narrative film directed by Godfrey Reggio and starring Michael Caine, Cate Blanchett and John Hurt. Set in Soviet-era Russia, the film was released in the United States two years later in 1989, when it was considered to be a classic of the genre.Set in the years immediately following the October Revolution, Powaqqatsi is a period drama with a strong satirical bent. Caine stars as Leonid (or Leon), a young Russian soldier who returns home after his service in World War II. His wife and child have died.

Giuseppe Saverio Raffaele Mercadante ( baptised 17 September 179517 December 1870 ) was an Italian composer , particularly of operas and choral music. He is regarded by many composers as a pioneer.BiographyEarly yearsHe was born into a poor family of Italian immigrants, but was educated at the local university in Milan, studying mathematics and engineering. He took the entrance examination for the Conservatoire of Bologna, but did not get into Conservatoire because of poor marks.He then spent a year as a student at the Academy of Athens, in Athens, Greece, then went to Milan where he studied piano with the violinist Luigi Perugini.

Civil liberties are guarantees and freedoms that governments commit not to abridge , either by constitution , legislation , or by their actions, unless they are clearly justified in a democratic process . The term is sometimes used more specifically to refer to any rights and liberties not specifically protected by legislation such as religious freedom, political freedom, or the right to free speech, and is sometimes used to refer to human rights in general.The term was first used by Thomas Paine in 1776. Electoral districts are areas where a voter's party vote decides the number of seats that will be held for that party in an election.

Tajiks (, Tājīk, Tājek; ) are a Persian-speaking Iranian ethnic group native to Central Asia, living primarily in Afghanistan, Tajikistan, and Uzbekistan. Tajiks are the largest ethnicity in Tajikistan, and the second-largest in Afghanistan and Uzbekistan. They speak varieties of Persian, a Western Iranian language. In Tajikistan, since the 1939 Soviet census, its small Pamiri and Yaghnobi ethnic groups are included as Tajiks. In China, the term is used to refer to its Pamiri ethnic groups, the Tajiks of Xinjiang, who speak the Eastern Iranian Pamiri languages.

Willow Rosenberg is a fictional character created for the fantasy television series Buffy the Vampire Slayer ( 1997–2003 ) . In the series, she serves as the Slayer's caretaker, mentor, and ex-girlfriend. A lesbian, she is one of Buffy's friends and is a member of the Watchers Council and the Trio of the Damned. She and the Scoobies are sometimes depicted as having a close, romantic relationship, but she is not shown to hold romantic feelings for Buffy.The character was played in the film by Tara Strong, who also voiced the character in all the Buffy the Vampire Slayer video games and media since its release.

Metaphone is a phonetic algorithm , published by Lawrence Philips in 1990 , for indexing words by their English pronunciation. The system consists of three distinct components: Phonology , which defines the properties of each letter in the language, and Phonotactic Phonics , which uses the system to recognize individual sounds. Each letter of the English alphabet is described by a separate property, and many words have two or more properties.PhonologyThe phoneme is a sound that makes up a phoneme. For English, phonemes consist of the sounds /l/, /ʃ/, and /r/. A word is considered complete if all phonemes of the word occur as a single unit.

The San Juan Islands are an archipelago in the Pacific Northwest of the United States between the U.S. state of Washington and British Columbia. They are named after Juan de Fuca Strait and are located off the northwest coast of Washington. The islands span a total of 9,843 square kilometers and are the largest archipelago by area in the U.S. state of Washington.The islands are home to many native and non-native species of birds, fish, and reptiles. These islands have a population of about 4,800 people living mostly on the North, Central, and South Islands, and another 11,000 living on the East and Southwest islands.

Kingston is the capital and largest city of Jamaica , located on the southeastern coast of the island . It is a major commercial hub with over 1,300,000 residents. Kingston's economic development is based on tourism and its status as a major international finance centre.The city of Kingston was officially named Kingston during the late 17th century.In the early 17th century, the city's inhabitants were called Jamaicans; the term "Kingstonians" was used until the early 20th century.Early historyThe early history of Kingston began during the English and Spanish colonial rule of the island from the mid-16th century until the 18th century.

An adverb is a word or an expression that modifies a verb, adjective, another adverb, determiner, clause, preposition, or sentence. Adverbs typically express manner, place, time, frequency, degree, level of certainty, etc., answering questions such as how?, in what way?, when?, where?, and to what extent?. This is called the adverbial function, and may be performed by single words (adverbs) or by multi-word adverbial phrases and adverbial clauses.Adverbs are traditionally regarded as one of the parts of speech.

On May 25 , 1865 , in Mobile , Alabama , in the Southern United States , an ordnance depot of the United States Army was set up at Camp Chase, near Mobile, Alabama, with the help of the United States War Department. It began to receive and store ammunition as soon as it was completed in April 1862, and, by July of the same year, it was running a full ammunition distribution system.By November 1869, the United States was able to supply ammunition to every Confederate state as well as Mexico, the Philippines and Hawaii.

Theodoret of Cyrus or Cyrrhus ( ; AD 393 – 458/466 ) was an influential theologian of the School of Alexandria. A native of Phocaea, he studied in Rome and Alexandria and was elected Bishop of Alexandria. His work, On the Incarnation and the Holy Spirit, contains the most influential of all Christian dogmas.His writings include some of the earliest references to the Trinity; he describes the union of the Holy Spirit with the Son of God as "one of the most ancient forms of monotheism". The Earth is a satellite orbiting the sun, known by the astronomical symbol η (Σ).

The Burrows–Wheeler transform (BWT, also called block-sorting compression) rearranges a character string into runs of similar characters. This is useful for compression, since it tends to be easy to compress a string that has runs of repeated characters by techniques such as move-to-front transform and run-length encoding. More importantly, the transformation is reversible, without needing to store any additional data except the position of the first original character. The BWT is thus a "free" method of improving the efficiency of text compression algorithms, costing only some extra computation.

Brighella ( in Bergamasque dialect : Brighèla ) is a comic , masked character from the Italian theatre style Commedia Dell'Arte . The character was first used in the 1894 Italian stage revival, and he was the protagonist of many of the plays written about him. He also appeared in two films, the first in 1927 and the second in 1935.BiographyThe character is based on a real-life playwright, Giuseppe Ramelli (1778–1856). Bridgewater  is a town located in Sussex, England. It is the seat of Devon County and a major port for shipping between the North Sea and the Baltic Sea.

Éraic ( or eric ) was the Irish equivalent of the Welsh galanas and the Anglo-Saxon and Scandinavian weregild , meaning a gift of wealth. It also can be translated as "wealth, honor, fame", "honorific title", or "a title of respect". A galane is a unit of wealth or honor in Irish society. Easter Sunday is the Catholic feast day of the Christian Resurrection, as well as the celebration of the Last Supper. The date is derived from the date on which Easter was first celebrated, according to Jewish tradition, which is December 25.

Mecklenburg-Vorpommern (MV; , ), also known by its anglicized name Mecklenburg–Western Pomerania, is a state in the north-east of Germany. Of the country's sixteen states, Mecklenburg-Vorpommern ranks 14th in population, 6th in area, and 16th in population density. Schwerin is the state capital and Rostock is the largest city. Other major cities include Neubrandenburg, Stralsund, Greifswald, Wismar and Güstrow.The state was established in 1945 after World War II through the merger of the historic regions of Mecklenburg and the Prussian Western Pomerania by the Soviet military administration in Allied-occupied Germany.

Paul Lansky (born June 18, 1944, in New York) is an American composer.BiographyPaul Lansky (born 1944) is an American composer. He was educated at Manhattan's High School of Music and Art, Queens College and Princeton University, studying with George Perle and Milton Babbitt, among others. He received his Ph.D. in music from Princeton in 1973. His doctoral dissertation consisted of an essay titled "Affine music" and a composition of string quartet. Originally intending to pursue a career in performance, during 1965–66 he played the French horn with the Dorian Wind Quintet.

Soil is a mixture of organic matter, minerals, gases, liquids, and organisms that together support life. Earth's body of soil, called the pedosphere, has four important functions: as a medium for plant growth as a means of water storage, supply and purification as a modifier of Earth's atmosphere as a habitat for organismsAll of these functions, in their turn, modify the soil and its properties.Soil is also commonly referred to as earth or dirt; some scientific definitions distinguish dirt from soil by restricting the former term specifically to displaced soil.

The Soma cube is a solid dissection puzzle invented by Danish polymath Piet Hein in 1933 during a lecture on Euclidean geometry by Adolf Loewenstein. It was published in 1935.It is not an ordinary puzzle as it has three sides, not two, and it includes a triangular piece that is rotated 90 degrees in the middle of the piece. The solution consists of removing a single corner and rotating it clockwise 180 degrees to form a square and placing the pieces of the cube back into place. The solution is to remove the corner and then rotate the cube 90 degrees in both directions.

Parasports are sports played by people with a disability, including physical and intellectual disabilities. Some parasports are forms of adapted physical activities from existing able-bodied sports, while others have been specifically created for persons with a disability and do not have an able-bodied equivalent. Disability exists in four categories: physical, mental, permanent and temporary. At a competitive level, disability sport classifications are applied to allow people of varying abilities to face similar opposition.EtymologyThe term "parasports" arose as a portmanteau of the words paraplegic and sports. Though the sport has since included athletes of disabilities other than paraplegia, the term persists as a catch-all.

SPARC (Scalable Processor Architecture) is a reduced instruction set computing (RISC) instruction set architecture originally developed by Sun Microsystems. Its design was strongly influenced by the experimental Berkeley RISC system developed in the early 1980s. First developed in 1986 and released in 1987, SPARC was one of the most successful early commercial RISC systems, and its success led to the introduction of similar RISC designs from a number of vendors through the 1980s and 90s.The first implementation of the original 32-bit architecture (SPARC V7) was used in Sun's Sun-4 workstation and server systems, replacing their earlier Sun-3 systems based on the Motorola 68000 series of processors.

A think tank, or policy institute, is a research institute that performs research and advocacy concerning topics such as social policy, political strategy, economics, military, technology, and culture. Most think tanks are non-governmental organizations, but some are semi-autonomous agencies within government or are associated with particular political parties, businesses or the military. Think-tank funding often includes a combination of donations from wealthy individuals and personal contributions, with many also accepting government grants.Think tanks publish articles, studies or even draft legislation on particular matters of policy or society.

Malayalam (; , ) is a Dravidian language spoken in the Indian state of Kerala and the union territories of Lakshadweep and Puducherry (Mahé district) by the Malayali people. It is one of 22 scheduled languages of India and is spoken by 2.88% of Indians. Malayalam has official language status in Kerala, Lakshadweep and Puducherry (Mahé), and is spoken by 34 million people worldwide. Malayalam is also spoken by linguistic minorities in the neighbouring states; with significant number of speakers in the Kodagu and Dakshina Kannada districts of Karnataka, and Nilgiris and Kanyakumari, districts of Tamil Nadu.

This is a list of monarchs who ruled over East Francia , and the Kingdom of Germany ( Regnum Teutonicum ), from 1 February 1327 to 9 May 1433. These kings were crowned by the King of Poland, or by his representative, the Bishop of Płock. This list has been included in the official royal lists of most kingdoms of the period, but some have excluded the names of the most important German kings, such as Frederick I, Elector of Saxony and King of Poland. In mathematics, a fraction is a relation of finite extent between numbers.Fractions are defined in a number of different ways.

The M18A1 Claymore is a directional anti-personnel mine developed for the United States Armed Forces. Its inventor, Norman MacLeod, named the mine after a large medieval Scottish sword. Unlike a conventional land mine, the Claymore is command-detonated and directional, meaning it is fired by remote-control and shoots a pattern of metal balls into the kill zone like a shotgun. The Claymore can also be victim-activated by booby-trapping it with a tripwire firing system for use in area denial operations.The Claymore fires steel balls out to about  within a 60° arc in front of the device.

The subset sum problem ( SSP ) is a decision problem in computer science . In its most general formulation, the problem asks which element of a finite subset of a data set (the input subset) is contained in the data set. In the case of finite subset of a subset of some finite subset, this problem is also known as the SSP or subgoal problem, because the goal is to determine a finite subset of the input. The Standard Model is an established theory of subatomic particles including protons, neutrons, neutrinos, and kaons.

KFC ( also known as Kentucky Fried Chicken ) is an American fast food restaurant chain headquartered in Louisville , Kentucky. It began in the 1950s as a fried chicken stand in a strip mall in Louisville, and eventually expanded into a chain of restaurants throughout the South, Midwest, and West Coast.The company was founded by Jim 'Buck' Stewart in 1946, after the death of his mother. The brand was originally called "Kentucky Fried Chicken." The company was acquired by Yum! Brands Incorporated on June 29, 2015 for $8.3 billion, making it the seventh-largest fast food company in the world.

Emissions trading is a market-based approach to controlling pollution by providing economic incentives for reducing the emissions of pollutants . This approach can reduce emissions by reducing the costs of producing a pollutant and thus, indirectly, the economic cost of emitting it. This is in contrast to the use of a policy instrument such as carbon taxes or emission quotas to directly control emissions of pollutants. The Internet Engineering Task Force is the central coordinating body of the IETF. In addition, the IETF is the primary international organisation responsible for the technical development of Internet protocols.

Liberation theology is a Christian theological approach emphasizing the liberation of the oppressed . In certain contexts , it engages with other approaches , such as the post-Christian eschatology of post-apostolic dispensationalism (see eschatology).Liberation theology has a history of wide use in several countries within the Christian world, and in recent years it has begun to find a foothold in many Western countries. A ley is a naturally occurring electromagnetic or electromagnetic energy source, a source of magnetic energy in the electromagnetic spectrum. A single ley may radiate energy in the electromagnetic spectrum.

A gas nuclear reactor ( or gas fueled reactor or vapor core reactor ) is a proposed kind of nuclear reactor powered by solid or gaseous fission products, such as neutrons or atoms of deuterium, which are vaporized at a low temperature in a containment vessel containing molten salt. The fuel is usually uranium dioxide or uranium hexafluoride (or both), which acts as the "fuel" in the reactor, and is fissioned and released as fission products. The fuel also provides heat to the reactor to prevent it from overheating.In the gas phase, the fission products act as radiation and are captured by materials in the containment vessel.

Peperomia ( radiator plant ) is one of the two large genera of the family Piperaceae . Most of them are epiphytic flowering plants, growing on woody stems or leaves. Epiphytes are classified as either conifers or coniferous plants depending on their habit. The genus is the world's largest genus of flowering plants, with about 7,100 described species, of which over half have been described since the early 1990s. The name "perpetua" derives from the Latin meaning "water-cooled"; the Latin name for another genus, Piper, means "to drink" or "to be drunk".

Dekker 's algorithm is the first known correct solution to the mutual exclusion problem in concurrent programming . The solution is known as the "Dekker–Niven–Venn algorithm", after its inventors, the American computer scientists Donald E. Niven and Robert F. Howard. Deliberate practice (also known as deliberate practice) is the process of consciously practicing a skill in a disciplined fashion over a long period of time. It is often described as a "mental exercise", and it is often seen as a form of self-directed learning. The concept has its origins in Western psychology and philosophy, and was first developed in the study of Zen Buddhism.

Bi-curious is a term for a person, usually someone who is a heterosexual, who is curious or open about engaging in sexual activity with a person whose sex differs from that of their usual sexual partners. The term is sometimes used to describe a broad continuum of sexual orientation between heterosexuality and bisexuality. Such continuums include mostly-heterosexual or mostly-homosexual, but these can be self-identified without identifying as bisexual. The terms heteroflexible and homoflexible are mainly applied to bi-curious people, though some authors distinguish heteroflexibility and homoflexibility as lacking the "wish to experiment with sexuality" implied by the bi-curious label.

Hex is a two player abstract strategy board game in which players attempt to connect opposite sides of a hexagonal board. Hex was invented by mathematician and poet Piet Hein in 1942 and independently by John Nash in 1948.It is traditionally played on an 11×11 rhombus board, although 13×13 and 19×19 boards are also popular. Each player is assigned a pair of opposite sides of the board which they must try to connect by taking turns placing a stone of their color onto any empty space. Once placed, the stones are unable to be moved or removed.

The Permanent Court of Arbitration ( PCA ) is a non-UN intergovernmental organization located in The Hague , Netherlands . As a permanent tribunal, it acts in dispute resolution matters related to international maritime law (IML).History The PCA's origin dates back to 1951, when the European Community (EC) adopted the Hague Conventions. The PCA came about in response to the need for a legally enforceable forum to adjudicate maritime disputes in the wake of the Spanish-American War and the resulting arbitration proceedings conducted by the United Nations (UN).

Commander Keen is a series of side-scrolling platform video games developed primarily by id Software. The series consists of six main episodes, a "lost" episode, and a final game; all but the final game were originally released for MS-DOS in 1990 and 1991, while the 2001 Commander Keen was released for the Game Boy Color. The series follows the eponymous Commander Keen, the secret identity of the eight-year-old genius Billy Blaze, as he defends the Earth and the galaxy from alien threats with his homemade spaceship, rayguns, and pogo stick.

East Malaysia , also known as Sabah, Sarawak and Labuan  or Malaysian Borneo, is the part of Malaysia on and near the island of Borneo, the world's third largest island. It consists of the Malaysian states of Sabah and Sarawak, as well as the Federal Territory of Labuan. Labuan is an island in a small archipelago near the coast of Sabah. East Malaysia lies to the east of Peninsular Malaysia (also known as West Malaysia), the part of the country on the Malay Peninsula. The two are separated by the South China Sea.East Malaysia is less populated and has less developed settlements than West Malaysia.

Linus Carl Pauling ( ; February 28 , 1901 – August 19 , 1994 ) was an American chemist , microbiologist, and geneticist who pioneered the discovery of genetic engineering.He won the 1963 Nobel Prize in Chemistry for his role in creating the first artificial recombinant DNA technology.Pauling was born into a Swedish family and attended the University of Chicago as a student in the 1920s. In 1934 he published his first research article on the structure and structure–activity relationship of adenine nucleobases. In 1937 he received his Ph.D. at Harvard, and began working in genetics, biochemistry, and immunology.

Ravenna ( , , also ; ) is the capital city of the Province of Ravenna , in the Emilia-Romagna region of Lombardy, Italy, and part of the region of Venetia.The town has a large number of important cultural attractions, including the Palatine Palace of the Medici kings, the Museum of Archaeological Art, and the University of Ravenna, which is considered an international leader in the fields of medicine, psychology, law, and philosophy, and is a prominent center of scientific research. It is also renowned for its architectural heritage.HistoryThe history of Ravenna can be divided into four periods, each ending with the Renaissance.

Today 's New International Version ( TNIV ) is an English translation of the Bible which was developed by the Evangelical Free Bible Society and the Society for Biblical Literature from the first draft of the Bible in 1611. The Bible was then revised and re-edited at least seven times and is now known as the King James Version or the King James Bible.The King James Version is the standard English translation of the Old Testament. This translation is also used as the standard English translation of the Old Testament and is used to teach and interpret Biblical Scripture in churches worldwide.

Cotton is a soft , fluffy staple fiber that grows in a boll , or protective case , around the seed, and which may be spun into thread or used for clothing, textiles and various industrial purposes. It is the world's dominant cash crop.Cotton is classified by the World Health Organization (WHO) under the family Hevea , alongside rice, cassava and sorghum.Cotton can be grown in areas up to 5.7 million ha (19.5 million acres), making it one of the most important crops worldwide. Crop production in India alone accounts for about 20% of the total world production.

Halebidu ( IAST : Haḷēbīḍ , literally `` old capital , city , encampment '' or `` ruined city '') is the second largest city of Ethiopia, situated in Upper Tigray Region. It is also known by the regional name Tigray  in the language of Tigrayans.In the late 19th century the city was the commercial center of Upper Tigray and is considered the seat of government of Upper Tigray.The ancient city of Adwa was located on the south bank of the Nile at the confluence of the Tigray and Aba Rivers, which formed the head of the Tigrayan delta, and was the administrative and religious center of Ethiopia for over three millennia.

Alfa Romeo Automobiles S.p.A.  is an Italian luxury car manufacturer and a subsidiary of Stellantis. The company was founded on 24 June 1910, in Milan, Italy. "Alfa" is an acronym of its founding name, "Anonima Lombarda Fabbrica Automobili." "Anonima" means "anonymous", which was a legal form of company at the time, as it was founded by anonymous investors. In the initial set-up phase, in order to have a building to produce cars, the company bought the Portello factory building of Darracq in Milan, which was closing up and selling all its assets.

Heliox is a breathing gas mixture of helium ( He ) and oxygen ( O2 ) .Heliox is a medical gas mixture used in the emergency treatment of a variety of non-urgent medical emergencies as a gas exchange medium for breathing while in a non-ventilated chamber or tube. The hydrogen atom has the symbol H and the symbol H. Helium is a heavy, colorless gas consisting largely of the heavier element He. The atomic radius of hydrogen is 13.7 Å. Its density is about 1 gram per cubic centimeter.Helium is a colorless, odourless, tasteless, non-combustible, and inert gas, but a liquid at normal temperatures and pressure.

The AGM-114 Hellfire (AGM stands for air-to-ground missile) is an air-to-surface missile (ASM) first developed for anti-armor use, but later models were developed for precision drone strikes against other target types, and have been used in a number of actions aimed to "destroy high-value targets." It was originally developed under the name Heliborne laser, fire-and-forget missile, which led to the colloquial name "Hellfire" ultimately becoming the missile's formal name. It has multi-mission, multi-target precision-strike ability, and can be launched from multiple air, sea, and ground platforms, including the Predator drone.

An anti-tank guided missile (ATGM), anti-tank missile, anti-tank guided weapon (ATGW) or anti-armor guided weapon is  a guided missile primarily designed to hit and destroy heavily armored military vehicles. ATGMs range in size from shoulder-launched weapons, which can be transported by a single soldier, to larger tripod-mounted weapons, which require a squad or team to transport and fire, to vehicle and aircraft mounted missile systems.Earlier man-portable anti-tank weapons like anti-tank rifles and magnetic anti-tank mines, generally had very short range, sometimes on the order of metres or tens of metres.

Oak Ridge National Laboratory (ORNL) is a U.S. multiprogram science and technology national laboratory sponsored by the U.S. Department of Energy (DOE) and administered, managed, and operated by UT–Battelle as a federally funded research and development center (FFRDC) under a contract with the DOE, located in Oak Ridge, Tennessee.Established in 1943, ORNL is the largest science and energy national laboratory in the Department of Energy system (by size) and third largest by annual budget. It is located in the Roane County section of Oak Ridge, Tennessee.

Pope Leo V was the bishop of Rome and nominal ruler of the Papal States from July 903 to his death in October 974, and the last pope of the Latin Church, the successor of the Holy Roman Catholic Church. He is known for restoring the Church's authority and increasing the number of its bishops and the authority of the papal See. Leo V is also considered the father of European history and modern European civilization. In mathematics, the LaTeX markup language is a text formatting language for writing mathematics. LaTeX differs from other markup languages in that it allows for much greater control and customization than that of HTML.

Year 878 (DCCCLXXVIII) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Britain  January 6 – King Alfred the Great is surprised by a Viking attack at Chippenham. He is forced to flee, with his retinue, into the Somerset Levels for safety. From his headquarters at Athelney, Alfred wages a guerrilla war against the Vikings. May – Battle of Edington: Supported by all the levies of Somerset, Wiltshire and Hampshire, Alfred the Great decisively defeats the main body of Danish Vikings, led by King Guthrum, at present-day Edington (near Bratton Castle).

Flavius Odoacer ( ; – 493 AD ) , also spelled Odovacer or Odovacar , was a soldier and statesman. He was the first to unite the Gothic and Roman armies and was the first to lead an expedition through the Alps. Olympia  ( ; ; ; , , ) was a Greek city-state located in Attica. Olympia  was the seat of the Athenian government. It lies on the northern part of Attica, in the Peloponnese and is one of the most important cities on the Attic Peninsula, the site of the Trojan War.

Isis ( ; Ēse ; ; Meroitic : Wos [ a ] or Wusa ) was a major goddess in the Canaanite pantheon who was the daughter of El and the goddess Athame, and the daughter of El and Asherah, the wife and sister of Adam. According to the Book of Enoch, Isis was the wife of Adam. Ionizing radiation is an electromagnetic radiation that consists of energetic particles (electrons and proton) with positive charge. Ionizing radiation is present in all matter and may be composed of a mixture of atoms, molecules, solid particles, gas, or liquid.

Radiohead are an English rock band formed in Abingdon , Oxfordshire , in 1985 . The band consists of Thom Yorke (lead vocalist, guitars and keyboards), Jonny Greenwood (bass guitar, electric piano, keyboards), Colin Greenwood (drums), Phil Selway (keyboards), and Rick Wakeman (drums). The name is an Anglicization of their middle name Yorke. They formed in Abingdon, and relocated to Oxford in 1989, where the group began touring.In 1992, a new album, Ok Computer, was released. Isle of Man  is a British overseas territory.

The Avignon Papacy was the period from 1309 to 1376 during which seven successive popes resided in Avignon ( then called Avignon-Ville) and ruled in the city until their abdication and the establishment of a papacy under the leadership of Clement IV (1314–1376). During the lifetime of St. John VII the most important popes under the papacy were Innocent III (1328–1354) and Gregory XII (1356–1404). After the deaths of the last two popes (Clement VI and Pius VII), the French king Louis VII (1377–1399) became the last reigning pope.

The Battle of Lechfeld was a series of military engagements over the course of three days from 10–12 August 955 in which the Kingdom of Germany led by king Otto I the Great annihilated the Hungarian army led by harka Bulcsú and the chieftains Lél and Súr. With this German victory further invasions by the Magyars into Latin Europe were ended.The Hungarians invaded the Duchy of Bavaria in late June or early July 955 with 8,000–10,000 horse archers, infantry, and siege engines, intending to draw the main German army under Otto I into battle in the open field and destroy it.

Pas-de-Calais (, "strait of Calais"; ; also ) is a department in northern France named after the French designation of the Strait of Dover, which it borders. It has the most communes of all the departments of France, 890, and is the 8th most populous. The Calais Passage connects to the Port of Calais on the English Channel. Pas-de-Calais borders the departments of Nord and Somme and is connected to the English county of Kent via the Channel Tunnel.HistoryInhabited since prehistoric times, the Pas-de-Calais region was populated in turn by the Celtic Belgae, the Romans, the Germanic Franks and the Alemanni.

A radionuclide (radioactive nuclide, radioisotope or radioactive isotope) is a nuclide that has excess nuclear energy, making it unstable. This excess energy can be used in one of three ways: emitted from the nucleus as gamma radiation; transferred to one of its electrons to release it as a conversion electron; or used to create and emit a new particle (alpha particle or beta particle) from the nucleus. During those processes, the radionuclide is said to undergo radioactive decay. These emissions are considered ionizing radiation because they are powerful enough to liberate an electron from another atom.

Warren Mitchell ( born Warren Misell ; 14 January 1926 – 14 November 2015 ) was a British actor . He is best known for his performance as Captain James T. Kirk in the original Star Trek series and films. Mitchell's career spanned over five decades, as his career began in the early 1950s and continued on through to his retirement from the industry. His first major feature film role was in 1952's The Big Sleep, but he appeared in more films on the silver screen during the same period than he did in all his previous roles.

Auger electron spectroscopy (AES; pronounced  in French) is a common analytical technique used specifically in the study of surfaces and, more generally, in the area of materials science. It is a form of electron spectroscopy that relies on the Auger effect, based on the analysis of energetic electrons emitted from an excited atom after a series of internal relaxation events. The Auger effect was discovered independently by both Lise Meitner and Pierre Auger in the 1920s. Though the discovery was made by Meitner and initially reported in the journal Zeitschrift für Physik in 1922, Auger is credited with the discovery in most of the scientific community.

Harriet Tubman ( born Araminta Ross , March 10 , 1913 ) was an American abolitionist and political activist . She was born and raised in Maryland, and served as a slave in Maryland's Eastern Shore plantation.She was captured by slave raiders and enslaved in Maryland for 18 months before her escape by boarding a ship and sailing to free America. Kotlin, short for Koda Kota , is a statically typed programming language developed by Google and open source as part of Android. Kotlin has been released as open source under the Apache License.HistoryKotlin originated in Google's open source Android development effort and was open sourced by Google in June 2016.

Theories of political behavior, as an aspect of political science, attempt to quantify and explain the influences that define a person's political views, ideology, and levels of political participation. Political behavior is the subset of human behavior that involves politics and power. Theorists who have had an influence on this field include Karl Deutsch and Theodor Adorno.Long-term influences on political orientationInteraction with the political views of parental figures is often thought of as the primary long-term influence on political orientation and willingness to take part in the political system.Teachers and other educational authority figures are also often thought to have a significant impact on political orientation.

A mass driver or electromagnetic catapult is a proposed method of non-rocket spacelaunch which would use a linear motor to propel a projectile into orbit. The proposed vehicle would consist of a vehicle with a propellant tank and a booster rocket whose purpose is to transfer mass and energy from the booster rocket to the propellant tanks of the vehicle to be launched. The propellant tanks are designed to hold a propellant and a propellant mixture of a particular rocket propellant (typically a solid fuel, e.g. Lox-Ketoxyhydrogen-Methylbutyl). In logic and logic theory, a non-empty sets  are sets that lack any element not present in the set.

Juan Moreno y Herrera–Jiménez ( born 30 July 1948 ) , known as Jean Reno , is a French actor and comedian. He became a national treasure at a relatively young age and became a celebrity on television and in cinema. Moreno has appeared in a large variety of films, many of them in French, and has starred in many animated films in which he is the voice and protagonist.He began his acting career with the French drama series Cinq à Sept. He went on to make notable appearances in several films and later in television.

Pope Leo VI (880 – 12 February 929) was the bishop of Rome and nominal ruler of the Papal States for just over seven months, from June 928 to his death. His pontificate occurred during the period known as the Saeculum obscurum.Family and early careerLeo VI was born into a Roman family, and his father was Christophorus, who had been primicerius under Pope John VIII around the year 876. Tradition has it that he was a member of the Sanguini family. Before his pontificate, Leo served as the cardinal-priest of Santa Susanna.PontificateLeo was elected pope around June 928, during a period of anarchy.

R.U.R . is a 1920 science-fiction play by the Czech writer Karel Čapek . `` R.U.R . '' stands for ``Red Universe'' in Russian. The play was based on the first three books in Čapký's series, The Rites of Science. The play was a popular cultural phenomenon during the 1930s; the play inspired many imitators and influenced science fiction literature in many countries of Europe.The first novel was first published in Czech language in 1932, and the play in English in 1934. Čapek adapted and enlarged the novel into an epic story.

Tazio Giorgio Nuvolari ( ; 16 November 1892 – 11 August 1953 ) was an Italian racing driver . He won three consecutive Italian Formula 1 championships. He was also the only three-time constructors' champion of World Drivers' Championship. He was the only driver to win back-to-back championships with the same team and manufacturer. His victories included five consecutive races in Italy, three at Monza (1954–57), and one at Spa (1957).In 1958 he was selected by Ferrari to drive for the Grand Prix of Rome for a second time, and won.

A brain tumor occurs when abnormal cells form within the brain . There are two main types of tumors : benign and malignant .Bilateral benign tumors are tumors that cause no symptoms and have no symptoms. A book is defined as any printed material that can be held in one hand and used with the other hand to read the written page, often called a reading or listening book. A number of other types of printed works, such as books, magazines, newspapers, pamphlets, newspapers in magazines, and pamphlets on magazines, may be written and intended for oral delivery.

A gold standard is a monetary system in which the standard economic unit of account is based on a fixed quantity of gold. The gold standard was the basis for the international monetary system from the 1870s to the early 1920s, and from the late 1920s to 1932 as well as from 1944 until 1971 when the United States unilaterally terminated convertibility of the US dollar to gold foreign central banks, effectively ending the Bretton Woods system. Many states still hold substantial gold reserves.Historically, the silver standard and bimetallism have been more common than the gold standard.

William Tyndale ( ; sometimes spelled Tynsdale , Tindall , Tindill , Tyndall ; – ) was an English biblical scholar, author, and reformer of the Reformation movement in the mid-to-late 12th century. Tyndale's work has been called "the most widely read, influential, and influential book of Christian doctrine from the Middle Ages and early Reformation." In the mid-15th century, he was considered the pre-eminent theologian of his day, although he was eclipsed by the later Martin Luther and John Calvin in the minds of many Protestant reformers. This article first appeared on Quora.

Year 984 (CMLXXXIV) was a leap year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  Spring – German boy-king Otto III (4-years old) is seized by the deposed Henry II (the Wrangler), duke of Bavaria, who has recovered his duchy and claims the regency as a member of the Ottonian Dynasty. But Henry is forced to hand over Otto to his mother, empress consort Theophanu. King Ramiro III loses his throne to Bermudo II (the rival king of Galicia), who also becomes ruler of the entire Kingdom of León (modern-day Spain).

The lungs are the primary organs of the respiratory system in humans and most animals including a few fish, and some snails. In mammals and most other vertebrates, two lungs are located near the backbone on either side of the heart. Their function in the respiratory system is to extract oxygen from the air and transfer it into the bloodstream, and to release carbon dioxide from the bloodstream into the atmosphere, in a process of gas exchange. Respiration is driven by different muscular systems in different species. Mammals, reptiles and birds use their different muscles to support and foster breathing.

The AGM-114 Hellfire ( AGM stands for air-to-ground missile ) is an air-to-surface missile ( ASM ) first developed for use against ground targets during World War II. Originally developed for use against enemy tanks, the Hellfire was designed as a low-altitude, low-speed ground attack weapon. Hellfires were often used against both ground and naval targets during the war. The first operational Hellfire missiles were issued to Marine Corps ground attack aircraft during the Vietnam War in 1968. It was used to attack ground targets by night in Vietnam and was used in other theatres during the Vietnam War for ground support missions, as well as in direct ground support operations.

Risk is a strategy board game of diplomacy, conflict and conquest for two to six players. The standard version is played on a board depicting a political map of the world, divided into forty-two territories, which are grouped into six continents. Turns rotate among players who control armies of playing pieces with which they attempt to capture territories from other players, with results determined by dice rolls. Players may form and dissolve alliances during the course of the game. The goal of the game is to occupy every territory on the board and, in doing so, eliminate the other players.

Year 1170 ( MCLXX ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) in Britain, Ireland, the British Isles, most of Northern Africa, Scandinavia, and parts of Europe, and beginning on Sunday in North America. It was used as the official year of the Roman Catholic Church, with the Gregorian calendar, and became officially adopted in the Catholic Church's Gregorian reform in 1652.Common years are not considered leap years, so the year 1 BC would still be an actual year, with no leap year year, making this year 1 BC.

Brave New World is a dystopian social science fiction novel by English author Aldous Huxley, written in 1931 and published in 1932. Largely set in a futuristic World State, whose citizens are environmentally engineered into an intelligence-based social hierarchy, the novel anticipates huge scientific advancements in reproductive technology, sleep-learning, psychological manipulation and classical conditioning that are combined to make a dystopian society which is challenged by only a single individual: the story's protagonist. Huxley followed this book with a reassessment in essay form, Brave New World Revisited (1958), and with his final novel, Island (1962), the utopian counterpart.

Coxsackie A virus (CAV) is a cytolytic Coxsackievirus of the Picornaviridae family, an enterovirus (a group containing the polioviruses, coxsackieviruses, and echoviruses).Viral structure and genome Coxsackie A virus is a subgroup of enterovirus A, which are small, non-enveloped, positive-sense, single-stranded RNA viruses. Its protective, icosahedral capsid has an external portion that contains sixty copies of viral proteins (VP1,-2,-3) and an internal portion surrounding the RNA genome containing sixty copies of VP4 viral proteins. This capsid mediates cell entry and elicits the humoral immune responses.

Belarusians , also known formerly as Byelorussians ( from the Byelorussian SSR ) , Belarussians or Belorusians , are an ethnic group of Russia, which consists of Belarusian-speaking peoples. Belarusians are the largest ethnic group of Russia, making up more than 40% of its total population. According to the 2011 Census of Russia, Belarusian ethnicity is made up of 43% of the population and 36% of the working population.HistoryBelarusian history dates back to antiquity, in the late Neolithic and the Neolithic era, when early farmers began to cultivate the soil.

The San Juan Islands are an archipelago in the Pacific Northwest of the United States between the U.S. state of Washington and Vancouver Island, British Columbia, Canada. The San Juan Islands are part of Washington state, and form the core of San Juan County.In the archipelago, four islands are accessible to vehicular and foot traffic via the Washington State Ferries system.HistoryArchaeologists use the term "Gulf of Georgia Culture Area" to refer to the San Juan and Gulf Islands, the whole of which shows many archaeological commonalities. The San Juan Islands were part of the traditional area of various peoples of the Coast Salish ethnolinguistic group.

Pope Leo VIII ( 915 – 1 March 965) was a Roman prelate who claimed the Holy See from 963 until 964 in opposition to John XII and Benedict V and again from 23 June 964 to his death. Today he is considered by the Catholic Church to have been an antipope during the first period and the legitimate pope during the second. An appointee of Holy Roman Emperor Otto I, Leo VIII's pontificate occurred after the period known as the Saeculum obscurum.Early lifeBorn in Rome in the region around the Clivus Argentarius, Leo came from an illustrious noble family.

Year 879 ( DCCCLXXIX ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) at 2:00 am. The name was used as the first day of each month, but in practice, it was not used until the Year of the Fourteenth Night, for which it was a common year from 1282. It is considered a leap year, but is not considered leap seconds. Diocese of St Andrews  is an English diocese with a total population of 8.6 million. It is the second largest diocese in the United Kingdom.

A county is a geographical region of a country used for administrative or other purposes in certain modern nations. The term is derived from the Old French   denoting a jurisdiction under the sovereignty of a count (earl) or a viscount. Literal equivalents in other languages, derived from the equivalent of "count", are now seldom used officially, including , , , , , , , and zhupa in Slavic languages; terms equivalent to English language administrative terms such as municipality, district, circuit and commune/community are now often instead used.When the Normans conquered England, they brought the term with them.

Casimir Jagiellon ( ; ; ; 3 October 1458 – 4 March 1484 ) was a prince of the Kingdom of Hungary who succeeded his older brother Peter as ruler of Hungary after the latter was captured by Habsburg Emperor Karl II in 1492.During the 1530s, Jagiellon was the leading opponent of the Hungarian Reformation and was one of the main opponents of the Habsburg Empire. He was killed in the Battle of Pest, near Vienna in 1534.The reign of Jagiellon begins on 3 October 1458, in which he succeeded his older brother Peter as regent in the absence of Peter's younger brother, Michael (1458–1495).

Barbecue or barbeque ( informally BBQ in the UK and US , barbie in Australia and braai in South Africa), is a popular form of food preparation and cooking that involves the co-application of meat with vegetables in a hot indirect fire.The name is a portmanteau of the words barbeque and cooking. The English word barbecue, in its modern form, was popularised in the late 19th and early 20th centuries by the Texas barbecue restaurant chain The Original Smokers. Barbara Walters was a former anchor, reporter, and entertainment journalist for ABC News and then for the network's evening news program, 20/20 (now ABC World News).

Courtesan , in modern usage , is a euphemism for a `` kept '' mistress or prostitute , particularly one who has sexual relations with an individual who is under a legal sentence of imprisonment for a term of years or more for the same crime as the person whose sex and/or place of residence the person in question is suspected to be (or who is the subject of such a suspicion), thus becoming a `` kept lady '' or ``kept man '' or ``kept woman''. In philosophy and other fields, the philosophy of religion is an interdisciplinary field that studies the religious beliefs and practices of various human cultures.

( ; `` The Master-Singers of Nuremberg '' ) , WWV 96 , is a music drama , or opera , by Ludwig van Beethoven (1821–1827) in two parts, as a one-act play in the major and minor keys. It was written as a memorial tribute to his beloved sister Anna Magdalena. The play was performed by the Nuremberg Philharmonic Society in 1894 and 1895 and by the Berlin Philharmonic Society in 1898 and 1899. Beethoven wrote it in May 1887 and performed it for a week in the Berlin City Opera House on 21 June 1887.

An ion thruster , ion drive , or ion engine is a form of electric propulsion used for spacecraft propulsion. They are used to accelerate spacecraft to a specific deltaV or higher, and to achieve speeds exceeding that of light. In contrast to rockets, they do not use a propellant to accelerate the spacecraft. For example, the Space Shuttle and the Delta II rocket use an oxidizer to accelerate a solid propellant. The International Space Station  (ISS) is a United States Government sponsored complex consisting of an Earth-orbiting orbital laboratory and supporting hardware and a permanently manned spacecraft.

Paul Leo Molitor ( born August 22 , 1956 ) , nicknamed `` Molly '' and `` The Ignitor '' (born July 20 , 1966) is an American writer, best known for his children's and adult novels. Molitor's childhood home was a boarding house, and he describes his childhood as one in which the house was the setting for his family's life together. His parents split when he was a young child, but they remained close.He graduated from the University of California, Santa Barbara, where he majored in English and received a graduate degree in fiction writing in 1995.

KFC (also known as Kentucky Fried Chicken) is an American fast food restaurant chain headquartered in Louisville, Kentucky that specializes in fried chicken. It is the world's second-largest restaurant chain (as measured by sales) after McDonald's, with 22,621 locations globally in 150 countries . The chain is a subsidiary of Yum! Brands, a restaurant company that also owns the Pizza Hut, Taco Bell and WingStreet chains.KFC was founded by Colonel Harland Sanders, an entrepreneur who began selling fried chicken from his roadside restaurant in Corbin, Kentucky during the Great Depression.

An anti-tank guided missile ( ATGM ) , anti-tank missile , anti-tank guided weapon ( ATGW ) or anti-armor guided missile ( AAAT ) is a weapon designed to destroy armoured targets. It is typically an explosive projectile with a warhead that is fired at a high speed, or a device that is mounted on a ship or vehicle and fires at low speeds to destroy enemy armour. Afghanistan (; ;  ; ) is an Islamic country in Central Asia located along the northern border of Central Asia, on the border of Afghanistan, Pakistan, Turkmenistan, and Uzbekistan.

Tajiks ( , Tājīk , Tājek ; ) are a Persian-speaking Iranian ethnic group native to Central Asia , living mainly in the former Soviet Union and Kazakhstan. The term refers to a specific ethnic group, which has lived there since at least the 13th century.HistoryTajiks originated in Afghanistan , and spread throughout the Middle East and Central Asia. Tajikistan , also known as Kyrgyzstan in Russian, Tajikstan in Russian, or Kyrgyzstan in Cyrillic, was a Soviet republic within Central Asia in the former Soviet Union (the successor state to the USSR) until it gained independence and became a republic of the Commonwealth of Independent States in 1995.

Twyla Tharp ( ; born July 1 , 1941 ) is an American dancer , choreographer , and author who is widely considered one of the most influential and popular dancers of the 20th century. As a member of the Tharp Brothers Ballet Company she performed with the company from the 1950s to the 1960s. In the 1960s and 1970s she became known as the "Dancing Queen", and was featured as one of the most famous and recognizable dancers of the era, appearing on a number of magazine covers and in a variety of films and television programs.

Gender is the range of characteristics pertaining to femininity and masculinity and differentiating between them . Depending on the context, the term can refer to the physical characteristics of female and male gender roles, such as genitalia or gender expression, the degree of comfort with one or both of the sexes (gender identity), and how one feels about various cultural or social issues related to these characteristics. Gender, as a cultural construct, has not existed since the emergence of human beings around 11,000 years ago, and is currently defined on a gender spectrum and in terms of sex-role social roles.

Henry Dunant (born Jean-Henri Dunant; 8 May 182830 October 1910), also known as Henri Dunant, was a Swiss humanitarian, businessman and social activist. He was the visionary, promoter and co-founder of the Red Cross. In 1901, he received the first Nobel Peace Prize together with Frédéric Passy, making Dunant the first Swiss Nobel laureate.During a business trip in 1859, Dunant was witness to the aftermath of the Battle of Solferino in modern-day Italy. He recorded his memories and experiences in the book A Memory of Solferino which inspired the creation of the International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC) in 1863.

Eastern Europe is the eastern region of Europe. There is no consistent definition of the precise area it covers, partly because the term has a wide range of geopolitical, geographical, ethnic, cultural, and socioeconomic connotations. Russia, located in Eastern Europe, is both the largest and most populous country of Europe, spanning roughly 40% of the continent's total landmass, with over 15% of its total population.According to the Center for Educational Technologies at Wheeling Jesuit University, there are "almost as many definitions of Eastern Europe as there are scholars of the region".

The First Book of Nephi: His Reign and Ministry , usually referred to as First Nephi or 1 Nephi, is the first book of the Book of Mormon and one of four books with the name Nephi. The original translation of the title did not include the word "first". First and Second were added to the titles of the Books of Nephi by Oliver Cowdery when preparing the book for printing. It is a first-person narrative by a prophet named Nephi, of events that began around 600 BC and recorded on the small plates of Nephi approximately 30 years later.

A knight 's tour is a sequence of moves of a knight on a chessboard such that the knight visits the same square as the king and the same square on the same row and column more than any other square, or more than any square on any adjacent row and column. A knight tour can be either diagonally or crosswise, and is often depicted in a diamond formation. The tour is usually a repetition of the first move of the first move, but it may also be different from the first move, or may have different moves of different length.

Westminster is an area of Central London , part of the wider City of Westminster.The area , which extends from Regent Street in the north to Tower Bridge in the south , is home to a number of embassies and international organisations, both governmental and private. Westminster is also the capital and largest city of England and the administrative centre of England, which is situated on the Thames estuary.London is the capital and the oldest city of England and the largest metropolitan city in the world. It has a population of approximately 6.2 million, and is the second-most populous city in England after New York .

In the history of cryptography, Typex (alternatively, Type X or TypeX) machines were British cipher machines used from 1937. It was an adaptation of the commercial German Enigma with a number of enhancements that greatly increased its security. The cipher machine (and its many revisions) was used until the mid-1950s when other more modern military encryption systems came into use.DescriptionLike Enigma, Typex was a rotor machine. Typex came in a number of variations, but all contained five rotors, as opposed to three or four in the Enigma.

Parsifal (WWV 111) is an opera in three acts by Richard Wagner with the libretto by the composer himself loosely based on the 13th-century Middle High German epic poem Parzival of the Minnesänger   Wolfram von Eschenbach, recounting the story of the Arthurian knight Parzival (Percival) and his quest for the Holy Grail.Wagner conceived the work in April 1857, but did not finish it until 25 years later. It was his last major work, and in composing it he took advantage of the particular acoustics of his Bayreuth Festspielhaus. Parsifal was first produced at the second Bayreuth Festival in 1882.

Warren Mitchell (born Warren Misell; 14 January 1926 – 14 November 2015) was a British  actor. He was a BAFTA TV Award winner and twice a Laurence Olivier Award winner.In the 1950s, Mitchell appeared on the radio programmes Educating Archie and Hancock's Half Hour. He also performed minor roles in several movies. In the 1960s, he rose to prominence in the role of bigoted cockney Alf Garnett in the BBC television sitcom Till Death Us Do Part (1965–75), created by Johnny Speight, which won him a Best TV Actor BAFTA in 1967.

Pope Gregory I (;  – 12 March 604), commonly known as Saint Gregory the Great, was the bishop of Rome from 3 September 590 to his death. He is known for instigating the first recorded large-scale mission from Rome, the Gregorian Mission, to convert the then-pagan Anglo-Saxons in England to Christianity. Gregory is also well known for his writings, which were more prolific than those of any of his predecessors as pope. The epithet Saint Gregory the Dialogist has been attached to him in Eastern Christianity because of his Dialogues.

Arabidopsis ( rockcress ) is a genus in the family Brassicaceae . They are small flowering plants related to cabbage (Brassica oleracea), which is native to Eurasia and Asia, and wild carrot (Daucus carota). It is the world's second-largest cultivated group of plant after rice. The genus includes over 500 species of flowering plants, which have been collected worldwide for thousands of years. The genus contains more than 500,000 species of herbs and medicinal plants and is the fourth largest group in the botanical world.Brassicadaceae is the only genus that can grow outdoors, and this is done by cross-breeding with related species.

The Permanent Court of Arbitration (PCA) is a non-UN intergovernmental organization located in The Hague, Netherlands. Unlike a judicial court in the traditional sense, the PCA provides services of arbitral tribunal to resolve disputes that arise out of international agreements between member states, international organizations or private parties. The cases span a range of legal issues involving territorial and maritime boundaries, sovereignty, human rights, international investment, and international and regional trade. The PCA is constituted through two separate multilateral conventions with a combined membership of 122 states.

Mosquitoes are members of a group of almost 3,600 species of small flies within the family Culicidae (from the Latin culex meaning "gnat"). The word "mosquito" (formed by mosca and diminutive -ito) is Spanish and Portuguese for "little fly". Mosquitoes have a slender segmented body, one pair of wings, one pair of halteres, three pairs of long hair-like legs, and elongated mouthparts.The mosquito life cycle consists of egg, larva, pupa, and adult stages. Eggs are laid on the water surface; they hatch into motile larvae that feed on aquatic algae and organic material.

Zooarchaeology ( sometimes incorrectly archaeozoology ) , also known as faunal analysis , is a branch of archaeology that studies and classifies the fossil remains of animals (including plants and fungi). Fossils can be of any organism and can include those of all types of living and extinct organisms. Faunal analysis is useful in reconstructing and comparing the evolutionary relationships among different taxa, and in evaluating the evolutionary status of species and subspecies. The Free Software Foundation is a nonprofit organization dedicated to promoting and protecting free software for use in any computer, digital or physical environment.

Year 1158 ( MCLVIII ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) in the Julian calendar, the Gregorian calendar used before 1582, and the Hebrew calendar (link will display the full calendar) used after 1582. Its length varies between 7½ days and 8 days. This year also falls on a Tuesday in the Muslim calendar, as does the year that follows. The year 1159 is also a common year, but is a Tuesday in the Julian calendar, as is the following year.

An inverse multiplexer (often abbreviated to inverse MUX or IMUX) allows a data stream to be broken into multiple lower data rate communication links. An inverse multiplexer differs from a demultiplexer because the multiple output streams from the former stay inter-related, whereas those from the latter are unrelated.
